      = \u2192 [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] (loan)\n| caps4          = 7\n| goals4         = 1\n| years5         = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs5         = \u2192 [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] (loan)\n| caps5          = 16\n| goals5         = 1\n| years6         = 2015\u20132018\n| clubs6         = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| caps6          = 18\n| goals6         = 0\n| years7         = 2016\n| clubs7         = \u2192 [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] (loan)\n| caps7          = 12\n| goals7         = 0\n| years8         = 2017\n| clubs8         = \u2192 [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] (loan)\n| caps8          = 17\n| goals8         = 5\n| years9         = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs9         = \u2192 [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] (loan)\n| caps9          = 29\n| goals9         = 3\n| years10        = 2018\u20132020\n| clubs10        = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n| caps10         = 54\n| goals10        = 9\n| years11        = 2020\u2013\n| clubs11        = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| caps11         = 8\n| goals11        = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2009\n| nationalteam1  = Scotland U15\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2009\u20132010\n| nationalteam2  = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 6\n| nationalgoals2 = 3\n| nationalyears3 = 2010\u20132012\n| nationalteam3  = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 15\n| nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2012\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national under-18 football team|Scotland U18]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2012\n| nationalteam5 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 10\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| nationalyears6 = 2012\n| nationalteam6 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 1\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| club-update = 21:09, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Matthew Kennedy''' (born 1 November 1994) is a [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], and represented Scotland at all youth international levels. He was sold to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in August 2012, and was loaned out to [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]], [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]], and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]], before being sold on to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in February 2015. Initially a first team regular at Cardiff, he was dropped in the 2015\u201316 season and joined [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on loan in January 2016, and then [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] on loan in January 2017; he helped Plymouth to achieve promotion out of [[EFL League Two]] at the end of the season. He joined [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on loan for the 2017\u201318 season.\n\nKennedy returned to Scottish football in July 2018, signing with [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]. He moved to Aberdeen in January 2020.\n\n==Career==\n===Kilmarnock===\nKennedy had the opportunity to join the [[youth system|youth academies]] of [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], but chose to join [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] as the club were closer to his home in [[South Ayrshire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/kilmarnock-s-kennedy-eyes-unlikely-outing-1-2173871/amp|title=Kilmarnock's Kennedy eyes unlikely outing|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref> and he felt played a style of football that suited him.<ref name=starlet>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Terry|title=Who is Cardiff City starlet Matthew Kennedy? The story of the boyhood Glasgow Rangers fan who signed from Everton|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-cardiff-city-starlet-matthew-8680086|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=Wales Online|date=20 February 2015}}</ref> On 19 November 2011, aged 17, Kennedy made his first team debut as a substitute in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] at [[Easter Road]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15704890.stm | title=Hibernian 1 \u2013 1 Kilmarnock | publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |work=BBC Sport | date=19 November 2011 | accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref> He started his first game for \"Killie\" in a 2\u20131 win over [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] at [[Rugby Park]] on 2 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kilmarnock 2 - 1 St Mirren|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16330995|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=2 January 2012}}</ref> He ended the [[2011\u201312 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2011\u201312]] campaign with 11 [[Scottish Premier League]] appearances. He played three games at the start of the [[2012\u201313 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2012\u201313]] season before leaving the club; manager [[Kenny Shiels]] expressed his concern that Kennedy had left Kilmarnock too soon and he had missed out on seeing Kennedy's \"proper development\" at the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kilmarnock boss concern over Matthew Kennedy's Everton switch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19463785|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=3 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Everton===\nOn 31 August 2012, the final day of the summer transfer window, Kennedy signed for English [[Premier League]] side [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] for a \"nominal fee\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19426773 | title=Everton: Matthew Kennedy secured from Kilmarnock |publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The fee was later revealed to be \u00a3225,000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prentice|first1=David|title=Everton FC: Teenage winger Matthew Kennedy says he's 'living the dream' after signing for Blues|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-fc-teenage-winger-matthew-3333987|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=Liverpool Echo|date=4 September 2012}}</ref> In a later interview he stated that \"I\u2019ve got nothing but praise for their [[Everton F.C. Reserves and Academy|academy]]. I don\u2019t think you could have a better youth set up. My coaches were [[David Unsworth]], [[Alan Stubbs]] and [[David Weir (Scottish footballer)|David Weir]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKay |first1=Gabriel |title=Matty Kennedy reflects on Everton apprenticeship after Aberdeen move |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/matty-kennedy-recalls-harsh-everton-21662370 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=dailyrecord |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 January 2014, Kennedy signed on loan for [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Everton Winger Joins Tranmere |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/kennedy-090114-1284458.aspx |work=Tranmere Rovers FC |date=9 January 2014}}</ref> Manager [[Ronnie Moore]] extended the loan spell for a further month after being impressed by his first six appearances at [[Prenton Park]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tranmere Extend Kennedy Loan |url=http://www.tranmererovers.co.uk/news/article/kennedy-100214-1351128.aspx |work=Tranmere Rovers FC |date=10 February 2014}}</ref> On 26 March 2014, Kennedy joined [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]], also of League One, on a youth loan until the end of the [[2013\u201314 Milton Keynes Dons F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dons swoop for Everton starlet |url=http://www.mkdons.com/news/article/dons-swoop-for-everton-starlet-1447908.aspx |work=Milton Keynes Dons FC |date=26 March 2014}}</ref> Manager [[Karl Robinson]] stated that Kennedy would bring \"pace, trickery and excitement\" to [[Stadium mk]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton's Matthew Kennedy joins MK Dons on loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26757713|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=26 March 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the [[English Football League]] for the \"Dons\" in a 2\u20132 draw at [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 26 April.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham 2 - 2 MK Dons|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27084357|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=26 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2014, Kennedy joined [[Scottish Championship]] side [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] on a six-month loan deal after being signed by his former Everton under-21 manager [[Alan Stubbs]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Winger Matthew Kennedy pens Hibernian loan deal|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/hibernian/winger-matthew-kennedy-pens-hibernian-loan-deal-1-3503926|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=8 August 2014}}</ref> He initially found himself on the bench at [[Easter Road]], though Stubbs was keen to extend the loan deal until the end of the [[2014\u201315 Hibernian F.C. season|2014\u201315]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hibs look to extend winger Matthew Kennedy's loan stay at Easter Road beyond January |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/hibs-look-extend-winger-matthew-4562898#sKF7Ra7SqJhz8Tbg.97|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=Daily Record|date=4 November 2014}}</ref> On 29 October, he scored his second senior goal to help secure a 3\u20133 draw with [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] in the [[Scottish League Cup]] quarter-finals, however he missed his penalty in the resulting shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hibernian 3 - 3 Dundee Utd|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29718350|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2014}}</ref> He said that he was \"devastated\" by his miss, which eliminated \"Hibs\" from the competition.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Forbes|first1=Craig|title=Matthew Kennedy wants to payback fans for pen miss |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/hibernian/matthew-kennedy-wants-to-payback-fans-for-pen-miss-1-3606001|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=15 November 2014}}</ref> He returned to [[Goodison Park]] on 5 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30685832 |title=Hibs' on-loan winger Matthew Kennedy returns to Everton |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cardiff City===\n[[File:Matty Kennedy.jpg|thumb|right|Kennedy playing for Cardiff City in 2015.]]\nOn 2 February 2015, Kennedy signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] on a three-and-a-half year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scottish U21 international links up permanently from Everton |url=http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/article/deadline-day-deal-kennedy-signs-2244873.aspx |work=Cardiff City FC |date=2 February 2015 |access-date=3 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923200555/http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/article/deadline-day-deal-kennedy-signs-2244873.aspx |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his full debut for the \"Bluebirds\" 15 days later in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at [[Cardiff City Stadium]], playing the full 90 minutes and producing a Man of the Match performance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Snapshot|url=http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/article/report-cardiff-1-1-blackburn-2277775.aspx|website=cardiffcityfc.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> He settled in well at the club, and was touted as one of manager [[Russell Slade]]'s best signings for the club.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Steve|title=Cardiff City signings rated: How have Russell Slade's super seven performed since their January arrivals?|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-city-signings-rated-how-8902341|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=Wales Online|date=23 March 2015}}</ref> He made a total of 14 league appearances in the second half of the [[2014\u201315 Cardiff City F.C. season|2014\u201315]] season.\n\nKennedy was described as a \"forgotten man\" after playing just one league game in the first half of the [[2015\u201316 Cardiff City F.C. season|2015\u201316]] season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Terry|title=Cardiff City's forgotten man Matthew Kennedy given chance to stake his claim for first team spot|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-citys-forgotten-man-matthew-10003351|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=Wales Online|date=7 September 2015}}</ref> On 25 January 2016, he joined League One side [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on a one-month loan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port Vale sign striker Robinson and Cardiff loan winger Kennedy|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35399530|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=25 January 2016}}</ref> He said that he was attracted to the \"Valiants\" by manager [[Rob Page]], who Cardiff coaches told him was the best man to bring out his best qualities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Matty Kennedy says Cardiff City recommended Vale and boss Rob Page|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Port-Vale-Matty-Kennedy-says-Cardiff-recommended/story-28599891-detail/story.html|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]|date=25 January 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He began his time at [[Vale Park]] in good form, and was hopeful of extending his stay further than the initial month.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port Vale: Cardiff City winger Matthew Kennedy eyeing loan extension|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35588255|accessdate=16 February 2016|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=16 February 2016}}</ref> After late negotiations, Cardiff agreed to extend the loan until 26 April.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baggaley|first1=Mike|title=Valiants clinch new deal for Cardiff winger Matty Kennedy|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Port-Vale-Valiants-clinch-new-deal-Cardiff-winger/story-28815987-detail/story.html|accessdate=27 February 2016|work=The Sentinel|date=26 February 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, he returned to Cardiff on 7 April after being demoted from the first eleven to a place on the bench.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Pete|title=Matty Kennedy recalled by Cardiff City|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Port-Vale-Blow-Vale-Matty-Kennedy-recalled/story-29069941-detail/story.html|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=The Sentinel|date=7 April 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Page said that \"to go from under-21s football to playing week-in, week-out, two games a week at League One level caught up with him\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Southcombe|first1=Matthew|title=Cardiff City winger Matthew Kennedy returns early from Port Vale loan spell as first team opportunities dry up|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-city-winger-matthew-kennedy-11153175|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=Wales Online|date=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2017, he joined [[EFL League Two]] club [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] on loan until the end of the [[2016\u201317 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Matty Kennedy leaves Cardiff City for Plymouth Argyle loan|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11705/10751370/matty-kennedy-leaves-cardiff-city-for-plymouth-argyle-loan|accessdate=1 February 2017|work=Sky Sports|date=31 January 2017}}</ref> Cardiff manager [[Neil Warnock]] predicted that Kennedy would \"set the league alight\" for the \"Pilgrims\", and his words were vindicated early on as Kennedy picked up two man of the match awards as he scored in three consecutive games \u2013 including an \"outstanding\" goal in a victory over [[West Country derby]] rivals [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] at [[Home Park]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Booth|first1=Dominic|title=Matty Kennedy is sparkling for Plymouth as Warnock proves prophetic|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/plymouth-argyle-fans-loving-matty-12626422|accessdate=3 April 2017|work=Wales Online|date=19 February 2017}}</ref> He went on to be nominated for the [[EFL League Two Player of the Month]] award for February.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Errington|first1=Chris|title=Argyle's Matt Kennedy up for League Two Player of the Month prize|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/plymouth-argyle-s-matt-kennedy-up-for-league-two-player-of-the-month-prize/story-30183206-detail/story.html|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=Plymouth Herald|date=7 March 2017|language=en}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He scored five goals in 17 games to help Argyle to win promotion as runners-up of League Two.<ref name=\"Errington\">{{cite news|last1=Errington|first1=Chris|title=Derek Adams aiming to make more history at promoted Argyle|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/derek-adams-aiming-to-make-more-history-at-promoted-plymouth-argyle/story-30329125-detail/story.html|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=Plymouth Herald|date=12 May 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514024752/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/derek-adams-aiming-to-make-more-history-at-promoted-plymouth-argyle/story-30329125-detail/story.html#|archive-date=14 May 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"2016/17\"/>\n\nOn 31 August 2017, Kennedy joined Cardiff teammate [[Stuart O'Keefe]] on loan at League One side [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] for the [[2017\u201318 Portsmouth F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41118500 |title=Cardiff sign Craig Bryson and Liam Feeney on loan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 August 2017|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> He had impressed \"Pompey\" manager [[Kenny Jackett]] playing against the club in the [[EFL Cup]] earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Booth|first1=Dominic|title=Cardiff City winger Matty Kennedy joins Portsmouth on loan|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/cardiff-city-winger-matty-kennedy-13557672|accessdate=1 September 2017|work=walesonline|date=31 August 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 3\u20131 defeat at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on 12 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41156400|title=Northampton 3-1 Portsmouth|publisher=BBC|date=12 September 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> After a good start to his time at [[Fratton Park]] he suffered a dip in form and ended up becoming a bit-part player, which assistant manager [[Joe Gallen]] blamed on Kennedy over-thinking his play.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rooney|first1=Will|title=Pompey winger told to get back to basics|url=https://www.portsmouth.co.uk/sport/football/pompey/pompey-winger-told-to-get-back-to-basics-1-8400644|accessdate=12 May 2018|work=Portsmouth News|date=3 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> At the end of the 2017\u201318 season, Kennedy was released by Cardiff upon the expiration of his contract on 30 June.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Cardiff City retained list: Who is staying and leaving | last = Booth | first = Dominic | work = Wales Online | date = 14 May 2018 | accessdate = 1 July 2018 | url = https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/cardiff-city-retained-list-players-14780106 }}</ref>\n\n===St Johnstone===\nOn 21 July 2018, Kennedy signed a two-year deal with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.perthstjohnstonefc.co.uk/news/post/winger-kennedy-joins-two-year-deal|title=Winger Kennedy joins on two-year-deal|publisher=St Johnstone F.C.|date=21 July 2018|accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref> Manager [[Tommy Wright (footballer, born 1963)|Tommy Wright]] said that it was a \"real coup for us\" to sign the winger.<ref>{{cite web |title=St Johnstone: Signing former Cardiff winger Matty Kennedy 'a coup' - Tommy Wright |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44911686 |accessdate=22 July 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 July 2018}}</ref> On 3 April 2019, he scored in a 2\u20130 win over [[Tayside derby]] rivals [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] at [[McDiarmid Park]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watt |first1=Martin |title=St Johnstone 2-0 Dundee: Callum Hendry & Matty Kennedy settle derby |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47715232 |accessdate=20 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport |date=3 April 2019}}</ref> He ended the [[2018\u201319 St Johnstone F.C. season|2018\u201319]] season with seven goals in 41 appearances as the \"Saints\" posted a seventh-place finish.\n\n===Aberdeen===\nKennedy signed a pre-contract agreement with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on 15 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51129910 |title=Matty Kennedy: St Johnstone midfielder signs Aberdeen pre-contract |website=BBC Sport |date=15 January 2020 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Nine days later he joined Aberdeen on a three-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51243146 |title=Matty Kennedy: St Johnstone winger joins Aberdeen after clubs agree early switch |first=Tyrone |last=Smith |website=BBC Sport |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref> The \"Dons\" were reported to have paid a transfer fee of \u00a375,000 plus add-ons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace |first1=Sean |title=Matty Kennedy 'can handle pressure' of helping to end Aberdeen's goal drought |url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/sport/football/aberdeen-fc/donsnews/042ex2801eea_story__8/ |accessdate=29 January 2020 |work=Evening Express |date=28 January 2020}}</ref> By the time the [[2019\u201320 Aberdeen F.C. season|2019\u201320]] season was halted due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland]], Kennedy had six goals (all for St Johnstone) and eight assists and said he was just starting to show his best form.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Owen |first1=Danny |title=6 goals, 8 assists; In-form attacker thanks Everton for unearthing his potential |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2020/03/10/6-goals-8-assists-in-form-attacker-thanks-everton-for-unearthing/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=HITC |date=10 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Panton |first1=Malcolm |title=Matty Kennedy Feature |url=https://www.afc.co.uk/2020/03/09/matty-kennedy-feature/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Aberdeen FC |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Scotland youth===\nKennedy has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-15 football team|under-15]], [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] level.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=823&playerID=69310&squadID=13 | title=Matthew Kennedy SFA Profile | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref> He was selected by [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] interim coach [[Ricky Sbragia]] to play [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal under-21]] at [[Est\u00e1dio do Bonfim]], [[Set\u00fabal]] on 14 November 2012; he came on for [[Callum Paterson]] 66 minutes into a 3\u20132 defeat, in what was his only under-21 cap.<ref>{{cite web|title=International Challenge Match|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=2855&matchID=123865|website=scottishfa.co.uk|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn September 2019, it was reported that Kennedy was due to switch his international allegiance to the country of his birth, [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]]. He was pictured training with the senior Northern Ireland squad ahead of a friendly with [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]].<ref name=\"born\">{{cite news |last1=Hanna |first1=Gareth |title=Who is Matty Kennedy? All you need to know about Scotland U21 international switching to Northern Ireland |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/who-is-matty-kennedy-all-you-need-to-know-about-scotland-u21-international-switching-to-northern-ireland-38469908.html |accessdate=6 September 2019 |work=Belfast Telegraph |date=5 September 2019}}</ref> He was called up to the Northern Ireland senior squad on 3 October.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2020 qualifiers: Jamal Lewis named in NI squad as Matthew Kennedy gets first call-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49923659 |accessdate=3 October 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAble to play on either wing, Kennedy was described by [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] manager [[Ronnie Moore]] as \"quick, [he] likes to take on defenders and [is someone] will create chances for his team-mates\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer window: Everton winger Matthew Kennedy joins Tranmere|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25674173|accessdate=26 January 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|7 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"2011/12\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58113|season=2011|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|11||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||11||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58113|season=2012|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n|Scottish Pr