"2019/20\">{{Soccerbase season|id=58113|season=2019|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n|Scottish Premiership\n|18||3||0||0||3||2||0||0||21||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!54!!9!!2!!0!!6!!3!!0!!0!!62!!12\n|-\n|[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Aberdeen F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"2019/20\"/>\n|Scottish Premiership\n|8||0||3||1||0||0||0||0||11||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!180!!18!!8!!1!!10!!4!!3!!0!!201!!23\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n;Plymouth Argyle\n*[[EFL League Two]] runner-up: [[2016\u201317 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"Errington\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Soccerway|matthew-kennedy/154189|Matty Kennedy}}\n*{{UEFA player|250022733|Matty Kennedy}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n\n{{Aberdeen F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennedy, Matty}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Ireland of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Association footballers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Kilmarnock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Milton Keynes Dons F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Plymouth Argyle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:David Weir\u2192David Weir (Scottish footballer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matty_Kennedy"}
{"title_page": "Immaculate Fools", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Immaculate Fools\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = De los sonidos de \u2018La movida\u2019 en recuerdo a Tierno Galv\u00e1n a la electr\u00f3nica m\u00e1s ecl\u00e9ctica - banda sonora de la v\u00edspera de San Isidro 11.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Immaculate Fools performance (2018)\n| origin              = [[Kent]], England \n| genre               = Pop\n| years_active        = 1984\u20131997, 2015\u2013\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], Continuum, [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dirty Ray]]\n* [[Weatherill and Lamb]]}}\n| website             = http://www.immaculatefools.com\n| current_members     = Kevin Weatherill [Vocals, Guitar, Harmonica]<br/>Linda Lamb [Vocals]<br/>Laura Solla G\u00f3mez [Guitar]<br/>Na\u00edma Acu\u00f1a [Drums]<br/>Paco Charl\u00edn [Bass]<br/>Alex Salgeiro [Keyboards]<br/>Helena 'Hels' Watt [Violin]\n| past_members        = Kevin Weatherill<br />Paul Weatherill<br />Andy Ross<br />Peter Ross<br />[[Barry Wickens]]<br />Paul Skidmore<br />Ian Devlin<br />Brian Betts<br />Nick Thomas<br />Alex Valentine<br />Adam Fuest<br />Phil Redfox Osullivan <br/>Christian Pattemore <br/>Phil Andrews\n}}\n'''Immaculate Fools''' were a pop group formed in 1984, who had their biggest success in 1985 with the single \"Immaculate Fools\",<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 268}}</ref> and continued until 1997, releasing six studio albums before splitting up. In 2015, Kevin Weatherill reformed the group with new members.\n\n==Formation, album history and tours==\nThe band was formed in [[Kent]], England by two sets of brothers: Kevin Weatherill (vocals, guitar) and Paul Weatherill (bass, vocals), and brothers Andy Ross (guitar) and Peter Ross (drums), the sons of saxophonist [[Ronnie Ross]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">Larkin, Colin (1995) ''The Guinness Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', Guinness Publishing, {{ISBN|0-85112-662-6}}</ref>\n\nThe band's single \"Immaculate Fools\" reached No. 51 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in January 1985.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> Their debut album, ''Hearts of Fortune'', reached No. 65 in the [[UK Albums Chart]] the same year.<ref name=\"CS\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ Immaculate Fools], Chart Stats</ref> The band toured Europe extensively, building a strong following in Spain, where they made several television appearances.<ref name=\"Larkin\" />\n\nIn 1987 the band's second album, ''Dumb Poet,'' was well received by critics (including a five-star review in ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'' magazine), although it did not repeat the first album's commercial success.<ref name=\"Larkin\" /> The album did, however, give the band a second charting single with \"Tragic Comedy.\"\n\nThe band underwent a major line-up change when the Ross brothers left, with [[Barry Wickens]] (violin), Brian Betts (guitar), Paul Skidmore (drums) and Ian Devlin (keyboards) joining for the ''Another Man's World'' album.<ref name=\"Larkin\" /> The band set up a recording studio in a farmhouse (Woodhouse) on the Welsh borders near Ludlow. For the band's final two albums, ''Woodhouse'' and ''Kiss and Punch'', the Weatherill brothers were joined by Wickens, Betts, and Nick Thomas (drums).<ref name=\"Larkin\" />\n\nThey continued to record music and occasionally tour until they formally split up in 1997.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==After the breakup==\nKevin Weatherill, who was not only the lead vocalist but also the main songwriter of the band, continues to record and tour both in the UK and Europe under the name [[Dirty Ray]]. In 2010 he worked with [[Miles Hunt]] (of the band [[Wonderstuff]]) and violinist [[Erica Nockalls]] to produce the album ''Big World for a Little Man''.\n\nAndy Ross went on to work with [[Basia Trzetrzelewska|Basia]], [[Howard Jones (musician)|Howard Jones]], [[Miguel Bos\u00e9]], and [[Tori Amos]].<ref>Gregory, Andy (2002) ''The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002'', Routledge, {{ISBN|1-85743-161-8}}</ref> In 2013 Andy Ross won an award at the [[Reel Earth Environmental Film Festival]] in New Zealand for his short film, Well Beyond Water, about the plight of drought affected farmers in New South Wales.\n\n==Reformation==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nIn December 2014, Kevin Weatherill announced on his website that Immaculate Fools were to reform in 2015, initially playing some gigs in Spain, Portugal and Italy, and then embarking on a UK tour. In February 2015, the band began recording a new album titled ''Turn the Whole World Down'', which was produced by Adam Fuest.\n\nThe reformed act toured Spain in 2015 with new members Linda Lamb (bass), Adam Fuest (guitar), Helen Watt (violin), Phil Redfox O'Sullivan (drums), and Alex Valentine (keyboards). For the Spring Tour of Spain in 2016, Immaculate Fools were joined by touring members Christian Pattemore and Phil Andrews of Thieves of Time on bass. Between October 2015 and June 2016 Immaculate Fools performed 26 shows in Spain. \n\nIn the summer of 2016, following Weatherill's relocation to Spain, the logistics of continuing the band in its current form became problematic. Adam Fuest and Kevin Weatherill parted company and Weatherill formed a new seven piece version of the band featuring local Spanish and UK musicians and continues to perform in Spain. In the spring of 2017, Weatherill released an album of new material under the name Immaculate Fools, titled ''Keep the Blade Sharp'' and began touring Spain to promote it. \n\nKevin Weatherill also continues to perform under the name Dirty Ray with Paco Charl\u00edn and Na\u00edma Acu\u00f1a.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Hearts of Fortune'' (1985) [[Polygram]] ([[UK Albums Chart|UK]] #65)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n*''Dumb Poet'' (1987) [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n*''Another Man's World'' (1990) [[CBS]]/[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*''The Toy Shop'' (1992) Continuum\n*''Woodhouse'' (1995) [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n*''Kiss and Punch'' (1996) Cooking Vinyl\n*''Turn the Whole World Down'' (2015) [[bandcamp]]\n*''Keep the Blade Sharp'' (2017)\n\n===Compilation albums===\n*''Smart Music for Smart People'' (1988) BNM\n*''The Best of Immaculate Fools'' (1998)\n*''No Gods No Masters'' (1998) Recall\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Nothing Means Nothing\" (1984) A&M\n*\"Immaculate Fools\" (1984) A&M ([[UK Singles Chart|UK]] #51)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n*\"Save It\" (1985) A&M\n*\"Tragic Comedy\" (1987) A&M (UK #76)<ref name=\"CS\" />\n*\"Wish You Were Here\" (1987) A&M\n*\"Falling Apart Together\" (1990) Epic\n*\"Sad\" (1990) CBS\n*\"Prince\" (1990) CBS/Epic\n*\"Heaven Down Here\" (1992) Continuum\n*\"Stand Down\" (1992) Continuum\n*\"Kiss and Punch\" (1996) Cooking Vinyl\n*\"Blanket\" (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3138439}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Immaculate Fools\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = De los sonidos de \u2018La movida\u2019 en recuerdo a Tierno Galv\u00e1n a la electr\u00f3nica m\u00e1s ecl\u00e9ctica - banda sonora de la v\u00edspera de San Isidro 11.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Immaculate Fools performance (2018)\n| origin              = [[Kent]], England \n| genre               = Pop\n| years_active        = 1984\u20131997, 2015\u2013\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], Continuum, [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dirty Ray]]\n* [[Weatherill and Lamb]]}}\n| website             = http://www.immaculatefools.com\n| current_members     = Kevin Weatherill [Vocals, Guitar, Harmonica]<br/>Linda Lamb [Vocals]<br/>Laura Solla G\u00f3mez [Guitar]<br/>Na\u00edma Acu\u00f1a [Drums]<br/>Paco Charl\u00edn [Bass]<br/>Alex Salgeiro [Keyboards]<br/>Helena 'Hels' Watt [Violin]\n| past_members        = Kevin Weatherill<br />Paul Weatherill<br />Andy Ross<br />Peter Ross<br />[[Barry Wickens]]<br />Paul Skidmore<br />Ian Devlin<br />Brian Betts<br />Nick Thomas<br />Alex Valentine<br />Adam Fuest<br />Phil Redfox Osullivan <br/>Christian Pattemore <br/>Phil Andrews\n}}\n'''Immaculate Fools''' were a pop group formed in 1984, who had their biggest success in 1985 with the single \"Immaculate Fools\",<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 268}}</ref> and continued until 1997, releasing six studio albums before splitting up. In 2015, Kevin Weatherill reformed the group with new members.\n\n==Formation, album history and tours==\nThe band was formed in [[Kent]], England by two sets of brothers: Kevin Weatherill (vocals, guitar) and Paul Weatherill (bass, vocals), and brothers Andy Ross (guitar) and Peter Ross (drums), the sons of saxophonist [[Ronnie Ross]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">Larkin, Colin (1995) ''The Guinness Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', Guinness Publishing, {{ISBN|0-85112-662-6}}</ref>\n\nThe band's single \"Immaculate Fools\" reached No. 51 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in January 1985.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> Their debut album, ''Hearts of Fortune'', reached No. 65 in the [[UK Albums Chart]] the same year.<ref name=\"CS\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ Immaculate Fools], Chart Stats</ref> The band toured Europe extensively, building a strong following in Spain, where they made several television appearances.<ref name=\"Larkin\" />\n\nIn 1987 the band's second album, ''Dumb Poet,'' was well received by critics (including a five-star review in ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'' magazine), although it did not repeat the first album's commercial success.<ref name=\"Larkin\" /> The album did, however, give the band a second charting single with \"Tragic Comedy.\"\n\nThe band underwent a major line-up change when the Ross brothers left, with [[Barry Wickens]] (violin), Brian Betts (guitar), Paul Skidmore (drums) and Ian Devlin (keyboards) joining for the ''Another Man's World'' album.<ref name=\"Larkin\" /> The band set up a recording studio in a farmhouse (Woodhouse) on the Welsh borders near Ludlow. For the band's final two albums, ''Woodhouse'' and ''Kiss and Punch'', the Weatherill brothers were joined by Wickens, Betts, and Nick Thomas (drums).<ref name=\"Larkin\" />\n\nThey continued to record music and occasionally tour until they formally split up in 1997.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==After the breakup==\nKevin Weatherill, who was not only the lead vocalist but also the main songwriter of the band, continues to record and tour both in the UK and Europe under the name [[Dirty Ray]]. In 2010 he worked with [[Miles Hunt]] (of the band [[Wonderstuff]]) and violinist [[Erica Nockalls]] to produce the album ''Big World for a Little Man''.\n\nAndy Ross went on to work with [[Basia Trzetrzelewska|Basia]], [[Howard Jones (musician)|Howard Jones]], [[Miguel Bos\u00e9]], and [[Tori Amos]].<ref>Gregory, Andy (2002) ''The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002'', Routledge, {{ISBN|1-85743-161-8}}</ref> In 2013 Andy Ross won an award at the [[Reel Earth Environmental Film Festival]] in New Zealand for his short film, Well Beyond Water, about the plight of drought affected farmers in New South Wales.\n\n==Reformation==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nIn December 2014, Kevin Weatherill announced on his website that Immaculate Fools were to reform in 2015, initially playing some gigs in Spain, Portugal and Italy, and then embarking on a UK tour. In February 2015, the band began recording a new album titled ''Turn the Whole World Down'', which was produced by Adam Fuest.\n\nThe reformed act toured Spain in 2015 with new members Linda Lamb (bass), Adam Fuest (guitar), Helen Watt (violin), Phil Redfox O'Sullivan (drums), and Alex Valentine (keyboards). For the Spring Tour of Spain in 2016, Immaculate Fools were joined by touring members Christian Pattemore and Phil Andrews of Thieves of Time on bass. Between October 2015 and June 2016 Immaculate Fools performed 26 shows in Spain. \n\nIn the summer of 2016, following Weatherill's relocation to Spain, the logistics of continuing the band in its current form became problematic. Adam Fuest and Kevin Weatherill parted company and Weatherill formed a new seven piece version of the band featuring local Spanish and UK musicians and continues to perform in Spain. In the spring of 2017, Weatherill released an album of new material under the name Immaculate Fools, titled ''Keep the Blade Sharp'' and began touring Spain to promote it. \n\nKevin Weatherill also continues to perform under the name Dirty Ray with Paco Charl\u00edn and Na\u00edma Acu\u00f1a.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Hearts of Fortune'' (1985) [[Polygram]] ([[UK Albums Chart|UK]] #65)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n*''Dumb Poet'' (1987) [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n*''Another Man's World'' (1990) [[CBS]]/[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n*''The Toy Shop'' (1992) Continuum\n*''Woodhouse'' (1995) [[Cooking Vinyl]]\n*''Kiss and Punch'' (1996) Cooking Vinyl\n*''Turn the Whole World Down'' (2015) [[bandcamp]]\n*''Keep the Blade Sharp'' (2017)\n\n===Compilation albums===\n*''Smart Music for Smart People'' (1988) BNM\n*''The Best of Immaculate Fools'' (1998)\n*''No Gods No Masters'' (1998) Recall\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Nothing Means Nothing\" (1984) A&M\n*\"Immaculate Fools\" (1984) A&M ([[UK Singles Chart|UK]] #51)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n*\"Save It\" (1985) A&M\n*\"Tragic Comedy\" (1987) A&M (UK ##76)<ref name=\"CS\" />\n*\"Wish You Were Here\" (1987) A&M\n*\"Falling Apart Together\" (1990) Epic\n*\"Sad\" (1990) CBS\n*\"Prince\" (1990) CBS/Epic\n*\"Heaven Down Here\" (1992) Continuum\n*\"Stand Down\" (1992) Continuum\n*\"Kiss and Punch\" (1996) Cooking Vinyl\n*\"Blanket\" (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3138439}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n", "name_user": "Jonclay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immaculate_Fools"}
{"title_page": "Erligou station", "text_new": "{{short description|future Beijing Subway interchange station}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Erligou\n| native_name      = \u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\n| native_name_lang = zh-Hans\n| symbol_location  = beijing\n| symbol           = subway\n| symbol_location2 = \n| symbol2          = \n| symbol_location3 = \n| symbol3          = \n| symbol_location4 = \n| symbol4          = \n| image            = Erligou Station and Xinjiang Plaza (20160909150108).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The construction site in September 2016\n| mlanguage        = <!-- Template:Infobox Chinese/Chinese -->\n| other_name       = \n| address = Chegongzhuang West Road / Chegongzhuang Street and [[:zh:\u4e09\u91cc\u6cb3\u8def|Sanlihe Road]]\n| borough          = [[Haidian District]] / [[Xicheng District]] border, [[Beijing]]\n| country = China\n| map_type = Beijing\n| map_caption = Location in central Beijing\n| map_size = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|39.931025|116.327294|format=dms|type:railwaystation_region:CN-11_source:Gaode|display=inline,title}}\n| operator         = [[Beijing Mass Transit Railway Operation Corporation Limited]]<br/>[[MTR Corporation#Beijing|Beijing MTR Metro Line 16 Corp. Ltd.]]\n| line             = {{rail color box|system=BJS|line=6|inline=yes}} (not opened)<br/>{{rail color box|system=BJS|line=16|inline=yes}} (under construction)\n| platforms        =  <!-- Note that island platforms each count as *two* platforms and not one \u2013 check the station layout; remove this comment afterwards -->\n| connections      = \n| structure        = \n| disabled         = \n| code             = \n| opened           = \n| closed           = \n| former           = \n| passengers       = \n| pass_year        = \n| services         = <!--{{s-rail|title=BJS}}\n{{s-line|system=BJS|line=6|previous=Baishiqiao South|next=Chegongzhuang West}}-->\n}}\n\n'''Erligou station''' ({{zh|s=\u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\u7ad9 |t=\u4e8c\u91cc\u6e9d\u7ad9 |p=\u00c8rl\u01d0g\u014du Zh\u00e0n}}) is a [[metro station|station]] under construction on [[Line 6, Beijing Subway|Line 6]] and [[Line 16, Beijing Subway|Line 16]] of the [[Beijing Subway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jtcx.beijing.cn/bus/dtcxxx/n214103785.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5730\u94c16\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u6cbf\u7ebf\u7ad9\u540d\u786e\u5b9a |publisher=[[Beijing Daily]] |date=2010-11-12 |accessdate=2013-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224103957/http://jtcx.beijing.cn/bus/dtcxxx/n214103785.shtml |archivedate=2013-12-24 }}</ref> This station did not enter into operation along with Line 6 Phase I on December 30, 2012. Rather it will open when the construction of Line 16 is finished.  The platform for Line 16 will be built above the Line 6 platform.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-hans |url=http://www.bjghw.gov.cn/web/dtfazs16/jtfa.html |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c116\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u7ad9\u8bbe\u8ba1\u65b9\u6848\u5c55\u793a |date=2013-04-25 |access-date=2014-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007200700/http://www.bjghw.gov.cn/web/dtfazs16/jtfa.html |archive-date=2013-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe station will be located at the intersection of the north-south [[:zh:\u4e09\u91cc\u6cb3\u8def|Sanlihe Road]] with the east-west thoroughfare known as Chegongzhuang West Road ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8f66\u516c\u5e84\u897f\u8def}}) to the west of Sanlihe Road and Chegongzhuang Street ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8f66\u516c\u5e84\u5927\u8857}}) to the east.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.163.com/12/0209/02/7PPOGBJ700014AED.html |script-title=zh:6\u53f7\u7ebf16\u53f7\u7ebf\u589e\u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\u6362\u4e58\u7ad9 |publisher=[[163.com]] news |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727085057/http://news.163.com/12/0209/02/7PPOGBJ700014AED.html |archive-date=2018-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--{{Beijing Subway Station\n|line6=yes\n|line16=yes\n}}-->\n\n[[Category:Beijing Subway stations in Haidian District]]\n[[Category:Beijing Subway stations in Xicheng District]]\n[[Category:Railway stations under construction in China]]\n\n{{Beijing-Subway-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|future Beijing Subway interchange station}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Erligou\n| native_name      = \u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\n| native_name_lang = zh-Hans\n| symbol_location  = beijing\n| symbol           = subway\n| symbol_location2 = \n| symbol2          = \n| symbol_location3 = \n| symbol3          = \n| symbol_location4 = \n| symbol4          = \n| image            = Erligou Station and Xinjiang Plaza (20160909150108).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = The construction site in September 2016\n| mlanguage        = <!-- Template:Infobox Chinese/Chinese -->\n| other_name       = \n| address = Chegongzhuang West Road / Chegongzhuang Street and [[:zh:\u4e09\u91cc\u6cb3\u8def|Sanlihe Road]]\n| borough          = [[Haidian District]] / [[Xicheng District]] border, [[Beijing]]\n| country = China\n| map_type = Beijing\n| map_caption = Location in central Beijing\n| map_size = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|39.931025|116.327294|format=dms|type:railwaystation_region:CN-11_source:Gaode|display=inline,title}}\n| operator         = [[Beijing Mass Transit Railway Operation Corporation Limited]]</br>[[MTR Corporation#Beijing|Beijing MTR Metro Line 16 Corp. Ltd.]]\n| line             = {{rail color box|system=BJS|line=6|inline=yes}} (not opened)</br>{{rail color box|system=BJS|line=16|inline=yes}} (under construction)\n| platforms        =  <!-- Note that island platforms each count as *two* platforms and not one \u2013 check the station layout; remove this comment afterwards -->\n| connections      = \n| structure        = \n| disabled         = \n| code             = \n| opened           = \n| closed           = \n| former           = \n| passengers       = \n| pass_year        = \n| services         = <!--{{s-rail|title=BJS}}\n{{s-line|system=BJS|line=6|previous=Baishiqiao South|next=Chegongzhuang West}}-->\n}}\n\n'''Erligou station''' ({{zh|s=\u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\u7ad9 |t=\u4e8c\u91cc\u6e9d\u7ad9 |p=\u00c8rl\u01d0g\u014du Zh\u00e0n}}) is a [[metro station|station]] under construction on [[Line 6, Beijing Subway|Line 6]] and [[Line 16, Beijing Subway|Line 16]] of the [[Beijing Subway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jtcx.beijing.cn/bus/dtcxxx/n214103785.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5730\u94c16\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e00\u671f\u6cbf\u7ebf\u7ad9\u540d\u786e\u5b9a |publisher=[[Beijing Daily]] |date=2010-11-12 |accessdate=2013-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224103957/http://jtcx.beijing.cn/bus/dtcxxx/n214103785.shtml |archivedate=2013-12-24 }}</ref> This station did not enter into operation along with Line 6 Phase I on December 30, 2012. Rather it will open when the construction of Line 16 is finished.  The platform for Line 16 will be built above the Line 6 platform.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-hans |url=http://www.bjghw.gov.cn/web/dtfazs16/jtfa.html |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c116\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u7ad9\u8bbe\u8ba1\u65b9\u6848\u5c55\u793a |date=2013-04-25 |access-date=2014-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007200700/http://www.bjghw.gov.cn/web/dtfazs16/jtfa.html |archive-date=2013-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe station will be located at the intersection of the north-south [[:zh:\u4e09\u91cc\u6cb3\u8def|Sanlihe Road]] with the east-west thoroughfare known as Chegongzhuang West Road ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8f66\u516c\u5e84\u897f\u8def}}) to the west of Sanlihe Road and Chegongzhuang Street ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8f66\u516c\u5e84\u5927\u8857}}) to the east.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.163.com/12/0209/02/7PPOGBJ700014AED.html |script-title=zh:6\u53f7\u7ebf16\u53f7\u7ebf\u589e\u4e8c\u91cc\u6c9f\u6362\u4e58\u7ad9 |publisher=[[163.com]] news |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727085057/http://news.163.com/12/0209/02/7PPOGBJ700014AED.html |archive-date=2018-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--{{Beijing Subway Station\n|line6=yes\n|line16=yes\n}}-->\n\n[[Category:Beijing Subway stations in Haidian District]]\n[[Category:Beijing Subway stations in Xicheng District]]\n[[Category:Railway stations under construction in China]]\n\n{{Beijing-Subway-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Tag with incorrect syntax)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erligou_station"}
{"title_page": "History of the Wales national football team (1876\u20131976)", "text_new": "[[File:Wales national team 1900.jpg|thumb|upright|260px|The Wales national team in 1900]]\nThe [[Wales national football team]] is the third oldest international [[association football]] team having played its first fixture in March 1876, four years after [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]] had contested the first international match. The team played annual fixtures against Scotland, England, and later [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] and these fixtures were eventually organised into the [[British Home Championship]], an annual competition between the [[Home Nations]]. Wales did not win its first championship until the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1906\u201307 edition]] of the competition and the triumph remained the nation's only title before the First World War. Wales improved considerably in the post-war period, and claimed three titles during the 1920s, although the team was often hindered by the reluctance of [[English Football League|Football League]] clubs to release its players for international duty. The situation was so grave that, in the early 1930s, Wales was forced to select a team of lower league and amateur players in a side that became known as \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\", in reference to captain [[Fred Keenor]] and the relative obscurity of his teammates.\n\nWhen able to call upon its strongest side, Wales enjoyed its most successful period in the British Home Championship, winning four titles in the six years before the Second World War. As competitive football resumed after the war, Wales began facing opponents from further afield and played matches against numerous other European nations for the first time. The side also began competing in qualification groups for the [[FIFA World Cup]]. After failing to qualify for the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]] editions, Wales qualified for its first World Cup in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]] after defeating [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a play-off match. During the tournament, the side progressed from its group under manager [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] before being defeated by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-final.\n\nThe side suffered a decline in the 1960s as the 1958 World Cup generation gradually retired. [[Dave Bowen]] replaced Murphy and managed the team for a decade between 1964 and 1974 but enjoyed little success, failing to qualify for a World Cup or the inaugural editions of the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] (later known as the European Championships). Bowen left the role in 1974, having turned down the chance to take the position full-time. He was replaced by Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]] who led the side to the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 1976]] in its centenary year, before being defeated by [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].{{#tag:ref|For the 1976 tournament, quarter-finals were played as a two-legged, home and away tie with the finals hosting only the semi-finals and beyond.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\"/>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Formation and early matches==\n[[File:Wales V Scotland 3386999.tif|thumb|A newspaper report of Wales first competitive match against Scotland in 1876]]\nThe [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first]] official international [[association football]] match was held in November 1872 between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ |title=The first international football match |publisher=BBC |last=Mitchell |first=Paul |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> Four years later, G. A. Clay-Thomas, a Welshman living in London, placed adverts in sports magazines ''[[The Field (magazine)|The Field]]'' and ''[[Bell's Life in London|Bell's Life]]'' proposing that a Welsh side be raised for a match against either Scotland or Ireland in [[rugby union|rugby]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853930/3853938/76/Clay |title=Football |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=8 |date=18 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> [[Llewelyn Kenrick]], a solicitor who had helped to found [[Druids F.C.]] in North Wales, pushed ahead with plans for a football match and accepted an invitation to play the Scottish national side. He helped establish the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW) in February 1876 to finalise arrangements for the forthcoming match,<ref name=\"Challenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/index.htm#y1876|title=1876 Kenrick's Challenge|work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> being appointed its first secretary.<ref>{{harvnb|Lile|Farmer|1984|p=196}}</ref> To qualify for selection, players were required to be Welsh or to have resided in the country for at least three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3386960/3386966/102/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=The Cardiff Times |p=6 |date=4 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Kenrick was criticised by some in South Wales for failing to notify players in the region of the forthcoming match, favouring to publish notices in London-based journals.<ref name=\"stead1013\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=10\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=120}}</ref> Unperturbed, he pushed forward with his plans and trial matches were held to find suitable players for the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853883/3853888/16/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=5 |date=12 February 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1876 Scotland v Wales football match|first Wales international football match]] was held on 2 March 1876 at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]] with the side wearing white shirts, featuring the [[Prince of Wales's feathers]], and black shorts.<ref name=\"stead1013\"/> The Welsh side were outclassed by their more experienced opponents, suffering a 4\u20130 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/wales-v-scotland-legendary-clashes-2021031 |title=Wales v Scotland: Legendary clashes |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Beech |first=Richard |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> A second fixture between the two sides was arranged for the following year and the [[Racecourse Ground]] in [[Wrexham]] became the venue for [[Wales national football team home stadium|Wales' first home international]].<ref name=\"dprecord\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |title=Is the Racecourse the world's oldest international venue? |newspaper=Daily Post |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925141407/https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Welsh side fell to a 2\u20130 defeat in the match. Wales returned to Scotland in 1878 but a fixture clash with the final of the [[Welsh Cup]] between Druids and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] led many players to refuse to travel. Such was the desperation to find willing players, the secretary of the [[Scottish Football Association]] travelled to Wales and visited the homes of players in an attempt to raise a side. A squad was eventually assembled but, having travelled overnight to Glasgow and containing many players who were not of sufficient standard, the side suffered a 9\u20130 defeat. The result remains Wales' worst defeat in international football.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, Wales and [[England national football team|England]] met for the first time in international football at a snow-covered [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]] in [[South London]]. The poor weather conditions resulted in the match being shortened to 60 minutes and the relatively unknown status of the Welsh side led to a low turnout of spectators; newspaper reports estimate the crowd was in the low hundreds with some even stating less than 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1878-79/M0008Wal1879.html |title=England 2\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RcfKAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=England+Wales+1879+snow+football&source=bl&ots=Cdw8QFMIi4&sig=ACfU3U1mF0MrVD9Z2p2ddF5DyEeI1JsjRQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgs6mTibXnAhXhQxUIHeT6BbgQ6AEwFnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=England%20Wales%201879%20snow%20football&f=false |title=The Victorian Football Miscellany |p=79 |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Superelastic |year=2013 |isbn=9780956227058}}</ref> During the match, [[William Davies (footballer, born 1855)|William Davies]] scored Wales' first international goal but his side were defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1877_1879.htm |title=The Story of Welsh Football 1877\u20131879 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The standard of the Welsh side was slowly improving and the side nearly held the visiting English side in March 1880. Having trailed 3\u20130, the Welsh side scored twice in the final ten minutes through [[William Roberts (footballer, born 1859)|William Roberts]] and [[John Roberts (footballer, born 1857)|John Roberts]] but were unable to equalise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1879-80/M0011Wal1880.html |title=Wales 2\u20134 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> William Roberts also scored Wales' goal against Scotland two weeks later in a 5\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=30}}</ref> Wales travelled to [[Alexandra Meadows]] in [[Blackburn]] the following year to play England. [[John Vaughan (footballer, born 1856)|John Vaughan]] scored the only goal of the game as Wales won its first international football match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4478237/4478241/90/Wales%20football |title=England V Wales |newspaper=Western Mail |p=4 |date=28 February 1881 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref><ref name=\"wcbc1880\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1880_1914.htm|title=The Story of Welsh Football 1880\u20131914 ||work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] were the final [[Home Nations|Home Nation]] to establish an international football team, playing its first fixture in February 1882 against England. Having suffered a 13\u20130 defeat against the English,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0014Ire1882.html |title=Ireland 0\u201313 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> the Irish side travelled to the Racecourse Ground to meet Wales for the first time. The more experienced Welsh side also proved too strong for the Irish, with [[John Price (footballer, born 1854)|John Price]] becoming the first [[List of Wales national football team hat-tricks|Welshman to score a hat-trick in international football]] during a 7\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tinyurl.gale.com/tinyurl/CXDsd2 |url-access=subscription |title=Wales V Ireland |newspaper=The Times |p=10 |date=27 February 1882 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Buoyed by their win, the Welsh side met England a month later and recorded a second victory over their neighbours. England had taken a 2\u20131 lead but were reduced to ten men when [[Charles Bambridge]] suffered a shoulder injury.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=31}}</ref> Wales pulled the score back to 3\u20133 before scoring twice in the final three minutes to claim a 5\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0016Wal1882.html |title=Wales 5\u20133 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Start of the British International Championship==\n\nWith all of the Home Nations competing regularly, the decision was taken to introduce a competitive tournament between the sides and the [[British Home Championship|British International Championship]] (later to become better known as the British Home Championship) was created in 1884.<ref name=\"stead3234\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=32\u201334}}</ref> The [[1883\u201384 British Home Championship|inaugural edition of the tournament]] was won by Scotland which won all three of its ties. Having defeated Ireland 6\u20130 in its opening match, Wales went on to finish third after suffering successive defeats to England and Scotland.<ref name=\"bhc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1884-99.html#1884 |title=British Home Championship 1884\u20131899 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> The early stages of the competition continued on the same lines; England and Scotland competed for the title, while Wales would finish third by defeating Ireland. In the first three years of competition, Wales' only points other than in matches against Ireland was a 1\u20131 draw with England in the [[1884\u201385 British Home Championship|1884\u201385 tournament]].<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> In the [[1886\u201387 British Home Championship|1886\u201387 edition]], Wales finished bottom of the competition for the first time after losing all three of its matches, including a 4\u20131 defeat to Ireland in the nation's first victory in international football. Wales had struggled to raise a team for the match and included Wrexham defender [[Bob Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|Bob Roberts]] playing as the goalkeeper. FAW secretary [[Alexander Hunter (footballer)|Alexander Hunter]] also stepped in when [[Humphrey Jones]] withdrew late.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> Hunter had never played football at such a level and his performance was described as \"glaringly deficient\".<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=93}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wales national team 1887.jpg|thumb|upright|240px|The Welsh national side in 1887]]\nIn a reversal of the previous year's events, the ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' claimed a weakened Ireland team travelled to Wales for the [[1887\u201388 British Home Championship]] and went on to lose the match 11\u20130,<ref name=\"wcbc1880\"/> although there were only four debutants in the team on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2010/11/017-3-march-1888.html?m=1 |title=Wales 11\u20130 Ireland |publisher=Northern Ireland Footballing Great |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> The scoreline remains a record victory for Wales. [[Jack Doughty]] scored four of the goals. Such was the one-sided nature of the game that three Welsh players left the field before the match ended to ensure they were on time for their train home.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> 5\u20131 defeats to both England and Scotland however ensured another third-place finish for Wales.<ref name=\"bhc\"/>\n\nWales avoided defeat in a fixture against Scotland for the first time with a goalless draw in the [[1888\u201389 British Home Championship]], simultaneously recording a first clean sheet against the Scots. The feat was achieved despite local amateur [[Alf Pugh]] starting in goal for Wales after the original selection, [[James Trainer]], failed to arrive at the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3670619/3670622/93/Wales%20football |title=Scotland vs Wales Association |newspaper=South Wales Daily News |p=3 |date=16 April 1889 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Pugh played the first 30 minutes before Wrexham's [[Sam Gillam]] arrived and took his place,<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> thus becoming the first substitution ever used in international football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales 0 Scotland 0|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/games/18890415.html|publisher=londonhearts.com|accessdate=16 December 2019|date=15 April 1889}}</ref> The following year, Wales played a home fixture outside the nation for the first time when a meeting with Ireland was held in [[Shrewsbury]] in an attempt to draw a large crowd. Wales won the match 5\u20132.<ref name=\"stead4041\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=40\u201341}}</ref> By the early 1890s, with the domestic game thriving in England, Wales was struggling to get players released for international fixtures, particularly for away matches against Ireland which required a three-day absence from a player's club due to ferry travel. As a result, Wales finished bottom of the British Home Championship five times during the decade, including three consecutive seasons between 1891 and 1893.<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4041\"/> Wales did record its highest placed finish to date in 1895 by finishing as runners-up to England after drawing all three of its fixtures, inspired by the likes of James Trainer, [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] and a debuting [[Billy Meredith]].<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4748\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\nWales continued its good form at the start of the [[1895\u201396 British Home Championship]] by thrashing Ireland 6\u20130 with both Meredith and Lewis scoring [[hat-trick|braces]]. The team's optimism was short-lived however when they suffered a crushing 9\u20131 defeat to England in their following match,<ref name=\"stead4748\"/> with [[Steve Bloomer]] scoring five of his side's goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/bloomer-intlg.html |title=Stephen Bloomer \u2013 International Goals |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Klukowski |first=Tomasz |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Wales would finish the 20th century by losing nine of its final ten matches, only avoiding defeat in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland in March 1897. The difficulties in calling up players from English teams became so pronounced that the FAW put forward a motion that national teams be granted the right to overrule clubs on player selection, although this was rejected. An approach to the English governing body, [[The Football Association]], also fell on deaf ears.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=51}}</ref>\n\n==New century==\n[[File:Billymeredith.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Billy Meredith]] made his debut for Wales in 1895]]\nThe [[1899\u20131900 British Home Championship]] revived hope in the side as Wales finished as runners-up to Scotland, led largely by the goals of Meredith and [[Tom Parry (footballer)|Tom Parry]]. Although results were still disappointing, the standard of the Welsh side was deemed to be improving rapidly as margins of defeat became smaller and several defeats to the English and Scottish sides between 1902 and 1905 were deemed unlucky based on the run of play.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=66\u201367}}</ref> The side also avoided defeat in an away fixture against the Scots in March 1904 after holding their opponents to a 1\u20131 draw. The following year, Wales defeated Scotland for the first time in its history after 29 years when goals from Meredith, [[Grenville Morris]] and [[Walter Watkins]] secured a 3\u20131 victory,<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=69}}</ref> although Wales was unable to capitalise on the victory as they finished second to England in the [[1905\u201306 British Home Championship]] after failing to win either of its other fixtures.<ref name=\"bhc1900\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1900-14.html |title=British Home Championship 1900\u20131914 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Having missed the previous two years while serving a ban for his part in the [[English football bribery scandal|1905 English football bribery scandal]], Meredith returned to play for Wales in the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship]]. In its first match, Wales defeated Ireland 3\u20132 in [[Belfast]] with Meredith scoring his side's second goal before [[Lot Jones]] scored the winning goal. Grenville Morris scored the only goal of the match to give Wales its third consecutive victory over Scotland.<ref name=\"stead7476\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=74\u201376}}</ref> In Wales' final match, Lot Jones gave his side the lead at [[Craven Cottage]] before England equalised in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1906-07/M0090Wal1907.html |title=England 1\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> England went on to draw its final game of the tournament against Scotland, handing Wales its first British Home Championship success. All 21 players used in the tournament were awarded a commemoration medal by the FAW for the achievement.<ref name=\"stead7476\"/>\n\nThe team's fortunes suffered a complete reversal in the [[1907\u201308 British Home Championship|1907\u201308 Championship]]. After losing their opening match against Scotland, the side suffered a 7\u20131 home defeat to England in a match where three goalkeepers were used. A final defeat against Ireland resulted in Wales finishing bottom of the championship table one year after winning the tournament outright.<ref name=\"stead7679\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=76\u201379}}</ref> Several personnel changes were implemented soon after, [[Ted Robbins (football administrator)|Ted Robbins]] was appointed FAW secretary in 1909 and one of Wales' most prominent players of the era, goalkeeper [[Leigh Richmond Roose]], was dropped.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=234}}</ref> Although considered \"one of the greatest players of his generation\",<ref name=\"Roose\">{{cite web |url=https://biography.wales/article/s-ROOS-RIC-1877 |title=Leigh Richmond Roose |publisher=Dictionary of Welsh Biography |last=Richards |first=Thomas |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Roose had developed a reputation for eccentricity that proved costly at times. In March 1910, Wales suffered a 1\u20130 defeat to Scotland when Roose allowed a speculative shot into the net having had his back turned towards play, talking to a spectator. In November of the same year, Roose suffered a broken arm while playing for his club side but declared himself fit for the British Home Championship internationals in March 1911. A poor performance in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland ultimately ended his international career as he was never selected for Wales again.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/>\n\nWales came within one match of winning a second title in 1912 and 1913, losing deciding matches against England on both occasions.<ref name=\"bhc1900\"/> In the [[1913\u201314 British Home Championship|final edition of the championship]] before the First World War, Wales finished bottom of the table with one point. Robbins complained that English clubs had been \"antagonistic\" when asked to release players for international duty. In December 1914, the Home Nations took the decision to suspend the British Home Championship following the outbreak of the war.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=85}}</ref> Eight players who had represented Wales in international football were killed during the conflict, including Leigh Roose.<ref name=\"Roose\"/>\n\nWales' first fixtures at the end of the war were two friendly matches against England, organised to raise funds for the FAW. The matches were not considered full internationals, being titled victory matches instead. Wales won the first meeting, led by 40-year old Meredith, but was defeated in the return match a fortnight later.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=89}}</ref> The British Home Championship returned for the [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1919\u201320 season]] with Wales' first post-war match ending in a 2\u20132 draw with pre-war champions Ireland in Belfast.<ref name=\"bhc1920\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1920-39.html |title=British Home Championship 1920\u20131939 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> A draw against Scotland was followed by a 2\u20131 victory over England, the first time Wales had defeated its neighbour in a competitive fixture since 1882. Goals from [[Stan Davies]] and [[Dick Richards (footballer)|Dick Richards]] secured victory for Wales, which had been reduced to ten men in the second half when [[Harry Millership]] went off injured, but the performance of the now 45-year old Meredith drew headlines.<ref name=\"stead9293\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=92\u201393}}</ref> Winning his final cap, 25 years after his debut, Meredith wept openly at the end of the match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=57}}</ref> He ended his international career as both Wales' most-capped player and its record goalscorer having scored 11 times in 48 appearances.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wal-recintlp.html |title=Wales \u2013 Record International Players |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Passo Alpuin |first=Luis Fernando |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The team were still reliant on England defeating Scotland to secure its second championship. Despite leading 4\u20132 at half-time, Scotland lost the match 5\u20134.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"stead9293\"/>\n\n==1920s success and decline==\n\nWales was unable to defend its title in the [[1920\u201321 British Home Championship|1920\u201321 season]], losing 2\u20131 to Scotland in the opening game. A goalless draw with England and a 2\u20131 victory over Ireland did secure the side the runners-up spot.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> With club sides in Wales attracting record crowds, the national team often found itself losing out to the domestic game. The victory over Ireland was held on the same day that [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] hosted [[South Shields F.C.|South Shields]] in the [[Football League Second Division]], with only 11,000 attending the national side's match in Swansea while more than 30,000 attended Cardiff's fixture.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=94\u201395}}</ref> Disappointing results between 1922 and 1923 prompted a revamp of the team for the [[1923\u201324 British Home Championship]]. One of the debutants in the team was [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town's]] [[Willie Davies (footballer)|Willie Davies]] who made an instant impact, scoring one of his side's goals during a 2\u20130 victory over Scotland in the opening game. Davies scored again in Wales' second match, a 2\u20131 victory over England with [[Ted Vizard]] scoring the winning goal. A final victory over Ireland, via a [[Moses Russell]] penalty, secured the title for Wales having beaten all three sides in the same tournament for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> The success was partly attributed to the team's star players being released to play, but this trend soon reverted to type for the opening match of the [[1924\u201325 British Home Championship|1924\u201325 tournament]]; six players withdrew from the squad for the opening match, a 3\u20131 defeat to Scotland. Wales' success did prompt England to agree to a Saturday fixture in Wales for the first time; [[Fred Keenor]] scored for Wales but the side fell to a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> Only a goalless draw with Ireland stopped Wales finishing last, only a year after winning the tournament.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\nSquad withdrawals proved a continued problem for the Welsh side. When Wales was left short for the visit of Scotland in the [[1925\u201326 British Home Championship|1925\u201326 Championship]], Ted Robbins called up debutant [[Jack Lewis (footballer, born 1902)|Jack Lewis]] after following him to a train station in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] where he was due to travel to Birmingham to play for Cardiff City.<ref name=\"s105106\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Defeats to Scotland and Ireland followed and Robbins was again forced to make a last minute interception for the final match against England. [[John Pullen]] had been travelling to London with Moses Russell and was persuaded to join up to win his first cap, alongside [[Charlie Jones (footballer, born 1899)|Charlie Jones]].<ref name=\"s105106\"/> Wales went on to win the match 3\u20131.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> Wales recorded a third championship win of the decade during the [[1927\u201328 British Home Championship|1927\u201328 tournament]]. The competition had started poorly for the side, conceding two goals in the first half against Scotland before [[Ernie Curtis]] and an own goal by [[Jimmy Gibson (footballer, born 1901)|Jimmy Gibson]] salvaged a point. Wales defeated England 2\u20131 before travelling to Belfast to play Ireland in the final match. The game was tied at 1\u20131 until [[Wilf Lewis]] secured the win for Wales, scoring the winning goal by charging both the ball and opposition goalkeeper into the net. When Ireland defeated Scotland two weeks later, Wales was officially confirmed as winners.<ref name=\"s110112\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the FAW received an invitation to tour Canada and selected a 20-man squad for the trip.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> Wales played 15 matches against regional teams in little over a month during the tour, winning each one.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/britishfatours.html#1929WAL |title=British FA XI Tours |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |last=Morrison |first=Neil |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> [[Len Davies]] proved prolific during the tour, scoring seven of his side's goals in an 8\u20130 victory over Lower Mainland.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> However, Wales returned to one of the worst British Home Championship campaigns in its history. After suffering a 4\u20132 defeat to Scotland in the opening match, Wales endured a 6\u20130 defeat to England in its second fixture.<ref name=\"s113114\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=113\u2013114}}</ref> The tournament ended with a severely depleted Wales side succumbing to a 7\u20130 defeat to Ireland in which [[Joe Bambrick]] scored six of his side's goals,<ref>{{harvnb|Leighton|2010|p=142}}</ref> the most any player has scored in a single match against Wales. The national side's poor results at the end of the 1920s were partly blamed on the deterioration of Welsh club sides. By the end of the decade, Cardiff City had been relegated to the Second Division, [[Aberdare Athletic F.C.|Aberdare Athletic]] had dropped out of the Football League and both [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and [[Merthyr Town F.C.|Merthyr Town]] had survived re-elections to avoid the same fate.<ref name=\"s113114\"/>\n\n==Pre-war recovery==\n[[File:Fred Keenor, Brentford FC footballer, 1919.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Fred Keenor]], who captained the team of \"unknowns\" in 1930]]\nIn 1930, the Football League introduced a new ruling which prohibited its members from releasing players for international fixtures. The ruling was designed to force international matches to be scheduled on days that would not clash with Football League fixtures. Wales' first match under the ruling was the opening game of the [[1930\u201331 British Home Championship]] against Scotland which was largely unaffected by the ruling as it drew the majority of its players from its own leagues. Wales were forced to call up a mixture of lower division and amateur players in order to field a side. Nine of Wales' eleven players made their international debut in the game, with only captain Fred Keenor and goalkeeper [[Len Evans (footballer)|Len Evans]] having previous international experience. As a result, the team was dubbed \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\".<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |title=Denmark v Wales: The story of the 1930s 'unknowns' who forced a draw in Scotland |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |last=Williams |first=Aled |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324124029/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |archive-date=24 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"s116118\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=116\u2013118}}</ref> Ahead of the match, Keenor asked Ted Robbins if he could have the players to himself for four hours before the game. Taking the team to relax and discuss tactics for the match, in his pre-match team talk he exhorted his teammates, \"There's eleven of them and eleven of us, and there's only one ball, and it's ours\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |title=Scotland vs. Wales: Five classic matches |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |first=Andi |last=Thomas |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818094059/http://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |archive-date=18 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite their inexperience, the Welsh side held Scotland to a 1\u20131 draw having taken the lead after six minutes from a goal by [[Tommy Bamford]].<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/> The display led to a Scottish newspaper describing the Welsh performance as \"the pluckiest display in the history of international football\".<ref name=\"s116118\"/> The Welsh public also responded by calling for the same side to remain for the following match against England, although [[Elvet Collins]] was replaced due to injury.<ref name=\"s116118\"/> There was no repeat of the result; the Welsh side lost 4\u20130 at the Racecourse Ground.<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/>\n\nA compromise between the Football League and the other Home Nations was reached in 1931, with the sides being required to provide 21 days notice for a player's release, although the club were only obliged to release English players. The FAW would also be responsible for the wages and insurance of the players during the time away, a stipulation that placed increasing strain on the organisation's already slim finances.<ref name=\"s119121\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=119\u2013121}}</ref> However, in practice, the more inclusive ruling provided little improvement as the FAW's release requests for players were continually rejected; during the [[1931\u201332 British Home Championship]], Wales finished bottom after losing all of its matches having used 26 players in only 3 games.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"s119121\"/> The number included [[Eddie Parris]] who became the first black player to represent Wales.<ref name=\"s119121\"/> The FAW subsequently gave in to the Football League and agreed to hold matches in midweek to avoid a fixture clash. The decision proved astute as Wales defeated Scotland 5\u20132 in the opening game of the [[1932\u201333 British Home Championship|1932\u201333 tournament]]. Fred Keenor won his 32nd and final international cap in the game, earning praise for his performance. A goalless draw with England and a 4\u20131 victory over Ireland secured Wales' fifth Home Championship title.<ref name=\"s122123\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=122\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nWales travelled to [[Paris]], France, in May 1933 to play its first international fixture against an opponent other than the Home Nations. [[Thomas Griffiths (footballer, born 1906)|Tommy Griffiths]] scored Wales' goal during a 1\u20131 draw with [[France national football team|France]] at the [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]].<ref name=\"s122123\"/> Buoyed by their championship victory, the Welsh team began their title defense in the [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship]] by securing a 3\u20132 victory over Scotland in front of 40,000 fans at [[Ninian Park]]. A draw with Ireland in Belfast meant Wales required a victory over England to guarantee consecutive titles. The match was played at [[St James' Park]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] with Wales taking an early lead through [[Tommy Mills (footballer)|Tommy Mills]]. The tension of the match was so intense that Mills nearly failed to return for the second half having been sick during half-time. [[Eric Brook]] equalised for England in the second half but, with less than ten minutes remaining, [[Dai Astley]] scored a header to give Wales victory and win the Home Championship in consecutive years for the only time in the nation's history.<ref name=\"s124125\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1933-34/M0189Wal1933.html |title=England 1\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales failed to retain its title in [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship|1934\u201335]], finishing last, but narrowly missed out on another title in the [[1935\u201336 British Home Championship]]. Needing a win against Ireland to secure the championship, Wales went on to lose 3\u20132.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> The side recovered the following season and defeated England in a home fixture for the first time since 1882 via goals from [[Pat Glover]] and [[Seymour Morris]]. Glover again proved the match winner in Wales' second fixture, scoring both goals as the side defeated Scotland 2\u20131. Wales won its third title in five years by winning 4\u20131 over Ireland in its last fixture, Glover scoring two more to finish as top goalscorer with five goals in the competition.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=128\u2013129}}</ref> Wales also went on to share the [[1938\u201339 British Home Championship]] title with both England and Scotland after all three sides attained four points in the final edition of the tournament before the outbreak of the Second World War.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\n==Wartime and new overseas competition==\nThe British Home Championship was postponed during wartime; Wales' final fixture before the start of the war was a 2\u20131 defeat against France.<ref name=\"matches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal-intres.html |title=International matches of Wales |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Nyg\u00e5rd |first=Jostein |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> The side's first wartime fixture was a 1\u20131 draw with England in a charity match to raise money for the [[Red Cross]]. The following year, Wales were hosted at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] for the first time having previously been considered less of a draw than Scotland. Wales won the match 1\u20130 through a goal by [[Bryn Jones (footballer, born 1912)|Bryn Jones]].<ref name=\"s133135\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=133\u2013135}}</ref> For the majority of the war, Wales only played fixtures against England, the two sides met 15 times between 1939 and 1945. Wales final wartime matches were against Scotland and Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welshsoccerarchive.co.uk/index.php/internationals/wartime |title=Wartime Internationals |publisher=Welsh Football Data Archive |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> As the war drew to a close, the national side was rocked by the death of Ted Robbins in January 1946. Robbins had served as secretary of the FAW since 1909 and was credited as a major factor in the team's success in previous decades.<ref name=\"s133135\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS134824498&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS134824498&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Sport in Brief |newspaper=The Times |p=8 |date=18 January 1946 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John Charles, Wales versus Scotland, Ninian Park, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|[[John Charles]] (pictured in 1954) was one of Wales' most prominent players during the 1950s.]]\nThe British Home Championship returned for the [[1946\u201347 British Home Championship|1946\u201347 campaign]] and Wales' first competitive post-war fixture was against Scotland in October 1946.<ref name=\"matches\"/> The wartime gap had increased public appetite for the sport and the break resulted in an entirely new generation of players being involved in the squad. One of the debutants, [[Trevor Ford]], scored one of Wales' goals in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=43}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=136}}</ref> However, defeats to England and Northern Ireland resulted in a third-place finish during the first post-war championship.<ref name=\"bhc1940\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1947-66.html |title=British Home Championship 1947\u20131966 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales began its campaign with a 3\u20130 defeat against England but defeated Scotland at [[Hampden Park]] for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=138\u2013139}}</ref> A win over Northern Ireland left Wales leading the group with only one match to be played. In the final match, England defeated Scotland to claim the championship by a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> In 1949, the Wales national side embarked on its first overseas tour with matches against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. As all three opponents wore red shirts, the fixtures necessitated the first away kit in Wales' history. A yellow shirt with green collar and trim was adopted for the tour, featuring the [[Welsh Dragon]] on the pocket. The tour proved disastrous for the squad however, as Wales lost all three fixtures and the squad was involved in a road accident when the team coach crashed during a tour of the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nWales and the other Home Nations entered the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time in 1950 and the [[1949\u201350 British Home Championship]] was used to determine qualification for the tournament. The added incentive resulted in a crowd of more than 60,000 attending Wales' opening fixture against England at Ninian Park, but they witnessed their side suffer a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=146}}</ref> A further defeat to Scotland ended Wales' hopes of qualification and only a goalless draw with Northern Ireland stopped the side finishing bottom of the group on [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Prior to the Ireland match, Belgium had travelled to Cardiff to become the first overseas side to visit Wales for an international match. Trevor Ford scored a hat-trick during a 5\u20131 victory for Wales. Portugal and Switzerland also travelled to Wales in 1951, as Wales avenged its earlier defeats by winning both matches.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=148\u2013149}}</ref> During the following year's championship, Trevor Ford became Wales' leading goalscorer of all-time when he scored a brace during a 4\u20132 defeat to England. Having entered the match on ten goals, his double resulted in him overtaking Billy Meredith's tally of eleven.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/trevor-ford-37679/ |title=Trevor Ford Player Statistics |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Some sources credit [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] with twelve goals for Wales,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1946-60/1950-51/M0260Wal1950.html |title=England 4\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> but most contemporary sources only list him with 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/wales/tab/stats/option/scorers/ |title=Wales national football team statistics and records: top scorers |website=11v11.com |publisher=FAS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=12145 |title= Billy Lewis |website=eu-football.info |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Further breakdown can be viewed at [[Talk:Billy Lewis (footballer)]].|group=lower-alpha}}\n\nWales celebrated its 75th anniversary by winning its first post-war British Home Championship title by sharing the [[1951\u201352 British Home Championship]] edition with England.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=45}}</ref> The two sides had drawn their meeting in the first fixture before both won their remaining matches to finish on five points.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Wales' final match of the competition was a 3\u20130 victory over Northern Ireland at Vetch Field, the first international match held at the ground in 25 years. The Welsh squad contained several young players born or brought up in the Swansea area, including Ford, [[Ivor Allchurch]] and [[Roy Paul]], and the game was regarded as a homecoming match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=150}}</ref> Allchurch scored one of his side's goals in the match to finish tied as the competition's top goalscorer.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=47}}</ref> Wales struggled in the years immediately afterwards, finishing bottom of the Championship in consecutive seasons, including the [[1953\u201354 British Home Championship|1953\u201354 tournament]] which saw the team fail to qualify for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> The period also included a disastrous European tour in 1953 during which Wales suffered a 6\u20131 defeat to France and a 5\u20132 defeat to [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=153}}</ref>\n\n===Austria and The Battle of Wrexham===\n[[File:Trevor Ford (1959).jpg|thumb|right|[[Trevor Ford]], Wales' record goalscorer at one time and whose physical style of play was a reason for Austrian animosity]] \nIn 1954, encouraged by the work of [[Walter Winterbottom]] with England, the FAW appointed the first manager of the Welsh national side in former captain [[Walley Barnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"s155156\"/> His first match in charge of the side was a match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in [[Vienna]] which attracted 60,000 spectators. Despite winning 2\u20130, the Austrians were infuriated by the physical style of play adopted by Wales, particularly forwards Ford and [[Derek Tapscott]], which was unfamiliar outside Britain. The Austria captain [[Ernst Ocwirk]] described the match as \"the dirtiest game he'd ever seen.\"<ref name=\"s155156\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=155}}</ref> Yugoslavia travelled to Wales in September 1954 in a reverse of the two side's fixture in 1953 and became the first foreign opposition to win in Wales after winning 3\u20131, having trailed 1\u20130 at half-time.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=51}}</ref> Wales' burgeoning involvement in continental football resulted in the FAW being accepted as members of the recently founded [[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) in 1954.<ref name=\"s155156\"/>\n\nThe [[1955\u201356 British Home Championship]] brought some improvement for Wales as the side recorded its first victory over England in 17 years at Ninian Park. The period also saw the emergence of [[John Charles]] for the national side.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> Charles and his brother [[Mel Charles|Mel]] often played alongside another set of brothers, Ivor and [[Len Allchurch]], becoming the first sets of brothers to play for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=12}}</ref> John Charles quickly gained a reputation as the side's leading player, featuring as either a [[centre-half]] or [[centre-forward]], and his performance in the victory over England led ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' reporter Dewi Lewis to describe him as \"indeed the perfect footballer if ever there was one.\"<ref name=\"s157160\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=157\u2013160}}</ref> All four sides shared the British Home Championship title after finishing on three points, the only occurrence of a four-way tie in the competition's 100-year history. Wales narrowly missed out on winning the title having drawn 1\u20131 with Northern Ireland in its final game in which Roy Paul missed a penalty with Wales already leading 1\u20130. Ireland later equalised and the game ended as a tie.<ref name=\"s157160\"/>\n\nAt the end of 1955, Austria travelled to Wales a year after its 2\u20130 victory. The Austrian team were eager to match the physicality of the Welsh side shown in the first meeting and the match descended into violent chaos.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The French referee, Louis Fauquemberghe,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-austria-23-november-1955-226605/ |title=Wales v Austria 23 November 1955 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/louis-fauquembergue/1/1/ |title=Louis Fauquembergue |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> who was unable to speak either German or English had little control as both sides continually resorted to fouling each other resulting in injuries to eight players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1945_1985.htm |title=1945\u20131986 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The most serious were to Austria's [[Theodor Wagner]], who suffered a fractured tibia, and Wales' Mel Charles, who left the field with ten minutes remaining after being heavily fouled.<ref name=\"timesaustria\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS67851640&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67851640&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Rough International Match at Wrexham |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=24 November 1955 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Roy Paul later described the scene in the Welsh dressing room after the match in his autobiography, writing \"Our goalkeeper, [[Jack Kelsey]], had scars on both legs. Derek Tapscott [...] had a six-inch gash on his knee. [...] John Charles leaned over his brother Melvyn with tears in his eyes. Melvyn lay silent, still dazed by a tackle which had sent him crashing to the ground.\"<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The national media were highly critical after the match; the ''Western Mail'' described the match as \"a disgrace\",<ref name=\"s157160\"/> while ''[[The Times]]'' wrote \"there were times when the pitch resembled a battlefield, with players down here and there\".<ref name=\"timesaustria\"/>\n\n==1958 FIFA World Cup==\n===Qualification and build-up===\nDisappointing results against European teams prompted a change of approach by the FAW who appointed [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] coach [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] as manager in 1956. Murphy enjoyed an inauspicious start with draws with Northern Ireland and Scotland before a 3\u20131 defeat to England in a match where Wales finished with nine players due to injuries. The British Home Championship was dropped as a qualifying format for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] and replaced by randomly drawn [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying groups]]. Wales was drawn alongside [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] and started positively by defeating Czechoslovakia 1\u20130 in its first fixture, via a goal by [[Roy Vernon]]. Wales travelled to East Germany in its second game with a squad of only 12 players. John Charles became highly critical of the FAW's reluctance to travel with more than a bare minimum of players, later writing \"There were more selectors than players. It was crazy. You've got to put the players first but with Wales it was the selectors first and the players second.\"<ref name=\"s161163\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=161\u2013163}}</ref> Wales eventually suffered a 2\u20131 defeat to the largely amateur East Germans in the nation's first competitive fixture.<ref name=\"s161163\"/>\n\n[[File:The Israeli team playing against Wales at the Ramat Gan stadium, 1958 D448-079.jpg|thumb|left|Wales playing [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] match to qualify for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]]]]\nThe squad continued to Czechoslovakia but had lost three players to illness and injury. The FAW, however, were still reluctant to call-up replacements and only an outcry from the press prompted Ray Daniel and [[Des Palmer]] to join up with the side. Nevertheless, Wales lost the match 2\u20130 and made qualification unobtainable. In the final group match, Palmer scored a hat-trick to defeat East Germany 4\u20131.<ref name=\"s161163\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/58qual.html#gr4 |title=World Cup 1958 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> A second opportunity at qualification emerged in December 1957 as the volatile political situation in Israel led to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] withdrawing from matches against the nation for varying reasons. FIFA rules decreed that no team could qualify for a World Cup without playing a match, and so a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] against a European qualifying group runner-up was arranged. [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] was drawn first but also refused to play Israel leading to a second draw in which Wales was selected. The FAW accepted the offer and Wales travelled to [[Tel Aviv]] for the first leg, winning 2\u20130 after goals from Ivor Allchurch and [[Dave Bowen]].<ref name=\"s165166\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer |Stead|1998|p=89}}</ref> The result was the first time Wales had won an international fixture outside Britain.<ref name=\"58guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/01/wales-1958-world-cup-quarter-final-euro-2016 |title=Wales at the 1958 World Cup: a quarter-final run with a difference |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Burton |first=Simon |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> Allchurch scored again in the second leg and a further goal from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] secured Wales' first qualification to a major international tournament.<ref name=\"s165166\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=165\u2013166}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15584126.from-the-argus-archive-when-wales-qualified-for-the-world-cup-in-1958-by-beating-israel-at-ninian-park-in-cardiff/ |title=From the Argus archive: When Wales qualified for the World Cup - in 1958 by beating Israel at Ninian Park in Cardiff |newspaper=South Wales Argus |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales received a favourable draw for the group stage of the tournament, being placed alongside [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and hosts [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. The side's preparations for the tournament were hampered by confusion over the availability of John Charles; having failed to qualify, the [[Italian Football Federation]] had instead organised a club tournament featuring Charles' side [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] who were reluctant to release the player. Wales manager Jimmy Murphy prepared his team to play without Charles, but the player eventually secured his release and arrived in Sweden only three days before the start of the competition.<ref name=\"s167168\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=167\u2013168}}</ref> The side was further weakened by the omission of Trevor Ford, the nation's record goalscorer. Ford had been banned from playing in Britain in 1956 after he revealed an illegal payments scandal in club football in his autobiography. Despite continuing to play abroad, he was overlooked for selection.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/league-legend-ford-one-finest-2486582 |title=League legend Ford one of finest Wales players |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Derek Tapscott had also fallen out with the FAW while Des Palmer missed out due to injury, leading to [[Colin Webster]] being selected in their stead.<ref name=\"s172173\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=172\u2013173}}</ref> Wales played a single warm-up match prior to the start of the tournament, defeating local amateur side Soltsjobaden 19\u20130.<ref name=\"s167168\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=91}}</ref>\n\n===Tournament===\nWales' opening game of the tournament was against Hungary. Although the Hungarian [[Golden Team]] had previously been considered one of the best teams in the world, the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] had weakened the side.<ref name=\"58guardian\"/><ref name=\"s169171\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=169\u2013171}}</ref> Nevertheless, Hungary quickly took the lead in the opening five minutes through [[J\u00f3zsef Bozsik]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-hungary-08-june-1958-227115/ |title=Wales v Hungary, 08 June 1958 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> The Hungarian defensive efforts were largely focused on containing John Charles who received attention described as \"rugged tactics\" by ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS50944713&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944713&searchId=R6&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh Fire Earns a Draw |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=9 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Journalist Ian Wooldridge wrote that the Hungarian tactics were often \"Just inside or wildly outside the international laws of soccer\".<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Charles scored an equaliser for Wales after 27 minutes, heading in from a corner to secure a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> In its second match, Wales played a Mexico side that had suffered a 3\u20130 defeat to Sweden in its opening game. The Welsh side entered the game as favourites but struggled to gain the advantage over their opponents.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Ivor Allchurch gave Wales the lead in the first half but Mexico responded strongly and scored a late equaliser in the 89th minute with Wales having been reduced to 10-men after [[Colin Baker (Welsh footballer)|Colin Baker]] had been injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CCS235231948&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235231948&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Late Goal by Mexico Checks Faltering Wales |newspaper=The Times |p=14 |date=12 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn its final group match, Wales met Sweden which had already qualified for the quarter-finals and had rested several players as a result.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> The Swedes were still the stronger of the two teams but were unable to breach the Welsh defense and the match ended goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=5&docId=GALE%7CCS50944720&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944720&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Draw with Sweden |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales finished the group stage with three points, tied for second with Hungary necessitating a play-off match between the two sides to determine which would advance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS50551504&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50551504&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Three U.K. Teams in World Cup Play-offs |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales faced Hungary needing a victory; Hungary's superior goal difference meant a draw would see it advance. Wales were dealt a blow when [[Lajos Tichy]] gave Hungary the lead after 30 minutes while John Charles was again the focus of the Hungarian defence, leaving the field on more than one occasion to receive treatment. Charles though, proved pivotal as he set up Ivor Allchurch for Wales' equalising goal. [[Terry Medwin]] scored a second for Wales and, despite finishing the match with 10-men following an injury to [[Ron Hewitt (footballer, born 1928)|Ron Hewitt]], the side held on to advance to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"s169171\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CCS51337938&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS51337938&searchId=R10&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales to Meet Brazil |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=18 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=95}}</ref>\n\nWales met [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], the winners of [[1958 FIFA World Cup Group 4|group 4]], in the quarter-finals. Much of the build-up for Wales focused on John Charles' attempts to recover from injuries sustained against Hungary. Described by one reporter as having received \"the most tremendous battering I have ever seen administered to a soccer player\", Charles failed to recover in time and his place in the side was taken by Colin Webster. Charles' absence proved costly as several chances were spurned with [[Brian Glanville]] of ''The Times'' remarking \"Wales could have won because all sorts of very tempting centres were coming across the goal and John wasn't there to head them in.\"<ref name=\"s172173\"/> Brazil went on to win the match by a single goal, scored by [[Pel\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS252140244&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS252140244&searchId=R11&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales' Gallant Exit from World Cup |newspaper=The Times |p=15 |date=20 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Post World Cup decline==\n===World Cup generation fades===\nThe success of the Welsh team in the World Cup resulted in huge demand for tickets for the side's opening match of the [[1958\u201359 British Home Championship]] against Scotland. However, the capacity home crowd at Ninian Park were left disappointed as Wales suffered a 3\u20130 defeat. Draws against England and Northern Ireland in the final two games left Wales bottom of the Championship, less than a year after its World Cup exploits. The following year, the post World Cup interest in the team led to a crowd of 62,634 attending a match against England at Ninian Park, a new record crowd for Wales and a record attendance for the ground.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=174\u2013176}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/8007646.stm |title=Farewell Ninian Park |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Wales began the 1960s by meeting the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] for the first time. The FAW had been against the Irish split and had resisted any attempts for the two sides to play for several years (England had played the Republic for the first time some 14 years earlier). Goals from Cliff Jones and [[Phil Woosnam]] won the match for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=178}}</ref>\n\nA shared British Home Championship title in [[1959\u201360 British Home Championship]] and a positive finish to the following year's campaign had raised hopes of Wales qualifying for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref name=\"s179182\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=179\u2013182}}</ref> Wales was drawn in a group with [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and Austria, although Austria withdrew due to financial problems before the matches began.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/62q.html |title=World Cup 1962 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4uJdBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq=Austria+1962+World+cup&source=bl&ots=xw6zGVVbQp&sig=ACfU3U1qFO3zLhQlHcjET-yfjb-mcrttfg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmoS1jKznAhU7VxUIHQnQDAYQ6AEwHHoECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=Austria%201962%20World%20cup&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of the FIFA World Cup |last=Dunmore |first=Tom |publisher=Scarecrow Press |p=131 |year=2015 |isbn=9780810887435}}</ref> Wales met Spain for the first match with a depleted side, missing several players including John Charles and Cliff Jones. Spain won the first match 2\u20131 before the two sides drew 1\u20131 in the second match in [[Madrid]] with Ivor Allchurch scoring Wales' goal. The result subsequently eliminated Wales from qualifying for the World Cup.<ref name=\"s179182\"/> Wales was invited to tour South America in 1962, the first matches played by the team outside Europe. The side played two matches against reigning World Cup holders Brazil, losing both 3\u20131. The tour concluded with a 2\u20131 defeat to Mexico and the retirement of long-serving goalkeeper Jack Kelsey from international football.<ref name=\"s179182\"/>\n\nWales entered the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] for the first time in 1964 (the Home Nations had not entered the inaugural edition in [[1960 European Nations' Cup|1960]]). In the preliminary qualifying round, Wales were drawn against Hungary and suffered a demoralising 3\u20131 defeat in the first leg in Budapest. A 1\u20131 draw in the return leg resulted in the side's elimination at the first attempt.<ref name=\"s184185\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=184\u2013185}}</ref> In April 1964, manager Jimmy Murphy was forced to miss Wales' match against Northern Ireland after his wife was taken ill. Swansea Town manager [[Trevor Morris (footballer)|Trevor Morris]] was placed in charge as Wales suffered a 3\u20132 defeat. Murphy never took charge of another match for Wales, resigning later in the year due to commitments with his role at Manchester United. The FAW drew up a shortlist of Welsh candidates, which included former players Jack Kelsey, [[Ron Burgess (footballer)|Ron Burgess]] and [[Tommy Jones (footballer, born 1909)|Tommy Jones]]. The role was eventually given to another former player, Dave Bowen, who had captained the team at the 1958 World Cup. Bowen took the job alongside his role as manager of [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. His first match in charge ended in victory when two late goals from [[Ken Leek]] secured a 3\u20132 win over Scotland in the [[1964\u201365 British Home Championship]].<ref name=\"s186187\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=186\u2013187}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Swansea Town Football Club (20740154461).jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Allchurch]] retired in 1966 as both Wales' record appearance holder and joint record goalscorer.]]\nIn [[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying]] for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], Wales was drawn in a group alongside the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"66rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/66qual.html |title=World Cup 1966 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The campaign began poorly for Wales as it lost 1\u20130 to Denmark in [[Copenhagen]] before losing a controversial game against Greece in [[Athens]]. Welsh players Ken Leek and [[Wyn Davies]] were continually fouled which led to brawls between players breaking out on several occasions.<ref name=\"s188190\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=188\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS67463050&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67463050&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Lose to Greece |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=10 December 1964 |accessdate=1 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> The home crowd also made attempts to break onto the pitch to confront the Welsh players which led to clashes with local police. Wales would avenge the defeat five months later with a 4\u20131 victory over Greece at Ninian Park in the return fixture. Wales travelled to [[Moscow]] in May 1965, suffering a 2\u20131 defeat in John Charles' final international appearance.<ref name=\"s188190\"/>\n\nDave Bowen was unavailable to manage Wales in its opening match of the [[1965\u201366 British Home Championship]] due to club commitments. Ron Burgess took charge for the match, which ended in a goalless draw.<ref name=\"s188190\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=23}}</ref> Bowen returned for the return fixture against the Soviet Union in October 1965. His side recorded a surprise 2\u20131 victory over their previously unbeaten opponents,<ref name=\"s191\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=191}}</ref> the only match the Soviet Union failed to win during qualifying,<ref name=\"66rsssf\"/> via goals by Roy Vernon and Ivor Allchurch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-ussr-27-october-1965-229197/ |title=Wales v USSR, 27 October 1965 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The result was not enough to secure qualification however as, despite beating Denmark 4\u20132 in its final game, Wales finished as runners-up in the group behind the Soviets.<ref name=\"s191\"/> Having failed to qualify for the World Cup, Wales instead embarked on another tour of South America in May 1966, playing two matches against Brazil and one against [[Chile national football team|Chile]]. Ivor Allchurch made his final appearance for Wales in the 2\u20130 defeat to Chile in the final match of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=140}}</ref> He retired as Wales' record appearance holder with 68 caps, and tied with Trevor Ford as the nation's record goalscorer with 23.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\"/><ref name=\"s191\"/>\n\n===Late 1960s struggles===\nLike the early World Cups, the qualifying phase for [[UEFA Euro 1968]] used the British Home Championship as a qualification group for the tour, with the results of the [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]] and [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368]] editions being combined to determine which of the Home Nations would progress.<ref name=\"s192\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=192}}</ref> Wales began the stage with a 1\u20131 draw against Scotland in October 1966 but ultimately finished third in the 1966\u201367 season after losing heavily to England and recording a goalless draw with Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"bhc1967\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1967-84.html |title=British Home Championship 1967\u20131984 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> For the 1967\u201368 championship, Wales adopted an all-red kit for the first time in its history. The team fared little better, losing to England and Scotland before recording its only victory of the Euro 1968 qualifying campaign by beating Northern Ireland 2\u20130.<ref name=\"s192\"/>\n\nWales recorded a creditable 1\u20131 draw with [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]] in April 1969 ahead of the qualifying campaign for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]. However, the side was hampered by withdrawals and refusals to release players for matches. Wales' first match was against reigning European champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Dave Bowen was forced to name several reserve players in the line-up, although the team only lost to a single goal by [[Luigi Riva]]. The side travelled to West Germany to play a return friendly against the side, with Bowen only able to select 13 players for the trip. Nevertheless, Wales recorded a second 1\u20131 draw; [[Barrie Jones]] had given Wales the lead before [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] equalised late in the match. The qualifying campaign for the 1970 World Cup ended with two defeats to East Germany and another to Italy as Wales failed to gain a single point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html |title=World Cup 1970 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Wales also finished bottom of the [[1968\u201369 British Home Championship|last British Home Championship of the decade]] with a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/>\n\nWales' struggles during the 1960s were blamed on several factors. The refusal of clubs to release players for international duty or to not allow a player to travel until a day before the match often disrupted the team. In his book ''Red Dragons: The Story of Welsh Football'', Phil Stead writes that Dave Bowen often could \"not pick a side until the day of the game because he was never sure who would be available.\"<ref name=\"s195197\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=195\u2013197}}</ref> The final match of the 1970 World Cup qualification group against Italy was nearly forfeited as Wales struggled to name a squad. One player, Wrexham's teenage defender [[Gareth Davies (footballer, born 1949)|Gareth Davies]], was contacted in the early hours of the morning and travelled overnight to make the team's flight to [[Rome]].<ref name=\"s195197\"/> The organisation of the team by the FAW was also criticised. Goalkeeper [[Gary Sprake]] later remarked that \"the international set-up with Wales at this time was amateurish at best\". Sprake later admitted to feigning injury under the guidance of his club manager [[Don Revie]] in order to avoid selection with the national side.<ref name=\"s186187\"/> [[John Toshack]], who made his debut in 1969, made similar comments: \"The whole set-up was a bit of a shambles [...] some of the players with more fashionable clubs were not too concerned about turning up for the less glamorous games.\"<ref name=\"s186187\"/> An incident in 1969 drew considerable criticism of the FAW when it failed to book enough seats for the ten travelling Welsh players and the organisation's members. When none of the officials offered to give up their seat, the crew declared that the last person to board the craft, winger [[Gil Reece]], would have to disembark. A furious Reece was left at the airport and had to travel alone to [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] before crossing the border into East Germany.<ref name=\"s195197\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-greats-pay-tribute-gil-2458945 |title=Welsh greats pay tribute to Gil the Blade |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=23 December 2003 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Departure of Bowen and arrival of Smith==\nWales began the 1970s in a more positive fashion, sharing the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship]] with England and Scotland. Wales had drawn with both before defeating Northern Ireland. The success raised hopes of the team qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1972]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=200}}</ref> Wales were drawn in a group alongside Czechoslovakia, [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. The side began the campaign with a goalless draw against Romania before losing 3\u20131 to Czechoslovakia,<ref name=\"72rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html |title=European Championship 1972 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> having led 1\u20130 with 12 minutes remaining.<ref name=\"s201204\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=201\u2013204}}</ref> Wales recovered with home and away victories over Finland but lost its remaining games to finish third, failing to qualify.<ref name=\"72rsssf\"/> During Wales' home victory over Finland, [[Trevor Hockey]] became the first player to represent the nation under a new parentage rule allowing players to represent countries other than their birth nations.<ref name=\"s201204\"/> His father had been born in [[Abertillery]], thus qualifying him for Wales under the new ruling.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=83}}</ref>\n\nWales' fortunes dipped alarmingly in the immediate years afterwards; the side finished bottom of the British Home Championship in four consecutive seasons between 1971 and 1975, winning only one match.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/> The team did perform slightly better during qualifying for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] in which they were drawn against England and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]. Wales lost to England in its opening game, failing to score for a sixth consecutive match, but surprised many by holding England to a draw in the return fixture at Wembley Stadium having taken an early lead through John Toshack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html#gr5 |title=World Cup 1974 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"s207209\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=207\u2013209}}</ref> Wales met Poland in March 1973 and recorded a 2\u20130 victory through goals by Trevor Hockey and [[Leighton James]]. Hockey would turn villain shortly before half-time during the return match in [[Chorz\u00f3w]], becoming the first Welsh player to be sent-off.<ref name=\"s207209\"/> The match deteriorated further in the second half as both sides committed numerous fouls and several scuffles broke out between the sides. [[Terry Yorath]] commented that he felt \"your physical well being was at risk\" during the game, while ''The Times'' headline referred to the match as \"a night of delinquency\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS302217531&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS302217531&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales lose their place and good name on night of delinquency |newspaper=The Times |p=18 |date=27 September 1973 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> In 1974, the FAW decided that the Wales manager's job required a full-time occupant and offered Dave Bowen the position on a permanent full-time basis. Bowen however rejected the role, unwilling to leave his position with Northampton. The job was instead given to the FAW's head of coaching, Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=211}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 1976===\n\nSmith's first test was the qualifying stage for [[UEFA Euro 1976]] as Wales were drawn alongside Hungary, Austria and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]]. In the opening match, Wales took the lead through [[Arfon Griffiths]], but eventually lost 2\u20131 to Austria. Griffiths scored again in Wales' next two matches, a 2\u20130 win over Hungary and a 5\u20130 win over Luxembourg. The side continued its good form by becoming the first British side to win in Hungary since 1909, also inflicting Hungary's first competitive home defeat since 1959, winning 2\u20131 via goals by John Toshack and [[John Mahoney (footballer)|John Mahoney]].<ref name=\"s212214\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=212\u2013214}}</ref> A second victory over Luxembourg was also Gary Sprake's final international appearance. Despite having being considered Wales' first choice goalkeeper for nearly a decade, he finished his career with 37 caps, later remarking \"it was expected of you as a [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] player that you put the club first\".<ref name=\"s212214\"/> In the final match, Wales met Austria in Wrexham needing only a draw to guarantee progress to the final eight of the tournament.<ref name=\"s217218\"/> Arfon Griffiths scored the only goal of the match as Wales secured a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=73}}</ref> In March 1976, the national side celebrated its centenary year with a friendly against England at the Racecourse Ground, which ended in a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref name=\"s217218\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nFor the 1976 edition of the European Championships, the quarter-finals were played as two-legged ties with the winners advancing to the semi-finals to be held in Yugoslavia.{{#tag:ref|Yugoslavia's hosting of the finals was dependent on the side progressing to the semi-finals.<ref name=\"s220\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} Wales was drawn against the host nation for its quarter-final tie with the first leg being played in [[Zagreb]]. The Yugoslavians took the lead after only 45 seconds through [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]] before adding a second early in the second half to win 2\u20130.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/76e.html |title=European Championship 1976 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> The second-leg was billed as one of the biggest matches in Wales' history, and the FAW (which had grown increasingly short of funds) considered an offer to move the game to Wembley Stadium to maximise profit. The FAW board was split after a vote, leaving the decision in the hands of president Terry Squire who ultimately chose Ninian Park as the venue.<ref name=\"s220\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=220}}</ref>\n\nEast German referee [[Rudi Gl\u00f6ckner]] was appointed for the match, and was infuriated when the flag of his home nation was not raised before the game.<ref name=\"woyugo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |title=The astonishing story of the forgotten Welsh football giants and the day Ninian Park erupted into violent chaos |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Abbandonato |first=Paul |date=22 May 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080442/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |archive-date=13 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gl\u00f6ckner controversially awarded Yugoslavia a penalty in the first half and disallowed a goal for Wales in the second, as the increasingly-irate crowd made several attempts to enter the pitch. Missiles were aimed at Gl\u00f6ckner for the remainder of the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw and eliminated Wales from the competition. Violence flared again at the final whistle; Gl\u00f6ckner required a police escort from the pitch, Yugoslavia midfielder [[Jurica Jerkovi\u0107]] had a physical altercation with a Welsh fan who had run onto the pitch, and another Welsh fan was arrested after a corner flag, which had been thrown in anger at the referee, struck a policeman in the neck.<ref name=\"s220\"/><ref name=\"woyugo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/wales-and-the-forgotten-quarter-final-team-of-1976-a7112191.html |title=Wales vs Belgium Euro 2016: The Welsh and the forgotten 'quarter-final' team of 1976 |newspaper=The Independent |last=Moore |first=Glen |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> As a result of the scenes during the match, Wales was initially handed a two-year ban from international football, although this was reduced on appeal to a fine of 20,000 [[Swiss franc]]s and the limitation of home qualifying matches for [[UEFA Euro 1980]] being held at least {{convert|200|km}} from Cardiff.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=222}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific''' \n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography''' \n* {{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth M |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |publisher=Bridge Books |year=1991 |isbn=1872424112 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=Ivor Allchurch M.B.E. |first1=David |last1=Farmer |first2 = Peter |last2= Stead |publisher=Christopher Davies (Publishing) Ltd. |location=Swansea | year= 1998 | isbn=0-7154-0733-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |url=https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1386666/1421693/201#?xywh=159%2C-142%2C1738%2C3921&cv=201 |title=The Early Development of Association Football in South Wales, 1890\u20131906 |journal=Transactions of the Honourable Society of the Cymmrodorian |last1=Lile |first1=Brian |last2=Farmer |first2=David |year=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=James |last=Leighton |title=Fred Keenor \u2013 The Man Who Never Gave Up |year=2010 |publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company |location=Derby |isbn=9781859838280 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/fredkeenormanwho0000leig }}\n*{{citation |title=Red Dragons \u2013 The Story of Welsh Football |last1=Stead |first1=Phil |publisher=Y Llofa |year=2013 |location=Ceredigion |isbn=9781847714688 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Wales national football team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Wales National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Wales national football team| ]]\n[[Category:History of association football by national team|Wales]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wales national team 1900.jpg|thumb|upright|260px|The Wales national team in 1900]]\nThe [[Wales national football team]] is the third oldest international [[association football]] team having played its first fixture in March 1876, four years after [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]] had contested the first international match. The team played annual fixtures against Scotland, England, and later [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] and these fixtures were eventually organised into the [[British Home Championship]], an annual competition between the [[Home Nations]]. Wales did not win its first championship until the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1906\u201307 edition]] of the competition and the triumph remained the nation's only title before the First World War. Wales improved considerably in the post-war period, and claimed three titles during the 1920s, although the team was often hindered by the reluctance of [[English Football League|Football League]] clubs to release its players for international duty. The situation was so grave that, in the early 1930s, Wales was forced to select a team of lower league and amateur players in a side that became known as \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\", in reference to captain [[Fred Keenor]] and the relative obscurity of his teammates.\n\nWhen able to call upon its strongest side, Wales enjoyed its most successful period in the British Home Championship, winning four titles in the six years before the Second World War. As competitive football resumed after the war, Wales began facing opponents from further afield and played matches against numerous other European nations for the first time. The side also began competing in qualification groups for the [[FIFA World Cup]]. After failing to qualify for the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]] editions, Wales qualified for its first World Cup in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]] after defeating [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a play-off match. During the tournament, the side progressed from its group under manager [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] before being defeated by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-final.\n\nThe side suffered a decline in the 1960s as the 1958 World Cup generation gradually retired. [[Dave Bowen]] replaced Murphy and managed the team for a decade between 1964 and 1974 but enjoyed little success, failing to qualify for a World Cup or the inaugural editions of the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] (later known as the European Championships). Bowen left the role in 1974, having turned down the chance to take the position full-time. He was replaced by Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]] who led the side to the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 1976]] in its centenary year, before being defeated by [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].{{#tag:ref|For the 1976 tournament, quarter-finals were played as a two-legged, home and away tie with the finals hosting only the semi-finals and beyond.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\"/>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Formation and early matches==\n[[File:Wales V Scotland 3386999.tif|thumb|A newspaper report of Wales first competitive match against Scotland in 1876]]\nThe [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first]] official international [[association football]] match was held in November 1872 between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ |title=The first international football match |publisher=BBC |last=Mitchell |first=Paul |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> Four years later, G. A. Clay-Thomas, a Welshman living in London, placed adverts in sports magazines ''[[The Field (magazine)|The Field]]'' and ''[[Bell's Life in London|Bell's Life]]'' proposing that a Welsh side be raised for a match against either Scotland or Ireland in [[rugby union|rugby]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853930/3853938/76/Clay |title=Football |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=8 |date=18 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> [[Llewelyn Kenrick]], a solicitor who had helped to found [[Druids F.C.]] in North Wales, pushed ahead with plans for a football match and accepted an invitation to play the Scottish national side. He helped establish the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW) in February 1876 to finalise arrangements for the forthcoming match,<ref name=\"Challenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/index.htm#y1876|title=1876 Kenrick's Challenge|work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> being appointed its first secretary.<ref>{{harvnb|Lile|Farmer|1984|p=196}}</ref> To qualify for selection, players were required to be Welsh or to have resided in the country for at least three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3386960/3386966/102/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=The Cardiff Times |p=6 |date=4 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Kenrick was criticised by some in South Wales for failing to notify players in the region of the forthcoming match, favouring to publish notices in London-based journals.<ref name=\"stead1013\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=10\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=120}}</ref> Unperturbed, he pushed forward with his plans and trial matches were held to find suitable players for the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853883/3853888/16/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=5 |date=12 February 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1876 Scotland v Wales football match|first Wales international football match]] was held on 2 March 1876 at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]] with the side wearing white shirts, featuring the [[Prince of Wales's feathers]], and black shorts.<ref name=\"stead1013\"/> The Welsh side were outclassed by their more experienced opponents, suffering a 4\u20130 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/wales-v-scotland-legendary-clashes-2021031 |title=Wales v Scotland: Legendary clashes |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Beech |first=Richard |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> A second fixture between the two sides was arranged for the following year and the [[Racecourse Ground]] in [[Wrexham]] became the venue for [[Wales national football team home stadium|Wales' first home international]].<ref name=\"dprecord\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |title=Is the Racecourse the world's oldest international venue? |newspaper=Daily Post |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925141407/https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Welsh side fell to a 2\u20130 defeat in the match. Wales returned to Scotland in 1878 but a fixture clash with the final of the [[Welsh Cup]] between Druids and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] led many players to refuse to travel. Such was the desperation to find willing players, the secretary of the [[Scottish Football Association]] travelled to Wales and visited the homes of players in an attempt to raise a side. A squad was eventually assembled but, having travelled overnight to Glasgow and containing many players who were not of sufficient standard, the side suffered a 9\u20130 defeat. The result remains Wales' worst defeat in international football.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, Wales and [[England national football team|England]] met for the first time in international football at a snow-covered [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]] in [[South London]]. The poor weather conditions resulted in the match being shortened to 60 minutes and the relatively unknown status of the Welsh side led to a low turnout of spectators; newspaper reports estimate the crowd was in the low hundreds with some even stating less than 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1878-79/M0008Wal1879.html |title=England 2\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RcfKAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=England+Wales+1879+snow+football&source=bl&ots=Cdw8QFMIi4&sig=ACfU3U1mF0MrVD9Z2p2ddF5DyEeI1JsjRQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgs6mTibXnAhXhQxUIHeT6BbgQ6AEwFnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=England%20Wales%201879%20snow%20football&f=false |title=The Victorian Football Miscellany |p=79 |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Superelastic |year=2013 |isbn=9780956227058}}</ref> During the match, [[William Davies (footballer, born 1855)|William Davies]] scored Wales' first international goal but his side were defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1877_1879.htm |title=The Story of Welsh Football 1877\u20131879 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The standard of the Welsh side was slowly improving and the side nearly held the visiting English side in March 1880. Having trailed 3\u20130, the Welsh side scored twice in the final ten minutes through [[William Roberts (footballer, born 1859)|William Roberts]] and [[John Roberts (footballer, born 1857)|John Roberts]] but were unable to equalise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1879-80/M0011Wal1880.html |title=Wales 2\u20134 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> William Roberts also scored Wales' goal against Scotland two weeks later in a 5\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=30}}</ref> Wales travelled to [[Alexandra Meadows]] in [[Blackburn]] the following year to play England. [[John Vaughan (footballer, born 1856)|John Vaughan]] scored the only goal of the game as Wales won its first international football match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4478237/4478241/90/Wales%20football |title=England V Wales |newspaper=Western Mail |p=4 |date=28 February 1881 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref><ref name=\"wcbc1880\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1880_1914.htm|title=The Story of Welsh Football 1880\u20131914 ||work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] were the final [[Home Nations|Home Nation]] to establish an international football team, playing its first fixture in February 1882 against England. Having suffered a 13\u20130 defeat against the English,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0014Ire1882.html |title=Ireland 0\u201313 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> the Irish side travelled to the Racecourse Ground to meet Wales for the first time. The more experienced Welsh side also proved too strong for the Irish, with [[John Price (footballer, born 1854)|John Price]] becoming the first [[List of Wales national football team hat-tricks|Welshman to score a hat-trick in international football]] during a 7\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tinyurl.gale.com/tinyurl/CXDsd2 |url-access=subscription |title=Wales V Ireland |newspaper=The Times |p=10 |date=27 February 1882 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Buoyed by their win, the Welsh side met England a month later and recorded a second victory over their neighbours. England had taken a 2\u20131 lead but were reduced to ten men when [[Charles Bambridge]] suffered a shoulder injury.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=31}}</ref> Wales pulled the score back to 3\u20133 before scoring twice in the final three minutes to claim a 5\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0016Wal1882.html |title=Wales 5\u20133 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Start of the British International Championship==\n\nWith all of the Home Nations competing regularly, the decision was taken to introduce a competitive tournament between the sides and the [[British Home Championship|British International Championship]] (later to become better known as the British Home Championship) was created in 1884.<ref name=\"stead3234\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=32\u201334}}</ref> The [[1883\u201384 British Home Championship|inaugural edition of the tournament]] was won by Scotland which won all three of its ties. Having defeated Ireland 6\u20130 in its opening match, Wales went on to finish third after suffering successive defeats to England and Scotland.<ref name=\"bhc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1884-99.html#1884 |title=British Home Championship 1884\u20131899 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> The early stages of the competition continued on the same lines; England and Scotland competed for the title, while Wales would finish third by defeating Ireland. In the first three years of competition, Wales' only points other than in matches against Ireland was a 1\u20131 draw with England in the [[1884\u201385 British Home Championship|1884\u201385 tournament]].<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> In the [[1886\u201387 British Home Championship|1886\u201387 edition]], Wales finished bottom of the competition for the first time after losing all three of its matches, including a 4\u20131 defeat to Ireland in the nation's first victory in international football. Wales had struggled to raise a team for the match and included Wrexham defender [[Bob Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|Bob Roberts]] playing as the goalkeeper. FAW secretary [[Alexander Hunter (footballer)|Alexander Hunter]] also stepped in when [[Humphrey Jones]] withdrew late.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> Hunter had never played football at such a level and his performance was described as \"glaringly deficient\".<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=93}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wales national team 1887.jpg|thumb|upright|240px|The Welsh national side in 1887]]\nIn a reversal of the previous year's events, the ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' claimed a weakened Ireland team travelled to Wales for the [[1887\u201388 British Home Championship]] and went on to lose the match 11\u20130,<ref name=\"wcbc1880\"/> although there were only four debutants in the team on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2010/11/017-3-march-1888.html?m=1 |title=Wales 11\u20130 Ireland |publisher=Northern Ireland Footballing Great |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> The scoreline remains a record victory for Wales. [[Jack Doughty]] scored four of the goals. Such was the one-sided nature of the game that three Welsh players left the field before the match ended to ensure they were on time for their train home.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> 5\u20131 defeats to both England and Scotland however ensured another third-place finish for Wales.<ref name=\"bhc\"/>\n\nWales avoided defeat in a fixture against Scotland for the first time with a goalless draw in the [[1888\u201389 British Home Championship]], simultaneously recording a first clean sheet against the Scots. The feat was achieved despite local amateur [[Alf Pugh]] starting in goal for Wales after the original selection, [[James Trainer]], failed to arrive at the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3670619/3670622/93/Wales%20football |title=Scotland vs Wales Association |newspaper=South Wales Daily News |p=3 |date=16 April 1889 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Pugh played the first 30 minutes before Wrexham's [[Sam Gillam]] arrived and took his place,<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> thus becoming the first substitution ever used in international football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales 0 Scotland 0|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/games/18890415.html|publisher=londonhearts.com|accessdate=16 December 2019|date=15 April 1889}}</ref> The following year, Wales played a home fixture outside the nation for the first time when a meeting with Ireland was held in [[Shrewsbury]] in an attempt to draw a large crowd. Wales won the match 5\u20132.<ref name=\"stead4041\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=40\u201341}}</ref> By the early 1890s, with the domestic game thriving in England, Wales was struggling to get players released for international fixtures, particularly for away matches against Ireland which required a three-day absence from a player's club due to ferry travel. As a result, Wales finished bottom of the British Home Championship five times during the decade, including three consecutive seasons between 1891 and 1893.<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4041\"/> Wales did record its highest placed finish to date in 1895 by finishing as runners-up to England after drawing all three of its fixtures, inspired by the likes of James Trainer, [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] and a debuting [[Billy Meredith]].<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4748\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\nWales continued its good form at the start of the [[1895\u201396 British Home Championship]] by thrashing Ireland 6\u20130 with both Meredith and Lewis scoring [[hat-trick|braces]]. The team's optimism was short-lived however when they suffered a crushing 9\u20131 defeat to England in their following match,<ref name=\"stead4748\"/> with [[Steve Bloomer]] scoring five of his side's goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/bloomer-intlg.html |title=Stephen Bloomer \u2013 International Goals |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Klukowski |first=Tomasz |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Wales would finish the 20th century by losing nine of its final ten matches, only avoiding defeat in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland in March 1897. The difficulties in calling up players from English teams became so pronounced that the FAW put forward a motion that national teams be granted the right to overrule clubs on player selection, although this was rejected. An approach to the English governing body, [[The Football Association]], also fell on deaf ears.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=51}}</ref>\n\n==New century==\n[[File:Billymeredith.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Billy Meredith]] made his debut for Wales in 1895]]\nThe [[1899\u20131900 British Home Championship]] revived hope in the side as Wales finished as runners-up to Scotland, led largely by the goals of Meredith and [[Tom Parry (footballer)|Tom Parry]]. Although results were still disappointing, the standard of the Welsh side was deemed to be improving rapidly as margins of defeat became smaller and several defeats to the English and Scottish sides between 1902 and 1905 were deemed unlucky based on the run of play.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=66\u201367}}</ref> The side also avoided defeat in an away fixture against the Scots in March 1904 after holding their opponents to a 1\u20131 draw. The following year, Wales defeated Scotland for the first time in its history after 29 years when goals from Meredith, [[Grenville Morris]] and [[Walter Watkins]] secured a 3\u20131 victory,<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=69}}</ref> although Wales was unable to capitalise on the victory as they finished second to England in the [[1905\u201306 British Home Championship]] after failing to win either of its other fixtures.<ref name=\"bhc1900\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1900-14.html |title=British Home Championship 1900\u20131914 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Having missed the previous two years while serving a ban for his part in the [[English football bribery scandal|1905 English football bribery scandal]], Meredith returned to play for Wales in the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship]]. In its first match, Wales defeated Ireland 3\u20132 in [[Belfast]] with Meredith scoring his side's second goal before [[Lot Jones]] scored the winning goal. Grenville Morris scored the only goal of the match to give Wales its third consecutive victory over Scotland.<ref name=\"stead7476\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=74\u201376}}</ref> In Wales' final match, Lot Jones gave his side the lead at [[Craven Cottage]] before England equalised in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1906-07/M0090Wal1907.html |title=England 1\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> England went on to draw its final game of the tournament against Scotland, handing Wales its first British Home Championship success. All 21 players used in the tournament were awarded a commemoration medal by the FAW for the achievement.<ref name=\"stead7476\"/>\n\nThe team's fortunes suffered a complete reversal in the [[1907\u201308 British Home Championship|1907\u201308 Championship]]. After losing their opening match against Scotland, the side suffered a 7\u20131 home defeat to England in a match where three goalkeepers were used. A final defeat against Ireland resulted in Wales finishing bottom of the championship table one year after winning the tournament outright.<ref name=\"stead7679\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=76\u201379}}</ref> Several personnel changes were implemented soon after, [[Ted Robbins (football administrator)|Ted Robbins]] was appointed FAW secretary in 1909 and one of Wales' most prominent players of the era, goalkeeper [[Leigh Richmond Roose]], was dropped.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=234}}</ref> Although considered \"one of the greatest players of his generation\",<ref name=\"Roose\">{{cite web |url=https://biography.wales/article/s-ROOS-RIC-1877 |title=Leigh Richmond Roose |publisher=Dictionary of Welsh Biography |last=Richards |first=Thomas |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Roose had developed a reputation for eccentricity that proved costly at times. In March 1910, Wales suffered a 1\u20130 defeat to Scotland when Roose allowed a speculative shot into the net having had his back turned towards play, talking to a spectator. In November of the same year, Roose suffered a broken arm while playing for his club side but declared himself fit for the British Home Championship internationals in March 1911. A poor performance in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland ultimately ended his international career as he was never selected for Wales again.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/>\n\nWales came within one match of winning a second title in 1912 and 1913, losing deciding matches against England on both occasions.<ref name=\"bhc1900\"/> In the [[1913\u201314 British Home Championship|final hosting of the championship]] before the First World War, Wales finished bottom of the table with one point. Robbins complained that English clubs had been \"antagonistic\" when asked to release players for international duty. In December 1914, the Home Nations took the decision to suspend the British Home Championship following the outbreak of the war.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=85}}</ref> Eight players who had represented Wales in international football were killed during the conflict, including Leigh Roose.<ref name=\"Roose\"/>\n\nWales' first fixtures at the end of the war were two friendly matches against England, organised to raise funds for the FAW. The matches were not considered full internationals, being titled victory matches instead. Wales won the first meeting, led by 40-year old Meredith, but was defeated in the return match a fortnight later.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=89}}</ref> The British Home Championship returned for the [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1919\u201320 season]] with Wales' first post-war match ending in a 2\u20132 draw with pre-war champions Ireland in Belfast.<ref name=\"bhc1920\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1920-39.html |title=British Home Championship 1920\u20131939 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> A draw against Scotland was followed by a 2\u20131 victory over England, the first time Wales had defeated its neighbour in a competitive fixture since 1882. Goals from [[Stan Davies]] and [[Dick Richards (footballer)|Dick Richards]] secured victory for Wales, which had been reduced to ten men in the second half when [[Harry Millership]] went off injured, but the performance of the now 45-year old Meredith drew headlines.<ref name=\"stead9293\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=92\u201393}}</ref> Winning his final cap, 25 years after his debut, Meredith wept openly at the end of the match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=57}}</ref> He ended his international career as both Wales' most-capped player and its record goalscorer having scored 11 times in 48 appearances.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wal-recintlp.html |title=Wales \u2013 Record International Players |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Passo Alpuin |first=Luis Fernando |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The team were still reliant on England defeating Scotland to secure its second championship. Despite leading 4\u20132 at half-time, Scotland lost the match 5\u20134.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"stead9293\"/>\n\n==1920s success and decline==\n\nWales was unable to defend its title in the [[1920\u201321 British Home Championship|1920\u201321 season]], losing 2\u20131 to Scotland in the opening game. A goalless draw with England and a 2\u20131 victory over Ireland did secure the side the runners-up spot.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> With club sides in Wales attracting record crowds, the national team often found itself losing out to the domestic game. The victory over Ireland was held on the same day that [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] hosted [[South Shields F.C.|South Shields]] in the [[Football League Second Division]], with only 11,000 attending the national side's match in Swansea while more than 30,000 attended Cardiff's fixture.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=94\u201395}}</ref> Disappointing results between 1922 and 1923 prompted a revamp of the team for the [[1923\u201324 British Home Championship]]. One of the debutants in the team was [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town's]] [[Willie Davies (footballer)|Willie Davies]] who made an instant impact, scoring one of his side's goals during a 2\u20130 victory over Scotland in the opening game. Davies scored again in Wales' second match, a 2\u20131 victory over England with [[Ted Vizard]] scoring the winning goal. A final victory over Ireland, via a [[Moses Russell]] penalty, secured the title for Wales having beaten all three sides in the same tournament for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> The success was partly attributed to the team's star players being released to play, but this trend soon reverted to type for the opening match of the [[1924\u201325 British Home Championship|1924\u201325 tournament]]; six players withdrew from the squad for the opening match, a 3\u20131 defeat to Scotland. Wales' success did prompt England to agree to a Saturday fixture in Wales for the first time; [[Fred Keenor]] scored for Wales but the side fell to a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> Only a goalless draw with Ireland stopped Wales finishing last, only a year after winning the tournament.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\nSquad withdrawals proved a continued problem for the Welsh side. When Wales was left short for the visit of Scotland in the [[1925\u201326 British Home Championship|1925\u201326 Championship]], Ted Robbins called up debutant [[Jack Lewis (footballer, born 1902)|Jack Lewis]] after following him to a train station in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] where he was due to travel to Birmingham to play for Cardiff City.<ref name=\"s105106\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Defeats to Scotland and Ireland followed and Robbins was again forced to make a last minute interception for the final match against England. [[John Pullen]] had been travelling to London with Moses Russell and was persuaded to join up to win his first cap, alongside [[Charlie Jones (footballer, born 1899)|Charlie Jones]].<ref name=\"s105106\"/> Wales went on to win the match 3\u20131.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> Wales recorded a third championship win of the decade during the [[1927\u201328 British Home Championship|1927\u201328 tournament]]. The competition had started poorly for the side, conceding two goals in the first half against Scotland before [[Ernie Curtis]] and an own goal by [[Jimmy Gibson (footballer, born 1901)|Jimmy Gibson]] salvaged a point. Wales defeated England 2\u20131 before travelling to Belfast to play Ireland in the final match. The game was tied at 1\u20131 until [[Wilf Lewis]] secured the win for Wales, scoring the winning goal by charging both the ball and opposition goalkeeper into the net. When Ireland defeated Scotland two weeks later, Wales was officially confirmed as winners.<ref name=\"s110112\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the FAW received an invitation to tour Canada and selected a 20-man squad for the trip.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> Wales played 15 matches against regional teams in little over a month during the tour, winning each one.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/britishfatours.html#1929WAL |title=British FA XI Tours |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |last=Morrison |first=Neil |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> [[Len Davies]] proved prolific during the tour, scoring seven of his side's goals in an 8\u20130 victory over Lower Mainland.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> However, Wales returned to one of the worst British Home Championship campaigns in its history. After suffering a 4\u20132 defeat to Scotland in the opening match, Wales endured a 6\u20130 defeat to England in its second fixture.<ref name=\"s113114\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=113\u2013114}}</ref> The tournament ended with a severely depleted Wales side succumbing to a 7\u20130 defeat to Ireland in which [[Joe Bambrick]] scored six of his side's goals,<ref>{{harvnb|Leighton|2010|p=142}}</ref> the most any player has scored in a single match against Wales. The national side's poor results at the end of the 1920s were partly blamed on the deterioration of Welsh club sides. By the end of the decade, Cardiff City had been relegated to the Second Division, [[Aberdare Athletic F.C.|Aberdare Athletic]] had dropped out of the Football League and both [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and [[Merthyr Town F.C.|Merthyr Town]] had survived re-elections to avoid the same fate.<ref name=\"s113114\"/>\n\n==Pre-war recovery==\n[[File:Fred Keenor, Brentford FC footballer, 1919.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Fred Keenor]], who captained the team of \"unknowns\" in 1930]]\nIn 1930, the Football League introduced a new ruling which prohibited its members from releasing players for international fixtures. The ruling was designed to force international matches to be scheduled on days that would not clash with Football League fixtures. Wales' first match under the ruling was the opening game of the [[1930\u201331 British Home Championship]] against Scotland which was largely unaffected by the ruling as it drew the majority of its players from its own leagues. Wales were forced to call up a mixture of lower division and amateur players in order to field a side. Nine of Wales' eleven players made their international debut in the game, with only captain Fred Keenor and goalkeeper [[Len Evans (footballer)|Len Evans]] having previous international experience. As a result, the team was dubbed \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\".<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |title=Denmark v Wales: The story of the 1930s 'unknowns' who forced a draw in Scotland |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |last=Williams |first=Aled |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324124029/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |archive-date=24 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"s116118\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=116\u2013118}}</ref> Ahead of the match, Keenor asked Ted Robbins if he could have the players to himself for four hours before the game. Taking the team to relax and discuss tactics for the match, in his pre-match team talk he exhorted his teammates, \"There's eleven of them and eleven of us, and there's only one ball, and it's ours\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |title=Scotland vs. Wales: Five classic matches |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |first=Andi |last=Thomas |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818094059/http://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |archive-date=18 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite their inexperience, the Welsh side held Scotland to a 1\u20131 draw having taken the lead after six minutes from a goal by [[Tommy Bamford]].<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/> The display led to a Scottish newspaper describing the Welsh performance as \"the pluckiest display in the history of international football\".<ref name=\"s116118\"/> The Welsh public also responded by calling for the same side to remain for the following match against England, although [[Elvet Collins]] was replaced due to injury.<ref name=\"s116118\"/> There was no repeat of the result; the Welsh side lost 4\u20130 at the Racecourse Ground.<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/>\n\nA compromise between the Football League and the other Home Nations was reached in 1931, with the sides being required to provide 21 days notice for a player's release, although the club were only obliged to release English players. The FAW would also be responsible for the wages and insurance of the players during the time away, a stipulation that placed increasing strain on the organisation's already slim finances.<ref name=\"s119121\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=119\u2013121}}</ref> However, in practice, the more inclusive ruling provided little improvement as the FAW's release requests for players were continually rejected; during the [[1931\u201332 British Home Championship]], Wales finished bottom after losing all of its matches having used 26 players in only 3 games.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"s119121\"/> The number included [[Eddie Parris]] who became the first black player to represent Wales.<ref name=\"s119121\"/> The FAW subsequently gave in to the Football League and agreed to hold matches in midweek to avoid a fixture clash. The decision proved astute as Wales defeated Scotland 5\u20132 in the opening game of the [[1932\u201333 British Home Championship|1932\u201333 tournament]]. Fred Keenor won his 32nd and final international cap in the game, earning praise for his performance. A goalless draw with England and a 4\u20131 victory over Ireland secured Wales' fifth Home Championship title.<ref name=\"s122123\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=122\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nWales travelled to [[Paris]], France, in May 1933 to play its first international fixture against an opponent other than the Home Nations. [[Thomas Griffiths (footballer, born 1906)|Tommy Griffiths]] scored Wales' goal during a 1\u20131 draw with [[France national football team|France]] at the [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]].<ref name=\"s122123\"/> Buoyed by their championship victory, the Welsh team began their title defense in the [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship]] by securing a 3\u20132 victory over Scotland in front of 40,000 fans at [[Ninian Park]]. A draw with Ireland in Belfast meant Wales required a victory over England to guarantee consecutive titles. The match was played at [[St James' Park]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] with Wales taking an early lead through [[Tommy Mills (footballer)|Tommy Mills]]. The tension of the match was so intense that Mills nearly failed to return for the second half having been sick during half-time. [[Eric Brook]] equalised for England in the second half but, with less than ten minutes remaining, [[Dai Astley]] scored a header to give Wales victory and win the Home Championship in consecutive years for the only time in the nation's history.<ref name=\"s124125\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1933-34/M0189Wal1933.html |title=England 1\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales failed to retain its title in [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship|1934\u201335]], finishing last, but narrowly missed out on another title in the [[1935\u201336 British Home Championship]]. Needing a win against Ireland to secure the championship, Wales went on to lose 3\u20132.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> The side recovered the following season and defeated England in a home fixture for the first time since 1882 via goals from [[Pat Glover]] and [[Seymour Morris]]. Glover again proved the match winner in Wales' second fixture, scoring both goals as the side defeated Scotland 2\u20131. Wales won its third title in five years by winning 4\u20131 over Ireland in its last fixture, Glover scoring two more to finish as top goalscorer with five goals in the competition.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=128\u2013129}}</ref> Wales also went on to share the [[1938\u201339 British Home Championship]] title with both England and Scotland after all three sides attained four points in the final edition of the tournament before the outbreak of the Second World War.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\n==Wartime and new overseas competition==\nThe British Home Championship was postponed during wartime; Wales' final fixture before the start of the war was a 2\u20131 defeat against France.<ref name=\"matches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal-intres.html |title=International matches of Wales |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Nyg\u00e5rd |first=Jostein |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> The side's first wartime fixture was a 1\u20131 draw with England in a charity match to raise money for the [[Red Cross]]. The following year, Wales were hosted at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] for the first time having previously been considered less of a draw than Scotland. Wales won the match 1\u20130 through a goal by [[Bryn Jones (footballer, born 1912)|Bryn Jones]].<ref name=\"s133135\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=133\u2013135}}</ref> For the majority of the war, Wales only played fixtures against England, the two sides met 15 times between 1939 and 1945. Wales final wartime matches were against Scotland and Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welshsoccerarchive.co.uk/index.php/internationals/wartime |title=Wartime Internationals |publisher=Welsh Football Data Archive |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> As the war drew to a close, the national side was rocked by the death of Ted Robbins in January 1946. Robbins had served as secretary of the FAW since 1909 and was credited as a major factor in the team's success in previous decades.<ref name=\"s133135\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS134824498&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS134824498&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Sport in Brief |newspaper=The Times |p=8 |date=18 January 1946 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John Charles, Wales versus Scotland, Ninian Park, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|[[John Charles]] (pictured in 1954) was one of Wales' most prominent players during the 1950s.]]\nThe British Home Championship returned for the [[1946\u201347 British Home Championship|1946\u201347 campaign]] and Wales' first competitive post-war fixture was against Scotland in October 1946.<ref name=\"matches\"/> The wartime gap had increased public appetite for the sport and the break resulted in an entirely new generation of players being involved in the squad. One of the debutants, [[Trevor Ford]], scored one of Wales' goals in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=43}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=136}}</ref> However, defeats to England and Northern Ireland resulted in a third-place finish during the first post-war championship.<ref name=\"bhc1940\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1947-66.html |title=British Home Championship 1947\u20131966 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales began its campaign with a 3\u20130 defeat against England but defeated Scotland at [[Hampden Park]] for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=138\u2013139}}</ref> A win over Northern Ireland left Wales leading the group with only one match to be played. In the final match, England defeated Scotland to claim the championship by a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> In 1949, the Wales national side embarked on its first overseas tour with matches against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. As all three opponents wore red shirts, the fixtures necessitated the first away kit in Wales' history. A yellow shirt with green collar and trim was adopted for the tour, featuring the [[Welsh Dragon]] on the pocket. The tour proved disastrous for the squad however, as Wales lost all three fixtures and the squad was involved in a road accident when the team coach crashed during a tour of the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nWales and the other Home Nations entered the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time in 1950 and the [[1949\u201350 British Home Championship]] was used to determine qualification for the tournament. The added incentive resulted in a crowd of more than 60,000 attending Wales' opening fixture against England at Ninian Park, but they witnessed their side suffer a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=146}}</ref> A further defeat to Scotland ended Wales' hopes of qualification and only a goalless draw with Northern Ireland stopped the side finishing bottom of the group on [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Prior to the Ireland match, Belgium had travelled to Cardiff to become the first overseas side to visit Wales for an international match. Trevor Ford scored a hat-trick during a 5\u20131 victory for Wales. Portugal and Switzerland also travelled to Wales in 1951, as Wales avenged its earlier defeats by winning both matches.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=148\u2013149}}</ref> During the following year's championship, Trevor Ford became Wales' leading goalscorer of all-time when he scored a brace during a 4\u20132 defeat to England. Having entered the match on ten goals, his double resulted in him overtaking Billy Meredith's tally of eleven.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/trevor-ford-37679/ |title=Trevor Ford Player Statistics |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Some sources credit [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] with twelve goals for Wales,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1946-60/1950-51/M0260Wal1950.html |title=England 4\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> but most contemporary sources only list him with 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/wales/tab/stats/option/scorers/ |title=Wales national football team statistics and records: top scorers |website=11v11.com |publisher=FAS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=12145 |title= Billy Lewis |website=eu-football.info |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Further breakdown can be viewed at [[Talk:Billy Lewis (footballer)]].|group=lower-alpha}}\n\nWales celebrated its 75th anniversary by winning its first post-war British Home Championship title by sharing the [[1951\u201352 British Home Championship]] edition with England.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=45}}</ref> The two sides had drawn their meeting in the first fixture before both won their remaining matches to finish on five points.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Wales' final match of the competition was a 3\u20130 victory over Northern Ireland at Vetch Field, the first international match held at the ground in 25 years. The Welsh squad contained several young players born or brought up in the Swansea area, including Ford, [[Ivor Allchurch]] and [[Roy Paul]], and the game was regarded as a homecoming match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=150}}</ref> Allchurch scored one of his side's goals in the match to finish tied as the competition's top goalscorer.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=47}}</ref> Wales struggled in the years immediately afterwards, finishing bottom of the Championship in consecutive seasons, including the [[1953\u201354 British Home Championship|1953\u201354 tournament]] which saw the team fail to qualify for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> The period also included a disastrous European tour in 1953 during which Wales suffered a 6\u20131 defeat to France and a 5\u20132 defeat to [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=153}}</ref>\n\n===Austria and The Battle of Wrexham===\n[[File:Trevor Ford (1959).jpg|thumb|right|[[Trevor Ford]], Wales' record goalscorer at one time and whose physical style of play was a reason for Austrian animosity]] \nIn 1954, encouraged by the work of [[Walter Winterbottom]] with England, the FAW appointed the first manager of the Welsh national side in former captain [[Walley Barnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"s155156\"/> His first match in charge of the side was a match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in [[Vienna]] which attracted 60,000 spectators. Despite winning 2\u20130, the Austrians were infuriated by the physical style of play adopted by Wales, particularly forwards Ford and [[Derek Tapscott]], which was unfamiliar outside Britain. The Austria captain [[Ernst Ocwirk]] described the match as \"the dirtiest game he'd ever seen.\"<ref name=\"s155156\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=155}}</ref> Yugoslavia travelled to Wales in September 1954 in a reverse of the two side's fixture in 1953 and became the first foreign opposition to win in Wales after winning 3\u20131, having trailed 1\u20130 at half-time.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=51}}</ref> Wales' burgeoning involvement in continental football resulted in the FAW being accepted as members of the recently founded [[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) in 1954.<ref name=\"s155156\"/>\n\nThe [[1955\u201356 British Home Championship]] brought some improvement for Wales as the side recorded its first victory over England in 17 years at Ninian Park. The period also saw the emergence of [[John Charles]] for the national side.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> Charles and his brother [[Mel Charles|Mel]] often played alongside another set of brothers, Ivor and [[Len Allchurch]], becoming the first sets of brothers to play for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=12}}</ref> John Charles quickly gained a reputation as the side's leading player, featuring as either a [[centre-half]] or [[centre-forward]], and his performance in the victory over England led ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' reporter Dewi Lewis to describe him as \"indeed the perfect footballer if ever there was one.\"<ref name=\"s157160\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=157\u2013160}}</ref> All four sides shared the British Home Championship title after finishing on three points, the only occurrence of a four-way tie in the competition's 100-year history. Wales narrowly missed out on winning the title having drawn 1\u20131 with Northern Ireland in its final game in which Roy Paul missed a penalty with Wales already leading 1\u20130. Ireland later equalised and the game ended as a tie.<ref name=\"s157160\"/>\n\nAt the end of 1955, Austria travelled to Wales a year after its 2\u20130 victory. The Austrian team were eager to match the physicality of the Welsh side shown in the first meeting and the match descended into violent chaos.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The French referee, Louis Fauquemberghe,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-austria-23-november-1955-226605/ |title=Wales v Austria 23 November 1955 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/louis-fauquembergue/1/1/ |title=Louis Fauquembergue |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> who was unable to speak either German or English had little control as both sides continually resorted to fouling each other resulting in injuries to eight players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1945_1985.htm |title=1945\u20131986 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The most serious were to Austria's [[Theodor Wagner]], who suffered a fractured tibia, and Wales' Mel Charles, who left the field with ten minutes remaining after being heavily fouled.<ref name=\"timesaustria\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS67851640&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67851640&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Rough International Match at Wrexham |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=24 November 1955 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Roy Paul later described the scene in the Welsh dressing room after the match in his autobiography, writing \"Our goalkeeper, [[Jack Kelsey]], had scars on both legs. Derek Tapscott [...] had a six-inch gash on his knee. [...] John Charles leaned over his brother Melvyn with tears in his eyes. Melvyn lay silent, still dazed by a tackle which had sent him crashing to the ground.\"<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The national media were highly critical after the match; the ''Western Mail'' described the match as \"a disgrace\",<ref name=\"s157160\"/> while ''[[The Times]]'' wrote \"there were times when the pitch resembled a battlefield, with players down here and there\".<ref name=\"timesaustria\"/>\n\n==1958 FIFA World Cup==\n===Qualification and build-up===\nDisappointing results against European teams prompted a change of approach by the FAW who appointed [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] coach [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] as manager in 1956. Murphy enjoyed an inauspicious start with draws with Northern Ireland and Scotland before a 3\u20131 defeat to England in a match where Wales finished with nine players due to injuries. The British Home Championship was dropped as a qualifying format for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] and replaced by randomly drawn [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying groups]]. Wales was drawn alongside [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] and started positively by defeating Czechoslovakia 1\u20130 in its first fixture, via a goal by [[Roy Vernon]]. Wales travelled to East Germany in its second game with a squad of only 12 players. John Charles became highly critical of the FAW's reluctance to travel with more than a bare minimum of players, later writing \"There were more selectors than players. It was crazy. You've got to put the players first but with Wales it was the selectors first and the players second.\"<ref name=\"s161163\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=161\u2013163}}</ref> Wales eventually suffered a 2\u20131 defeat to the largely amateur East Germans in the nation's first competitive fixture.<ref name=\"s161163\"/>\n\n[[File:The Israeli team playing against Wales at the Ramat Gan stadium, 1958 D448-079.jpg|thumb|left|Wales playing [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] match to qualify for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]]]]\nThe squad continued to Czechoslovakia but had lost three players to illness and injury. The FAW, however, were still reluctant to call-up replacements and only an outcry from the press prompted Ray Daniel and [[Des Palmer]] to join up with the side. Nevertheless, Wales lost the match 2\u20130 and made qualification unobtainable. In the final group match, Palmer scored a hat-trick to defeat East Germany 4\u20131.<ref name=\"s161163\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/58qual.html#gr4 |title=World Cup 1958 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> A second opportunity at qualification emerged in December 1957 as the volatile political situation in Israel led to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] withdrawing from matches against the nation for varying reasons. FIFA rules decreed that no team could qualify for a World Cup without playing a match, and so a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] against a European qualifying group runner-up was arranged. [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] was drawn first but also refused to play Israel leading to a second draw in which Wales was selected. The FAW accepted the offer and Wales travelled to [[Tel Aviv]] for the first leg, winning 2\u20130 after goals from Ivor Allchurch and [[Dave Bowen]].<ref name=\"s165166\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer |Stead|1998|p=89}}</ref> The result was the first time Wales had won an international fixture outside Britain.<ref name=\"58guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/01/wales-1958-world-cup-quarter-final-euro-2016 |title=Wales at the 1958 World Cup: a quarter-final run with a difference |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Burton |first=Simon |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> Allchurch scored again in the second leg and a further goal from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] secured Wales' first qualification to a major international tournament.<ref name=\"s165166\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=165\u2013166}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15584126.from-the-argus-archive-when-wales-qualified-for-the-world-cup-in-1958-by-beating-israel-at-ninian-park-in-cardiff/ |title=From the Argus archive: When Wales qualified for the World Cup - in 1958 by beating Israel at Ninian Park in Cardiff |newspaper=South Wales Argus |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales received a favourable draw for the group stage of the tournament, being placed alongside [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and hosts [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. The side's preparations for the tournament were hampered by confusion over the availability of John Charles; having failed to qualify, the [[Italian Football Federation]] had instead organised a club tournament featuring Charles' side [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] who were reluctant to release the player. Wales manager Jimmy Murphy prepared his team to play without Charles, but the player eventually secured his release and arrived in Sweden only three days before the start of the competition.<ref name=\"s167168\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=167\u2013168}}</ref> The side was further weakened by the omission of Trevor Ford, the nation's record goalscorer. Ford had been banned from playing in Britain in 1956 after he revealed an illegal payments scandal in club football in his autobiography. Despite continuing to play abroad, he was overlooked for selection.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/league-legend-ford-one-finest-2486582 |title=League legend Ford one of finest Wales players |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Derek Tapscott had also fallen out with the FAW while Des Palmer missed out due to injury, leading to [[Colin Webster]] being selected in their stead.<ref name=\"s172173\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=172\u2013173}}</ref> Wales played a single warm-up match prior to the start of the tournament, defeating local amateur side Soltsjobaden 19\u20130.<ref name=\"s167168\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=91}}</ref>\n\n===Tournament===\nWales' opening game of the tournament was against Hungary. Although the Hungarian [[Golden Team]] had previously been considered one of the best teams in the world, the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] had weakened the side.<ref name=\"58guardian\"/><ref name=\"s169171\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=169\u2013171}}</ref> Nevertheless, Hungary quickly took the lead in the opening five minutes through [[J\u00f3zsef Bozsik]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-hungary-08-june-1958-227115/ |title=Wales v Hungary, 08 June 1958 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> The Hungarian defensive efforts were largely focused on containing John Charles who received attention described as \"rugged tactics\" by ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS50944713&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944713&searchId=R6&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh Fire Earns a Draw |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=9 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Journalist Ian Wooldridge wrote that the Hungarian tactics were often \"Just inside or wildly outside the international laws of soccer\".<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Charles scored an equaliser for Wales after 27 minutes, heading in from a corner to secure a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> In its second match, Wales played a Mexico side that had suffered a 3\u20130 defeat to Sweden in its opening game. The Welsh side entered the game as favourites but struggled to gain the advantage over their opponents.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Ivor Allchurch gave Wales the lead in the first half but Mexico responded strongly and scored a late equaliser in the 89th minute with Wales having been reduced to 10-men after [[Colin Baker (Welsh footballer)|Colin Baker]] had been injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CCS235231948&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235231948&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Late Goal by Mexico Checks Faltering Wales |newspaper=The Times |p=14 |date=12 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn its final group match, Wales met Sweden which had already qualified for the quarter-finals and had rested several players as a result.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> The Swedes were still the stronger of the two teams but were unable to breach the Welsh defense and the match ended goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=5&docId=GALE%7CCS50944720&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944720&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Draw with Sweden |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales finished the group stage with three points, tied for second with Hungary necessitating a play-off match between the two sides to determine which would advance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS50551504&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50551504&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Three U.K. Teams in World Cup Play-offs |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales faced Hungary needing a victory; Hungary's superior goal difference meant a draw would see it advance. Wales were dealt a blow when [[Lajos Tichy]] gave Hungary the lead after 30 minutes while John Charles was again the focus of the Hungarian defence, leaving the field on more than one occasion to receive treatment. Charles though, proved pivotal as he set up Ivor Allchurch for Wales' equalising goal. [[Terry Medwin]] scored a second for Wales and, despite finishing the match with 10-men following an injury to [[Ron Hewitt (footballer, born 1928)|Ron Hewitt]], the side held on to advance to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"s169171\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CCS51337938&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS51337938&searchId=R10&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales to Meet Brazil |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=18 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=95}}</ref>\n\nWales met [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], the winners of [[1958 FIFA World Cup Group 4|group 4]], in the quarter-finals. Much of the build-up for Wales focused on John Charles' attempts to recover from injuries sustained against Hungary. Described by one reporter as having received \"the most tremendous battering I have ever seen administered to a soccer player\", Charles failed to recover in time and his place in the side was taken by Colin Webster. Charles' absence proved costly as several chances were spurned with [[Brian Glanville]] of ''The Times'' remarking \"Wales could have won because all sorts of very tempting centres were coming across the goal and John wasn't there to head them in.\"<ref name=\"s172173\"/> Brazil went on to win the match by a single goal, scored by [[Pel\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS252140244&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS252140244&searchId=R11&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales' Gallant Exit from World Cup |newspaper=The Times |p=15 |date=20 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Post World Cup decline==\n===World Cup generation fades===\nThe success of the Welsh team in the World Cup resulted in huge demand for tickets for the side's opening match of the [[1958\u201359 British Home Championship]] against Scotland. However, the capacity home crowd at Ninian Park were left disappointed as Wales suffered a 3\u20130 defeat. Draws against England and Northern Ireland in the final two games left Wales bottom of the Championship, less than a year after its World Cup exploits. The following year, the post World Cup interest in the team led to a crowd of 62,634 attending a match against England at Ninian Park, a new record crowd for Wales and a record attendance for the ground.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=174\u2013176}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/8007646.stm |title=Farewell Ninian Park |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Wales began the 1960s by meeting the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] for the first time. The FAW had been against the Irish split and had resisted any attempts for the two sides to play for several years (England had played the Republic for the first time some 14 years earlier). Goals from Cliff Jones and [[Phil Woosnam]] won the match for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=178}}</ref>\n\nA shared British Home Championship title in [[1959\u201360 British Home Championship]] and a positive finish to the following year's campaign had raised hopes of Wales qualifying for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref name=\"s179182\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=179\u2013182}}</ref> Wales was drawn in a group with [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and Austria, although Austria withdrew due to financial problems before the matches began.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/62q.html |title=World Cup 1962 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4uJdBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq=Austria+1962+World+cup&source=bl&ots=xw6zGVVbQp&sig=ACfU3U1qFO3zLhQlHcjET-yfjb-mcrttfg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmoS1jKznAhU7VxUIHQnQDAYQ6AEwHHoECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=Austria%201962%20World%20cup&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of the FIFA World Cup |last=Dunmore |first=Tom |publisher=Scarecrow Press |p=131 |year=2015 |isbn=9780810887435}}</ref> Wales met Spain for the first match with a depleted side, missing several players including John Charles and Cliff Jones. Spain won the first match 2\u20131 before the two sides drew 1\u20131 in the second match in [[Madrid]] with Ivor Allchurch scoring Wales' goal. The result subsequently eliminated Wales from qualifying for the World Cup.<ref name=\"s179182\"/> Wales was invited to tour South America in 1962, the first matches played by the team outside Europe. The side played two matches against reigning World Cup holders Brazil, losing both 3\u20131. The tour concluded with a 2\u20131 defeat to Mexico and the retirement of long-serving goalkeeper Jack Kelsey from international football.<ref name=\"s179182\"/>\n\nWales entered the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] for the first time in 1964 (the Home Nations had not entered the inaugural edition in [[1960 European Nations' Cup|1960]]). In the preliminary qualifying round, Wales were drawn against Hungary and suffered a demoralising 3\u20131 defeat in the first leg in Budapest. A 1\u20131 draw in the return leg resulted in the side's elimination at the first attempt.<ref name=\"s184185\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=184\u2013185}}</ref> In April 1964, manager Jimmy Murphy was forced to miss Wales' match against Northern Ireland after his wife was taken ill. Swansea Town manager [[Trevor Morris (footballer)|Trevor Morris]] was placed in charge as Wales suffered a 3\u20132 defeat. Murphy never took charge of another match for Wales, resigning later in the year due to commitments with his role at Manchester United. The FAW drew up a shortlist of Welsh candidates, which included former players Jack Kelsey, [[Ron Burgess (footballer)|Ron Burgess]] and [[Tommy Jones (footballer, born 1909)|Tommy Jones]]. The role was eventually given to another former player, Dave Bowen, who had captained the team at the 1958 World Cup. Bowen took the job alongside his role as manager of [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. His first match in charge ended in victory when two late goals from [[Ken Leek]] secured a 3\u20132 win over Scotland in the [[1964\u201365 British Home Championship]].<ref name=\"s186187\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=186\u2013187}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Swansea Town Football Club (20740154461).jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Allchurch]] retired in 1966 as both Wales' record appearance holder and joint record goalscorer.]]\nIn [[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying]] for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], Wales was drawn in a group alongside the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"66rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/66qual.html |title=World Cup 1966 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The campaign began poorly for Wales as it lost 1\u20130 to Denmark in [[Copenhagen]] before losing a controversial game against Greece in [[Athens]]. Welsh players Ken Leek and [[Wyn Davies]] were continually fouled which led to brawls between players breaking out on several occasions.<ref name=\"s188190\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=188\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS67463050&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67463050&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Lose to Greece |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=10 December 1964 |accessdate=1 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> The home crowd also made attempts to break onto the pitch to confront the Welsh players which led to clashes with local police. Wales would avenge the defeat five months later with a 4\u20131 victory over Greece at Ninian Park in the return fixture. Wales travelled to [[Moscow]] in May 1965, suffering a 2\u20131 defeat in John Charles' final international appearance.<ref name=\"s188190\"/>\n\nDave Bowen was unavailable to manage Wales in its opening match of the [[1965\u201366 British Home Championship]] due to club commitments. Ron Burgess took charge for the match, which ended in a goalless draw.<ref name=\"s188190\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=23}}</ref> Bowen returned for the return fixture against the Soviet Union in October 1965. His side recorded a surprise 2\u20131 victory over their previously unbeaten opponents,<ref name=\"s191\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=191}}</ref> the only match the Soviet Union failed to win during qualifying,<ref name=\"66rsssf\"/> via goals by Roy Vernon and Ivor Allchurch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-ussr-27-october-1965-229197/ |title=Wales v USSR, 27 October 1965 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The result was not enough to secure qualification however as, despite beating Denmark 4\u20132 in its final game, Wales finished as runners-up in the group behind the Soviets.<ref name=\"s191\"/> Having failed to qualify for the World Cup, Wales instead embarked on another tour of South America in May 1966, playing two matches against Brazil and one against [[Chile national football team|Chile]]. Ivor Allchurch made his final appearance for Wales in the 2\u20130 defeat to Chile in the final match of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=140}}</ref> He retired as Wales' record appearance holder with 68 caps, and tied with Trevor Ford as the nation's record goalscorer with 23.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\"/><ref name=\"s191\"/>\n\n===Late 1960s struggles===\nLike the early World Cups, the qualifying phase for [[UEFA Euro 1968]] used the British Home Championship as a qualification group for the tour, with the results of the [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]] and [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368]] editions being combined to determine which of the Home Nations would progress.<ref name=\"s192\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=192}}</ref> Wales began the stage with a 1\u20131 draw against Scotland in October 1966 but ultimately finished third in the 1966\u201367 season after losing heavily to England and recording a goalless draw with Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"bhc1967\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1967-84.html |title=British Home Championship 1967\u20131984 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> For the 1967\u201368 championship, Wales adopted an all-red kit for the first time in its history. The team fared little better, losing to England and Scotland before recording its only victory of the Euro 1968 qualifying campaign by beating Northern Ireland 2\u20130.<ref name=\"s192\"/>\n\nWales recorded a creditable 1\u20131 draw with [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]] in April 1969 ahead of the qualifying campaign for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]. However, the side was hampered by withdrawals and refusals to release players for matches. Wales' first match was against reigning European champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Dave Bowen was forced to name several reserve players in the line-up, although the team only lost to a single goal by [[Luigi Riva]]. The side travelled to West Germany to play a return friendly against the side, with Bowen only able to select 13 players for the trip. Nevertheless, Wales recorded a second 1\u20131 draw; [[Barrie Jones]] had given Wales the lead before [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] equalised late in the match. The qualifying campaign for the 1970 World Cup ended with two defeats to East Germany and another to Italy as Wales failed to gain a single point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html |title=World Cup 1970 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Wales also finished bottom of the [[1968\u201369 British Home Championship|last British Home Championship of the decade]] with a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/>\n\nWales' struggles during the 1960s were blamed on several factors. The refusal of clubs to release players for international duty or to not allow a player to travel until a day before the match often disrupted the team. In his book ''Red Dragons: The Story of Welsh Football'', Phil Stead writes that Dave Bowen often could \"not pick a side until the day of the game because he was never sure who would be available.\"<ref name=\"s195197\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=195\u2013197}}</ref> The final match of the 1970 World Cup qualification group against Italy was nearly forfeited as Wales struggled to name a squad. One player, Wrexham's teenage defender [[Gareth Davies (footballer, born 1949)|Gareth Davies]], was contacted in the early hours of the morning and travelled overnight to make the team's flight to [[Rome]].<ref name=\"s195197\"/> The organisation of the team by the FAW was also criticised. Goalkeeper [[Gary Sprake]] later remarked that \"the international set-up with Wales at this time was amateurish at best\". Sprake later admitted to feigning injury under the guidance of his club manager [[Don Revie]] in order to avoid selection with the national side.<ref name=\"s186187\"/> [[John Toshack]], who made his debut in 1969, made similar comments: \"The whole set-up was a bit of a shambles [...] some of the players with more fashionable clubs were not too concerned about turning up for the less glamorous games.\"<ref name=\"s186187\"/> An incident in 1969 drew considerable criticism of the FAW when it failed to book enough seats for the ten travelling Welsh players and the organisation's members. When none of the officials offered to give up their seat, the crew declared that the last person to board the craft, winger [[Gil Reece]], would have to disembark. A furious Reece was left at the airport and had to travel alone to [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] before crossing the border into East Germany.<ref name=\"s195197\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-greats-pay-tribute-gil-2458945 |title=Welsh greats pay tribute to Gil the Blade |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=23 December 2003 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Departure of Bowen and arrival of Smith==\nWales began the 1970s in a more positive fashion, sharing the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship]] with England and Scotland. Wales had drawn with both before defeating Northern Ireland. The success raised hopes of the team qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1972]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=200}}</ref> Wales were drawn in a group alongside Czechoslovakia, [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. The side began the campaign with a goalless draw against Romania before losing 3\u20131 to Czechoslovakia,<ref name=\"72rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html |title=European Championship 1972 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> having led 1\u20130 with 12 minutes remaining.<ref name=\"s201204\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=201\u2013204}}</ref> Wales recovered with home and away victories over Finland but lost its remaining games to finish third, failing to qualify.<ref name=\"72rsssf\"/> During Wales' home victory over Finland, [[Trevor Hockey]] became the first player to represent the nation under a new parentage rule allowing players to represent countries other than their birth nations.<ref name=\"s201204\"/> His father had been born in [[Abertillery]], thus qualifying him for Wales under the new ruling.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=83}}</ref>\n\nWales' fortunes dipped alarmingly in the immediate years afterwards; the side finished bottom of the British Home Championship in four consecutive seasons between 1971 and 1975, winning only one match.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/> The team did perform slightly better during qualifying for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] in which they were drawn against England and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]. Wales lost to England in its opening game, failing to score for a sixth consecutive match, but surprised many by holding England to a draw in the return fixture at Wembley Stadium having taken an early lead through John Toshack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html#gr5 |title=World Cup 1974 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"s207209\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=207\u2013209}}</ref> Wales met Poland in March 1973 and recorded a 2\u20130 victory through goals by Trevor Hockey and [[Leighton James]]. Hockey would turn villain shortly before half-time during the return match in [[Chorz\u00f3w]], becoming the first Welsh player to be sent-off.<ref name=\"s207209\"/> The match deteriorated further in the second half as both sides committed numerous fouls and several scuffles broke out between the sides. [[Terry Yorath]] commented that he felt \"your physical well being was at risk\" during the game, while ''The Times'' headline referred to the match as \"a night of delinquency\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS302217531&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS302217531&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales lose their place and good name on night of delinquency |newspaper=The Times |p=18 |date=27 September 1973 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> In 1974, the FAW decided that the Wales manager's job required a full-time occupant and offered Dave Bowen the position on a permanent full-time basis. Bowen however rejected the role, unwilling to leave his position with Northampton. The job was instead given to the FAW's head of coaching, Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=211}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 1976===\n\nSmith's first test was the qualifying stage for [[UEFA Euro 1976]] as Wales were drawn alongside Hungary, Austria and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]]. In the opening match, Wales took the lead through [[Arfon Griffiths]], but eventually lost 2\u20131 to Austria. Griffiths scored again in Wales' next two matches, a 2\u20130 win over Hungary and a 5\u20130 win over Luxembourg. The side continued its good form by becoming the first British side to win in Hungary since 1909, also inflicting Hungary's first competitive home defeat since 1959, winning 2\u20131 via goals by John Toshack and [[John Mahoney (footballer)|John Mahoney]].<ref name=\"s212214\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=212\u2013214}}</ref> A second victory over Luxembourg was also Gary Sprake's final international appearance. Despite having being considered Wales' first choice goalkeeper for nearly a decade, he finished his career with 37 caps, later remarking \"it was expected of you as a [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] player that you put the club first\".<ref name=\"s212214\"/> In the final match, Wales met Austria in Wrexham needing only a draw to guarantee progress to the final eight of the tournament.<ref name=\"s217218\"/> Arfon Griffiths scored the only goal of the match as Wales secured a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=73}}</ref> In March 1976, the national side celebrated its centenary year with a friendly against England at the Racecourse Ground, which ended in a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref name=\"s217218\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nFor the 1976 edition of the European Championships, the quarter-finals were played as two-legged ties with the winners advancing to the semi-finals to be held in Yugoslavia.{{#tag:ref|Yugoslavia's hosting of the finals was dependent on the side progressing to the semi-finals.<ref name=\"s220\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} Wales was drawn against the host nation for its quarter-final tie with the first leg being played in [[Zagreb]]. The Yugoslavians took the lead after only 45 seconds through [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]] before adding a second early in the second half to win 2\u20130.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/76e.html |title=European Championship 1976 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> The second-leg was billed as one of the biggest matches in Wales' history, and the FAW (which had grown increasingly short of funds) considered an offer to move the game to Wembley Stadium to maximise profit. The FAW board was split after a vote, leaving the decision in the hands of president Terry Squire who ultimately chose Ninian Park as the venue.<ref name=\"s220\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=220}}</ref>\n\nEast German referee [[Rudi Gl\u00f6ckner]] was appointed for the match, and was infuriated when the flag of his home nation was not raised before the game.<ref name=\"woyugo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |title=The astonishing story of the forgotten Welsh football giants and the day Ninian Park erupted into violent chaos |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Abbandonato |first=Paul |date=22 May 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080442/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |archive-date=13 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gl\u00f6ckner controversially awarded Yugoslavia a penalty in the first half and disallowed a goal for Wales in the second, as the increasingly-irate crowd made several attempts to enter the pitch. Missiles were aimed at Gl\u00f6ckner for the remainder of the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw and eliminated Wales from the competition. Violence flared again at the final whistle; Gl\u00f6ckner required a police escort from the pitch, Yugoslavia midfielder [[Jurica Jerkovi\u0107]] had a physical altercation with a Welsh fan who had run onto the pitch, and another Welsh fan was arrested after a corner flag, which had been thrown in anger at the referee, struck a policeman in the neck.<ref name=\"s220\"/><ref name=\"woyugo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/wales-and-the-forgotten-quarter-final-team-of-1976-a7112191.html |title=Wales vs Belgium Euro 2016: The Welsh and the forgotten 'quarter-final' team of 1976 |newspaper=The Independent |last=Moore |first=Glen |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> As a result of the scenes during the match, Wales was initially handed a two-year ban from international football, although this was reduced on appeal to a fine of 20,000 [[Swiss franc]]s and the limitation of home qualifying matches for [[UEFA Euro 1980]] being held at least {{convert|200|km}} from Cardiff.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=222}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific''' \n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography''' \n* {{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth M |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |publisher=Bridge Books |year=1991 |isbn=1872424112 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=Ivor Allchurch M.B.E. |first1=David |last1=Farmer |first2 = Peter |last2= Stead |publisher=Christopher Davies (Publishing) Ltd. |location=Swansea | year= 1998 | isbn=0-7154-0733-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |url=https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1386666/1421693/201#?xywh=159%2C-142%2C1738%2C3921&cv=201 |title=The Early Development of Association Football in South Wales, 1890\u20131906 |journal=Transactions of the Honourable Society of the Cymmrodorian |last1=Lile |first1=Brian |last2=Farmer |first2=David |year=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=James |last=Leighton |title=Fred Keenor \u2013 The Man Who Never Gave Up |year=2010 |publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company |location=Derby |isbn=9781859838280 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/fredkeenormanwho0000leig }}\n*{{citation |title=Red Dragons \u2013 The Story of Welsh Football |last1=Stead |first1=Phil |publisher=Y Llofa |year=2013 |location=Ceredigion |isbn=9781847714688 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Wales national football team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Wales National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Wales national football team| ]]\n[[Category:History of association football by national team|Wales]]\n", "name_user": "No Great Shaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNew century:edition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Wales_national_football_team_(1876%E2%80%931976)"}
{"title_page": "Mankumari Basu", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Mankumari Basu\n| image    = \n| image_size     =\n| caption  =  Mankumari Basu\n| birth_date   = 25 January 1863\n| birth_place  = Sagardanri [[Jessore  ]], [[Bengal Presidency]], now  [[Bangladesh]]   \n| death_date   = 26 December 1943 (Age 80)\n| death_place = [[Khulna]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| alma mater =  \n| occupation     = Poet and short story  writer \n| awards          =  [[Kuntanil Award]]<br/> [[Bhumanmohini Gold Medal]]<br/>[[Jagattarini Gold Medal]]\n|parents        = Anandamohan Dutta (Father)<br> Shantamoni Devi (Mother)\n|spouse  = Bidhushankar Basu (Husband)\n|children      = Priyabala\n}}\n\n'''Mankumari Basu  '''({{lang-bn| \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u0995\u09c1\u09ae\u09be\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09b8\u09c1}})( Born - 25 January, 1863 - Death - 26 December ,1943) a popular Bengali poet and short story writer. <ref name=\"Samsad\"> Samsad Bangla Charitabhidhan, edited Subodhchandra Sengupta & Anjali Bose, published Sahitya Samsad Kolkata First Edition , August 2016, Page 566 , {{ISBN|978-81-7955-135-6}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\n\nMankumar Basu was born on the 25 January 1863 at her maternal uncle's home in the village of Sridharpur in Jessore district. Her father was Anandamohan Dutta, and Michael Madhusudan Dutt was her uncle. Her paternal residence was at Sagardari in Jessore. In 1873, at the age of ten, she was married to Bidhushankar Basu, a son of Rashbehari Basu, a well known Deputy Magistrate and a student of Medical College.  She was widowed in 1882 at the age of nineteen with her only one female child Priyabala.\n\n==Works==\n\nAt the premature death of her husband, she started writing in his memory the poems, short stories, essays and novels.Many of her essays were written for  the necessity of female education and the eradication of social corruption and superstitions. She regularly contributed to the magazine called  'Bamabodhini.'\n\nMankumari\u2019s first poem, \u2018Purandarer Prati Indubela\u2019, written in blank verse and published in the sangbad prabhakar, shows, in theme and style, the explicit influence of Madhusudan. Her books of poems include Kusumanjali (1893), Kanakanjali (1896), and Birkumarbadh (1904). The basic themes of her poems include nature, society, history and nationalism. Priyaprasanga or Harano Pranay (1884), written in both prose and verse, is a remarkable piece of writing expressing her grief at the premature death of her husband.\nMankumari also wrote a number of stories and essays. Puratan Chhabi (1936) is a collection of her short stories. Her books of essays include Bangali Ramanider Grihadharma (1890) and Bibahita Striloker Kartabya. <ref>Banglapedia</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\nShe received several honours for her literary achievements, among them, the Kuntanil Award for her stories, 'Rajlakshmi', 'Adrista-Chakra' and 'Shobha', a scholarship by the Indian government (1919) till her death, the Bhumanmohini Gold Medal (1939) and the Jagattarini Gold Medal (1941) from Calcutta University. In 1937, she presided over the poetry session of Bangiya Sahitya Sammelan (Bengal Literary Conference) held in Chandannagar. <ref>Samsad</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nMankumar Basu died at the age of eighty at Khulna on the 26 December 1943.\n\n==Works==\n*''Kusumanjali (With The Floral bucket)'' (1893) \n*''Kanakanjali (With The Golden bucket)'' (1896)\n*''Priyaprasanga (About My Beloved)'' (1884)\n*''Harano Pranay (The Lost Love)'' (1884)\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite book |last=Ahmed |first=Wakil |year=2012 |chapter=Basu, Mankumari |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Basu,_Mankumari |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basu, Mankumari}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bengali female poets]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name   = Mankumari Basu\n| image    = \n| image_size     =\n| caption  =  Mankumari Basu\n| birth_date   = 25 January,  1863\n| birth_place  = Sagardanri [[Jessore  ]], [[Bengal Presidency]], now  [[Bangladesh]]   \n| death_date   = 26 December, 1943 (Age 80)\n| death_place = [[Khulna]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| alma mater =  \n| occupation     = Poet and short story  writer \n| awards          =  [[Kuntanil Award]]</br> [[Bhumanmohini Gold Medal]]</br>[[Jagattarini Gold Medal]]\n|parents        = Anandamohan Dutta (Father)<br> Shantamoni Devi (Mother)\n|spouse  = Bidhushankar Basu (Husband)\n|children      = Priyabala\n}}\n\n'''Mankumari Basu  '''({{lang-bn| \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u0995\u09c1\u09ae\u09be\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09b8\u09c1}})( Born - 25 January, 1863 - Death - 26 December ,1943) a popular Bengali poet and short story writer. <ref name=\"Samsad\"> Samsad Bangla Charitabhidhan, edited Subodhchandra Sengupta & Anjali Bose, published Sahitya Samsad Kolkata First Edition , August 2016, Page 566 , {ISBN|978-81-7955-135-6}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\n\nMankumar Basu was born on the 25 January 1863 at her maternal uncle's home in the village of Sridharpur in\u00a0Jessore\u00a0district. Her father was Anandamohan Dutta, and\u00a0Michael Madhusudan Dutt\u00a0was her uncle. Her paternal residence was at Sagardari in Jessore. In 1873, at the age of ten, she was married to Bidhushankar Basu, a son of Rashbehari Basu, a well known Deputy Magistrate and a student of Medical College.  She was widowed in 1882 at the age of nineteen with her only one female child Priyabala.\n\n==Works==\n\nAt the premature death of her husband, she started writing in his memory the poems, short stories, essays and novels.Many of her essays were written for  the necessity of female education and the eradication of social corruption and superstitions. She regularly contributed to the magazine called  'Bamabodhini.'\n\nMankumari\u2019s first poem, \u2018Purandarer Prati Indubela\u2019, written in blank verse and published in the\u00a0sangbad prabhakar, shows, in theme and style, the explicit influence of Madhusudan. Her books of poems include Kusumanjali (1893), Kanakanjali (1896), and Birkumarbadh (1904). The basic themes of her poems include nature, society, history and nationalism. Priyaprasanga or Harano Pranay (1884), written in both prose and verse, is a remarkable piece of writing expressing her grief at the premature death of her husband.\nMankumari also wrote a number of stories and essays. Puratan Chhabi (1936) is a collection of her short stories. Her books of essays include Bangali Ramanider Grihadharma (1890) and Bibahita Striloker Kartabya. <ref>Banglapedia</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\nShe received several honours for her literary achievements, among them, the Kuntanil Award for her stories, 'Rajlakshmi', 'Adrista-Chakra' and 'Shobha', a scholarship by the Indian government (1919) till her death, the Bhumanmohini Gold Medal (1939) and the Jagattarini Gold Medal (1941) from Calcutta University. In 1937, she presided over the poetry session of Bangiya Sahitya Sammelan (Bengal Literary Conference) held in Chandannagar. <ref>Samsad</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nMankumar Basu died at the age of eighty at Khulna on the 26 December 1943.\n\n==Works==\n*''Kusumanjali (With The Floral bucket)'' (1893) \n*''Kanakanjali (With The Golden bucket)'' (1896)\n*''Priyaprasanga (About My Beloved)'' (1884)\n*''Harano Pranay (The Lost Love)'' (1884)\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite book |last=Ahmed |first=Wakil |year=2012 |chapter=Basu, Mankumari |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Basu,_Mankumari |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\