{"title_page": "Murder of Ben Wilson", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''[[Ben Wilson (basketball)|Ben Wilson]]''', an American high school basketball star from [[Simeon Career Academy|Neal F. Simeon High School]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], USA, was shot in the neighborhood surrounding the school during its lunch hour on November 20, 1984. Wilson '''died from injuries sustained in the shooting''' the following morning.<ref name=\"SlamOnline November 2009\">{{cite magazine |title=Original Old School: Nuthin\u2019 But Love |url=http://www.slamonline.com/online/the-magazine/features/2009/11/original-old-school-nuthin-but-love |magazine=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |date=November 21, 2009 |last=Jackson |first=Scoop |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN October 2012\">{{cite web |title=Benji Wilson's ongoing journey |url=http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/8543190/scoop-jackson-benji-wilson-tragedy |publisher=[[ESPN.com|ESPN]] |last=Jackson |first=Scoop |date=October 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Hp4aNvgDT_UC&pg=PT217&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6AEwAHoECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false Chicken Soup for the Soul: Inside Basketball: 101 Great Hoop Stories from ..., By Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen, Pat Williams].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=sehsmCmHR5gC&pg=PA207&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6AEwAnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false The Great Book of Chicago Sports Lists, By Dan McNeil, Ed Sherman].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=T1pmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT26&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6wEwA3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false Derrick Rose, By Adam Woog].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nAt the time of the shooting, Wilson was seventeen years old and had just started his senior year at Simeon. As a junior, he had led the Simeon Wolverines basketball team to the Illinois Class AA state championship, and over the summer he was given the honor of being ranked as the best high school player in the entire nation.<ref name=\"PopMatters October 2012\">{{cite magazine |title='Benji' Revisits the Story of Chicago Basketball Star Ben Wilson |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164743-benji-remembers-chicago-basketball-star-ben-wilson/ |magazine=[[PopMatters]] |last=Fuchs |first=Cynthia |date=October 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Day of the shooting==\n===Domestic problem===\nIn addition to all of the accolades that were bestowed upon him, Wilson's life was also greatly affected by the fact that he had now become a father. Over the summer, his girlfriend Jetun Rush had given birth to a baby boy that the two named Brandon. For reasons unclear, Rush became withdrawn toward Wilson. While the two were still seeing each other, Rush had been avoiding Wilson and did not allow him to see his son. This greatly upset Wilson, who continued to try to figure out why Rush was acting in such a manner. So, as lunchtime came at Simeon on the 20th, Wilson elected to forgo eating with his teammates and instead wait for Rush.\n\n===Billy Moore and Omar Dixon arrive at Simeon===\nAs this was going on, two students from nearby [[Calumet High School (Chicago)|Calumet High School]], Billy Moore and Omar Dixon, had made their way to the school. Moore and Dixon had cut school that day, and Moore had a .22 caliber pistol in his possession. Moore's cousin had been robbed of $10, allegedly by a student of Simeon, and he brought the gun with him to avenge his cousin. The conflict, however, was resolved before Moore got there.\n\nThe two boys then decided to hang out for a little while and wait to see if Erica Murphy, Wilson's classmate and a friend of Moore's, was around. Murphy met up with the two boys shortly thereafter, and Moore and Dixon followed her to a luncheonette on South Vincennes Avenue. Murphy went in alone, while Moore and Dixon chose to wait. As they did so, Wilson and his girlfriend came walking up South Vincennes and, as before, Rush was avoiding him.\n\n===The shooting===\nIn his desperation to get Rush to talk to him, Wilson was unaware of his surroundings. He never saw Moore standing outside the luncheonette and bumped into him as he went up the street. Moore was not pleased and yelled up the street at Wilson to watch where he was going.<ref>[http://www.csnchicago.com/ben-wilsons-killer-i-dont-consider-myself-criminal \"Ben Wilson's killer: 'I don't consider myself a criminal' \"], ''CSN Chicago'', 21 Nov 2012.</ref>\n\nWilson, now angered, then turned and headed back toward Moore and a loud argument broke out. At one point, Moore drew the .22 from his pocket. This made Wilson madder and caused him to taunt Moore and dare him to fire. After Wilson lunged forward at him Moore, who would later say that Wilson was \"punking\" him\" pulled the trigger and fired off two rounds. The first struck Wilson in his groin while the second struck him in his abdomen and caused significant internal bleeding.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune October 1985\">{{cite news |title=Basketball Star's Slaying Described By Girlfriend |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-10-09/news/8503080823_1_ben-wilson-simeon-vocational-high-school-benjamin-wilson |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Myers |first=Linnet |date=October 9, 1985 |accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref> Moore and Dixon then fled the scene, with Moore heading straight for Murphy's house.\n\n==Aftermath of the shooting==\nAt 12:37 PM local time, a call was placed to 911 for emergency assistance. It took paramedics forty minutes to arrive at the scene, and to further complicate matters Chicago emergency protocol in place forced the ambulance to take Wilson to the closest available hospital. That hospital, St. Bernard Hospital in the [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] section, was not equipped to handle major trauma cases and thus Wilson was not able to be seen by a doctor for several hours. His condition progressively worsened during the hours that followed, which led his mother, Mary, to have her son taken off of life support. Early the next morning, November 21, Wilson died.<ref name=\"Wordpress August 2012\">{{cite web |title=Ben Wilson: A Life Cut Short but the Memories Remain |url=http://historyrat.wordpress.com/2012/08/19/ben-wilson/ |publisher=The History Rat|date=August 19, 2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes February 2003\">{{cite news |title=PRO BASKETBALL; A Dead Friend, a Living Memory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/14/sports/pro-basketball-a-dead-friend-a-living-memory.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Berkow |first=Ira |date=February 14, 1993 |accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests and trial==\nBilly Moore remained at Erica Murphy's home for most of the rest of the day. Later that night, Chicago police arrested him there and shortly thereafter apprehended Omar Dixon. The two boys were brought into interrogation rooms and questioned by detectives for most of the night, eventually signing confessions that they later recanted. Moore and Dixon were both charged with murder, and Cook County prosecutors elected to charge both of them as adults due to the nature of the crime.\n\nThe trial began in the fall of 1985. State Attorneys Kenneth Malatesta and Arthur Hill presided over the prosecution and presented the police's theory, which was in the confessions that were recanted: Moore pulled the gun on Wilson as Dixon tried to pick his pockets, and after Dixon robbed Wilson, he ordered Moore to shoot Wilson. The prosecution's lead witness was Jetun Rush, who testified to that effect. The prosecutors also tried to introuce evidence that the boys were members of a street gang, but were precluded from doing so.<ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-10-12-8503090624-story.html</ref>\n\nThe defense attorneys for both boys denied the charges vehemently. Dixon's attorney, Brian Dosch, called his client's confession \"garbage\" and destroyed a copy of it in front of reporters. Isaiah Gant, Moore's attorney, argued that his client was only trying to protect himself from the much larger Wilson. He also expressed that he felt both of the defendants were being \"railroaded\" by overzealous law enforcement officials whose desperation to hold someone accountable for the murder of a star athlete compromised their integrity and led them to create false case theory.\n\nMalatesta, in response to these charges, chose instead to focus on the actions that led to Wilson's death. In his closing on October 11, 1985, he urged the jury to focus less on the celebrity of the victim and simply follow the law. The jury was only out for about one hour before returning guilty verdicts against both Moore and Dixon.<ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-10-12-8503090624-story.html</ref> A month later, Moore was sentenced to 40 years in prison while Dixon received 30.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSimeon honored Wilson by retiring his number 25. However, the school still issues the number every year to the best player on the team.\n\nOmar Dixon was released on parole in 2000. In 2007 he was arrested again and charged with three weapons offenses, for which he began serving a 40-year sentence in 2011.<ref>https://www2.illinois.gov/idoc/Offender/pages/inmatesearch.aspx</ref> Billy Moore was paroled in 2005.\n\nThe life and murder of Ben Wilson has been featured in two documentary films produced in the 21st century. The first, directed by [[Coodie and Chike]] and produced in association with [[ESPN Films]], was titled ''[[Benji (2012 film)|Benji]]'' and made its debut at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. The most recent was first screened during the 2020 NBA All-Star Weekend in Chicago and was titled ''Two Sides of the Gun: A Story of Reconciliation''. I\nAt the screening, Billy Moore and Ben Wilson's brothers Anthony and Jeffrey appeared onstage together and the two Wilsons publicly forgave Moore for his action; this was the dying wish of Mary Wilson, who passed away at the age of 63 in December 2000.<ref>http://www.chicagonow.com/patriotic-dissenter/2020/02/new-details-emerge-surrounding-ben-wilson-death-as-family-forgives-killer/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sports]]\n[[Category:Chicago]]\n[[Category:1984 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[Ben Wilson (basketball)|Ben Wilson]]''', an American high school basketball star from [[Simeon Career Academy|Neal F. Simeon High School]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], USA, was shot in the neighborhood surrounding the school during its lunch hour on November 20, 1984. Wilson '''died from injuries sustained in the shooting''' the following morning.<ref name=\"SlamOnline November 2009\">{{cite magazine |title=Original Old School: Nuthin\u2019 But Love |url=http://www.slamonline.com/online/the-magazine/features/2009/11/original-old-school-nuthin-but-love |magazine=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |date=November 21, 2009 |last=Jackson |first=Scoop |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN October 2012\">{{cite web |title=Benji Wilson's ongoing journey |url=http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/8543190/scoop-jackson-benji-wilson-tragedy |publisher=[[ESPN.com|ESPN]] |last=Jackson |first=Scoop |date=October 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Hp4aNvgDT_UC&pg=PT217&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6AEwAHoECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false Chicken Soup for the Soul: Inside Basketball: 101 Great Hoop Stories from ..., By Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen, Pat Williams].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=sehsmCmHR5gC&pg=PA207&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6AEwAnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false The Great Book of Chicago Sports Lists, By Dan McNeil, Ed Sherman].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=T1pmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT26&dq=ben+wilson+simeon&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiy4_TNvdfmAhWHKs0KHfLtA4EQ6wEwA3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=ben%20wilson%20simeon&f=false Derrick Rose, By Adam Woog].Retrieved December 27, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nAt the time of the shooting, Wilson was seventeen years old and had just started his senior year at Simeon. As a junior, he had led the Simeon Wolverines basketball team to the Illinois Class AA state championship, and over the summer he was given the honor of being ranked as the best high school player in the entire nation.<ref name=\"PopMatters October 2012\">{{cite magazine |title='Benji' Revisits the Story of Chicago Basketball Star Ben Wilson |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164743-benji-remembers-chicago-basketball-star-ben-wilson/ |magazine=[[PopMatters]] |last=Fuchs |first=Cynthia |date=October 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Day of the shooting==\n===Domestic problem===\nIn addition to all of the accolades that were bestowed upon him, Wilson's life was also greatly affected by the fact that he had now become a father. Over the summer, his girlfriend Jetun Rush had given birth to a baby boy that the two named Brandon. For reasons unclear, Rush became withdrawn toward Wilson. While the two were still seeing each other, Rush had been avoiding Wilson and did not allow him to see his son. This greatly upset Wilson, who continued to try to figure out why Rush was acting in such a manner. So, as lunchtime came at Simeon on the 20th, Wilson elected to forgo eating with his teammates and instead wait for Rush. \n\n===Billy Moore and Omar Dixon arrive at Simeon===\nAs this was going on, two students from nearby [[Calumet High School (Chicago)|Calumet High School]], Billy Moore and Omar Dixon, had made their way to the school. Moore and Dixon had cut school that day, and Moore had a .22 caliber pistol in his possession. Moore's cousin had been robbed of $10, allegedly by a student of Simeon, and he brought the gun with him to avenge his cousin. The conflict, however, was resolved before Moore got there. \n\nThe two boys then decided to hang out for a little while and wait to see if Erica Murphy, Wilson's classmate and a friend of Moore's, was around. Murphy met up with the two boys shortly thereafter, and Moore and Dixon followed her to a luncheonette on South Vincennes Avenue. Murphy went in alone, while Moore and Dixon chose to wait. As they did so, Wilson and his girlfriend came walking up South Vincennes and, as before, Rush was avoiding him. \n\n===The shooting===\nIn his desperation to get Rush to talk to him, Wilson was unaware of his surroundings. He never saw Moore standing outside the luncheonette and bumped into him as he went up the street. Moore was not pleased and yelled up the street at Wilson to watch where he was going.<ref>[http://www.csnchicago.com/ben-wilsons-killer-i-dont-consider-myself-criminal \"Ben Wilson's killer: 'I don't consider myself a criminal' \"], ''CSN Chicago'', 21 Nov 2012.</ref>\n\nWilson, now angered, then turned and headed back toward Moore and a loud argument broke out. At one point, Moore drew the .22 from his pocket. This made Wilson madder and caused him to taunt Moore and dare him to fire. After Wilson lunged forward at him Moore, who would later say that Wilson was \"punking\" him\" pulled the trigger and fired off two rounds. The first struck Wilson in his groin while the second struck him in his abdomen and caused significant internal bleeding.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune October 1985\">{{cite news |title=Basketball Star's Slaying Described By Girlfriend |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-10-09/news/8503080823_1_ben-wilson-simeon-vocational-high-school-benjamin-wilson |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |last=Myers |first=Linnet |date=October 9, 1985 |accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref> Moore and Dixon then fled the scene, with Moore heading straight for Murphy's house.\n\n==Aftermath of the shooting==\nAt 12:37 PM local time, a call was placed to 911 for emergency assistance. It took paramedics forty minutes to arrive at the scene, and to further complicate matters Chicago emergency protocol in place forced the ambulance to take Wilson to the closest available hospital. That hospital, St. Bernard Hospital in the [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] section, was not equipped to handle major trauma cases and thus Wilson was not able to be seen by a doctor for several hours. His condition progressively worsened during the hours that followed, which led his mother, Mary, to have her son taken off of life support. Early the next morning, November 21, Wilson died.<ref name=\"Wordpress August 2012\">{{cite web |title=Ben Wilson: A Life Cut Short but the Memories Remain |url=http://historyrat.wordpress.com/2012/08/19/ben-wilson/ |publisher=The History Rat|date=August 19, 2012 |accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes February 2003\">{{cite news |title=PRO BASKETBALL; A Dead Friend, a Living Memory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/14/sports/pro-basketball-a-dead-friend-a-living-memory.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Berkow |first=Ira |date=February 14, 1993 |accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests and trial==\nBilly Moore remained at Erica Murphy's home for most of the rest of the day. Later that night, Chicago police arrested him there and shortly thereafter apprehended Omar Dixon. The two boys were brought into interrogation rooms and questioned by detectives for most of the night, eventually signing confessions that they later recanted. Moore and Dixon were both charged with murder, and Cook County prosecutors elected to charge both of them as adults due to the nature of the crime.\n\nThe trial began in the fall of 1985. State Attorneys Kenneth Malatesta and Arthur Hill presided over the prosecution and presented the police's theory, which was in the confessions that were recanted: Moore pulled the gun on Wilson as Dixon tried to pick his pockets, and after Dixon robbed Wilson, he ordered Moore to shoot Wilson. The prosecution's lead witness was Jetun Rush, who testified to that effect. The prosecutors also tried to introuce evidence that the boys were members of a street gang, but were precluded from doing so.<ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-10-12-8503090624-story.html</ref>\n\nThe defense attorneys for both boys denied the charges vehemently. Dixon's attorney, Brian Dosch, called his client's confession \"garbage\" and destroyed a copy of it in front of reporters. Isaiah Gant, Moore's attorney, argued that his client was only trying to protect himself from the much larger Wilson. He also expressed that he felt both of the defendants were being \"railroaded\" by overzealous law enforcement officials whose desperation to hold someone accountable for the murder of a star athlete compromised their integrity and led them to create false case theory. \n\nMalatesta, in response to these charges, chose instead to focus on the actions that led to Wilson's death. In his closing on October 11, 1985, he urged the jury to focus less on the celebrity of the victim and simply follow the law. The jury was only out for about one hour before returning guilty verdicts against both Moore and Dixon. <ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-10-12-8503090624-story.html</ref> A month later, Moore was sentenced to 40 years in prison while Dixon received 30.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSimeon honored Wilson by retiring his number 25. However, the school still issues the number every year to the best player on the team.\n\nOmar Dixon was released on parole in 2000. In 2007 he was arrested again and charged with three weapons offenses, for which he began serving a 40 year sentence in 2011.<ref>https://www2.illinois.gov/idoc/Offender/pages/inmatesearch.aspx</ref> Billy Moore was paroled in 2005.\n\nThe life and murder of Ben Wilson has been featured in two documentary films produced in the 21st century. The first, directed by [[Coodie and Chike]] and produced in association with [[ESPN Films]], was titled ''[[Benji (2012 film)|Benji]]'' and made its debut at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. The most recent was first screened during the 2020 NBA All-Star Weekend in Chicago and was titled ''Two Sides of the Gun: A Story of Reconciliation''. I\nAt the screening, Billy Moore and Ben Wilson's brothers Anthony and Jeffrey appeared onstage together and the two Wilsons publicly forgave Moore for his action; this was the dying wish of Mary Wilson, who passed away at the age of 63 in December 2000.<ref>http://www.chicagonow.com/patriotic-dissenter/2020/02/new-details-emerge-surrounding-ben-wilson-death-as-family-forgives-killer/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sports]]\n[[Category:Chicago]]\n[[Category:1984 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag,typo(s) fixed: 40 year \u2192 40-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Ben_Wilson"}
{"title_page": "1986 FIFA World Cup", "text_new": "{{redirect|1986 World Cup}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = FIFA World Cup\n| year = 1986\n| other_titles = Copa Mundial de F\u00fatbol M\u00e9xico '86\n| image = 1986 FIFA World Cup.svg\n| size = 175px\n| caption = 1986 FIFA World Cup official logo, designed by Rub\u00e9n Santiago Hern\u00e1ndez\n| country = Mexico\n| dates = 31 May \u2013 29 June\n| confederations = 5\n| num_teams = 24\n| venues = 12\n| cities = 11\n| champion = Argentina\n| count = 2\n| second = West Germany\n| third = France\n| fourth = Belgium\n| matches = 52\n| goals = 132\n| attendance = 2394031\n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Lineker]] (6 goals)\n| player = {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Diego Maradona]]\n| young_player = {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Enzo Scifo]]\n| fair_play = {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n| prevseason = [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]\n| nextseason = [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1986 FIFA World Cup''', the 13th [[FIFA World Cup]], was held in [[Mexico]] from 31 May to 29 June 1986.  The tournament was the second to feature a 24-team format.  With European nations not allowed to host after the previous World Cup in Spain, Colombia had been originally chosen to host the competition by [[FIFA]] but, largely due to economic reasons, was not able to do so and officially resigned in 1982.  Mexico was selected as the new host in May 1983, thus becoming the first country to host the World Cup more than once. This was the third FIFA World Cup tournament in succession that was hosted by a Spanish-speaking country, after Argentina 1978, and Spain 1982.\n\nIt was won by [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] (their second title, after winning in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]). Argentina was captained by the 25-year old [[Diego Maradona]], who played a large part in his team's success. Maradona scored the \"[[The hand of God|Hand of God]]\" goal, as well as another voted \"Goal of the Century\", in the [[Argentina v England (1986 FIFA World Cup quarter-final)|same quarter-final]] against England. These were two of the five goals that Maradona scored during the tournament, and he also created another five for his teammates.<ref name=Over>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/news/newsid=502188/index.html |title=1986 FIFA World Cup Mexico \u2013 Overview |work=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref> Argentina beat [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] 3\u20132 in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] at [[Mexico City]]'s [[Estadio Azteca]]. Total attendance was 2,394,031, an average per match of 46,039.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/worldcup/mexico1986/index.html |title=1986 FIFA World Cup Mexico |work=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n[[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] made their first appearances at the final stage.\n\nThe format of the competition changed from [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]. The final pair of matches in each group started at the same time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algeria.com/blog/the-game-that-changed-the-world-cup-algeria|title=The Game that Changed the World Cup&nbsp;\u2014 Algeria|work=algeria.com|accessdate=15 September 2009}}</ref> and the second round was played on a knock-out basis rather than groups. The 24 teams qualified were divided into six groups of four (A to F). The top two teams and the four best third-place finishers from the six groups advanced to the knockout round of 16 teams.\n[[Italy national football team|Italy]] were the defending champions, but were eliminated by [[France national football team|France]] in the Round of 16.\n\nThe 1986 World Cup saw the appearance of an audience phenomenon dubbed the [[Mexican wave]], which was popularised worldwide after featuring during the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who invented the Mexican Wave? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8742454.stm |accessdate=12 September 2018 |agency=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/168505,fan-crazes.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110173626/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/168505%2Cfan-crazes.aspx |archivedate=10 November 2013 |title=...Fan Crazes |first=Andy |last=Jackson |date=11 June 2010 |publisher=[[FourFourTwo (Australia)]] |accessdate=25 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/the-100-greatest-world-cup-moments-1915569.html?action=Gallery&ino=94 |title=The 100 greatest World Cup moments. # 94. The Mexican Wave |first=Simon |last=Rice |newspaper=The Independent |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Host selection ==\n[[File:1986 FIFA World Cup official Mascot.png|thumb|150px|Pique, the official mascot of the 1986 FIFA World Cup]]\n{{Main|FIFA World Cup hosts}}\n[[Colombia]] was originally chosen as [[FIFA World Cup hosts#1986 FIFA World Cup|hosts]] by [[FIFA]] in June 1974. However, the Colombian authorities eventually declared on 5 November 1982 that they could not afford to host the World Cup under the terms that FIFA demanded because of economic concerns.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pougatch|first=Mark|title=Three Lions Versus the World: England's World Cup Stories from the Men Who Were There|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcLeQJan_skC&pg=PT175|date=11 January 2011|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-907195-59-4|page=175}}</ref> [[Mexico]] was selected on 20 May 1983 as the replacement hosts, beating the bids of Canada and the United States (who eventually hosted the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]]), and thereby became the first nation to host two World Cups. This second World Cup in Mexico came 16 years after the first one in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]. A [[1985 Mexico City earthquake|severe earthquake]] in September 1985, eight months before the tournament, cast doubt over Mexico's ability to organize the event, but the stadia were not affected and it was decided to go ahead with the preparations.\n\nAs 1986 had been declared the International Year of Peace by the [[United Nations]], the advertising boards of all the stadia displayed the [[FIFA]] and [[United Nations]] logos along with the legend \"Football for Peace \u2013 Peace Year\".\n\nFor the design of the logo an unofficial motto was adopted:  \"El Mundo Unido por Un Bal\u00f3n\" (\"The World United by a Ball\").\n\n== Mascot ==\nThe [[FIFA World Cup mascots|official mascot]] of the 1986 World Cup was ''Pique'', a [[jalape\u00f1o]] pepper, characteristic of [[Mexican cuisine]], with a moustache, a Colimote [[sombrero]], and Mexican football team colours. Its name comes from ''picante'', Spanish for spicy, and was also a pun on the \"PK\" abbreviation of the football term [[penalty shot|penalty kick]].\n\nThe character caused a degree of controversy within Mexico for its ethnic stereotypes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Snyder|first=John|title=Soccer's Most Wanted\u2122: The Top 10 Book of Clumsy Keepers, Clever Crosses, and Outlandish Oddities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_fvyc3QC0TYC&pg=PA247|date=1 September 2001|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|isbn=978-1-57488-365-7|page=247}}</ref>\n\n== Qualification ==\n\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup qualification}}\nThree teams qualified for the World Cup for the first time: [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]]. Canada clinched its spot after winning the final match against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] 2\u20131 in [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]]. [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] played all their home matches on neutral ground because of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]].  South Korea qualified for the first time since 1954, Paraguay for the first time since 1958, Portugal for the first time since 1966 and Bulgaria and Uruguay for the first time since 1974. {{As of|2018}}, this was the last time that [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], Canada, Iraq and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] qualified for the finals. In addition, this was the last time that the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] did not qualify for the finals until the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] tournament.\n\n===List of qualified teams===\n\nThe following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.\n{{col begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|AFC]] (2)\n* {{fb|IRQ|1963}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|KOR|1984}}&nbsp;\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|CAF]] (2)\n* {{fb|ALG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|MAR}}&nbsp;\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|OFC]] (0)\n* ''None qualified''\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|CONCACAF]] (2)\n* {{fb|CAN}}&nbsp; \n* {{fb|MEX}}&nbsp;(hosts)\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|CONMEBOL]] (4)\n* {{fb|ARG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|BRA|1968}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|PAR|1954}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|URU}}&nbsp;\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|UEFA]] (14)\n* {{fb|BEL}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|BUL|1971}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|DEN}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ENG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|FRA}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|HPR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ITA|1946}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|NIR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|POL}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|POR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|SCO}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|SOV}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ESP}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|FRG}}&nbsp;\n\n{{col-4}}\n[[File:1986 world cup qualification.png|thumb|upright=1.5|{{legend|#000cff|Countries qualified for World Cup}} {{legend|#ffb400|Country did not qualify}} {{legend|black|Countries that did not enter World Cup}} {{legend|#ababab|Country not a FIFA member}}]]\n{{col end}}\n\n== Venues ==\nEleven cities hosted the tournament. The Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, the largest stadium used for the tournament, hosted nine matches (including the final), more than any other stadium used. Mexico City hosted 13 total matches; the Olimpico Universitario Stadium hosted four matches (if the Mexico City suburban town Nezahualcoyotl's 3 matches are included, this brings the total up to 16 matches; nearly a third of all matches in this tournament). Guadalajara, Mexico's second largest city hosted 10 total matches (the Jalisco Stadium hosted seven matches, the Tres de Marzo Stadium in Zapopan hosted three), Monterrey hosted 8 matches (The Tecnologico Stadium and the Universitario Stadium in San Nicolas de los Garza hosted four matches each), and the Cuauht\u00e9moc Stadium in [[Puebla]] hosted 5 matches.\n\nThe hot, humid and rainy summer weather in Mexico varied from humid desert locations like Monterrey to tropical locations such as Guadalajara; but perhaps the greatest hardship the players had to contend with was the high altitude of the Mexican locations. With the exception of the 93-104&nbsp;\u00b0F (34-40&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures of Monterrey (still 2,000 feet above sea level), all of the stadia were located in cities that varied anywhere from Guadalajara being {{convert|5138|ft}} above sea level to Toluca being {{convert|8730|ft}} above sea level, making conditions very difficult for the players running around in these stadia- but the higher the cities, the less intense the heat. Mexico City, the location of the final match and the location where the most matches were played was {{convert|7380|ft}} above sea level and the weather there was not as hot as in other cities used in this World Cup.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Mexico City]]\n! [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]]\n! [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n![[San Nicol\u00e1s de los Garza]]<br>{{small|(Monterrey area)}}\n|-\n| [[Estadio Azteca]]\n| [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]]\n| [[Estadio Jalisco]]\n| [[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]]\n|[[Estadio Universitario (UANL)|Estadio Universitario]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''114,600'''\n| Capacity: '''72,212'''\n| Capacity: '''66,193'''\n| Capacity: '''46,416'''\n|Capacity: '''43,780'''\n|-\n|[[File:Estadio Azteca, 2015.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio olimpico universitario unam.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio jalisco.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc.jpeg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Universitario Concachampions.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|-\n![[Santiago de Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]]\n! colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"4\" |{{Location map+|Mexico|places={{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.302911 |long=-99.150442 |label=<small>[[Mexico City]]</small>|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.681667 |long=-103.462778 |label=<small>[[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]]</small>|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=25.722806 |long=-100.312056 |label=<small>[[Monterrey]]</small> |position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.5875 |long=-100.392778 |label=<small>[[Quer\u00e9taro, Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]]</small>|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.0778 |long=-98.1644 |label=<small>[[Puebla]]</small>|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.2873 |long=-99.6667 |label=<small>[[Toluca]]</small>|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.6841 |long=-101.3563 |label=<small>[[Irapuato]]</small>|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=21.1155 |long=-101.6577 |label=<small>[[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]</small>|position=top}}|float=center|width=650|caption=}}\n![[Ciudad Nezahualc\u00f3yotl|Nezahualcoyotl]]<br>{{small|(Mexico City area)}}\n|-\n|[[Estadio La Corregidora]]\n|[[Estadio Neza 86]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''38,576'''\n|Capacity: '''34,536'''\n|-\n|[[File:Estadio la Corregidora.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Neza 86.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|-\n![[Monterrey]]\n![[Toluca]]\n![[Irapuato]]\n![[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]\n![[Zapopan, Jalisco|Zapopan]]<br>{{small|(Guadalajara area)}}\n|-\n|[[Estadio Tecnol\u00f3gico]]\n|[[Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez]]\n|[[Estadio Sergio Le\u00f3n Ch\u00e1vez]]\n|[[Estadio Nou Camp]]\n|[[Estadio Tres de Marzo]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''33,805'''\n| Capacity: '''32,612'''\n| Capacity: '''31,336'''\n| Capacity: '''30,531'''\n|Capacity: '''30,015'''\n|-\n|[[File:EstadioTecnologico.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Nemesio diez.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio SLC Irapuato.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Le\u00f3n (Nou Camp), Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato, M\u00e9xico -Imagen Actual- 2013-12-10 14-09.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Tecos stadium.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|}\n\nAll of these venues except Monterrey were located in central Mexico, as this tournament was organized with the then-standard way of keeping teams playing in locations in close proximity to each other. Group A only played at the Olimpico and in Puebla (except for the Bulgaria-Italy opening tournament match, which was played in the Azteca), Group B only played at the Azteca and in Toluca (hosts Mexico were part of this group; they played all their group stage matches at the Azteca), Group C played in Le\u00f3n and Irapuato, Group D only played in Guadalajara (including the Guadalajara area town of Zapopan; the last match of this group was played in Monterrey), Group E exclusively played in Quer\u00e9taro and Nezahualc\u00f3yotl, and Group F played in the northern city of Monterrey (including the Monterrey area town of San Nicolas de los Garza; the last match of this group was played in Guadalajara). All of the venues listed hosted knockout round matches except the ones in Nezahualcoyotl, Irapuato, Zapopan, Toluca and the Estadio Tecnologico in Monterrey.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Stadium\n!Matches\n!Teams hosted in the first round\n|-\n|Estadio Azteca||Opening match, Group B,<br /> R2, QF, SF, Final||'''{{fb|MEX}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario||Group A, R2||{{fb|ARG}}, {{fb|BUL|1971}}, {{fb|KOR|1984}}\n|-\n|Estadio 