n{{col-3}}\n;North and Central America\n* {{fbaicon|GUA}} [[R\u00f3mulo M\u00e9ndez]]\n* {{fbaicon|MEX}} [[Antonio M\u00e1rquez Ram\u00edrez]]\n* {{fbaicon|USA}} [[David Socha]]\n* {{fbaicon|CRC}} [[Berny Ulloa Morera]]\n\n;Oceania\n* {{fbaicon|AUS}} [[Chris Bambridge]]\n\n;South America\n* {{fbaicon|BRA|1968}} [[Romualdo Arppi Filho]]\n* {{fbaicon|COL}} [[Jes\u00fas D\u00edaz (football referee)|Jes\u00fas D\u00edaz]]\n* {{fbaicon|ARG}} [[Carlos Esp\u00f3sito]]\n* {{fbaicon|PAR|1954}} [[Gabriel Gonz\u00e1lez (referee)|Gabriel Gonz\u00e1lez Roa]]\n* {{fbaicon|URU}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Mart\u00ednez Baz\u00e1n]]\n* {{fbaicon|CHI}} [[Hern\u00e1n Silva]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Squads ==\nFor a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see ''[[1986 FIFA World Cup squads]]''.\n\n== Seeding ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=98%\n|-\n!width=25%| Pot 1\n!width=25%| Pot 2\n!width=25%| Pot 3\n!width=25%| Pot 4\n|-\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|MEX}} (hosts)\n* {{fb|ITA}} (1982 winners)\n* {{nowrap|{{fb|FRG}} (1982 runners-up)}}\n* {{fb|POL}} (1982 third place)\n* {{fb|FRA}} (1982 fourth place)\n* {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|ENG}}\n* {{fb|URS}}\n* {{fb|ARG}}\n* {{fb|ESP}}\n* {{fb|PAR|1954}}\n* {{fb|URU}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|ALG}}\n* {{fb|CAN}}\n* {{fb|DEN}}\n* {{fb|IRQ|1963}}\n* {{fb|MAR}}\n* {{fb|KOR|1984}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|BEL}}\n* {{fb|BUL|1971}}\n* {{fb|HPR}}\n* {{fb|NIR}}\n* {{fb|POR}}\n* {{fb|SCO}}\n|}\n\n== Summary ==\n[[File:1986 world cup.png|thumb|upright=1.9|Map of results {{col-start}} {{col-4}} {{legend|#2b42a3|Champion}} {{legend|#34c0be|Runner-up}}{{col-4}}  {{legend|#269c5a|Third place}} {{legend|#81c846|Fourth place}} {{col-4}} {{legend|#e4e454|Quarter-finals}} {{legend|#f4d4ac|Round of 16}} {{col-4}}{{legend|#b94954|Group stage}}{{col-end}}]]\n\n=== First round ===\n[[File:026549-018 FUTBOLEROS FESTEJANDO EN EL Z\u00d3CALO JUNIO 7 1986 (45398933914).jpg|thumb|Celebrations of Mexican fans at Zocalo main square, June 7, 1986.]]\nThe first round of the finals began in Group A, where [[Italy national football team|Italy]] were held 1\u20131 by [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]]. Meanwhile, [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] beat [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] 3\u20131, with [[Diego Maradona]] playing a major part. [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] drew 1\u20131, Maradona and [[Alessandro Altobelli]] scoring. South Korea and Bulgaria also drew 1\u20131 in a downpour. The final set of matches saw Argentina beating Bulgaria 2\u20130, and Italy narrowly defeating South Korea 3\u20132.\n\nIn Group B [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] beat [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] 2\u20131, and despite being held 1\u20131 by [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]], they won the group after a further win over [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]], 1\u20130. Paraguay and Belgium also progressed after both beating Iraq and drawing with each other.\n\nGroup C pitted a strong [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]-dominated [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] side against the reigning European champions [[France national football team|France]]. They drew with each other 1\u20131, with a goal scored by [[Vasyl Rats]]. France beat [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] 1\u20130 and finished in 2nd place in the group after beating [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], 3\u20130. Hungary had earlier lost 6\u20130 against the Soviet Union, which won the group due to goal difference.\n\nGroup D saw [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] start against [[Spain national football team|Spain]], winning 1\u20130 after the referee failed to validate a legal goal scored by [[M\u00edchel (footballer, born 1963)|M\u00edchel]]. [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] began their campaign with a draw against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]. Northern Ireland were then narrowly beaten by Spain before losing to Brazil 3\u20130 in their final match. This match saw a goal from [[Josimar]] on his debut and was also the final time [[Pat Jennings]] played for [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]]. Spain qualified along with Brazil after defeating Algeria 3\u20130.\n\n[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] stormed through Group E, dubbed the [[group of death]], with a 100 per cent record. They beat [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] 1\u20130 in their first game, then hammered [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 6\u20131, with [[Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen]] hitting a hat-trick. Denmark beat one of the favourites to win the tournament, [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Jesper Olsen]] penalty and a goal from [[John Eriksen]]. After losing to Denmark, Scotland took the lead against West Germany thanks to a [[Gordon Strachan]] goal, but the West Germans fought back to win 2\u20131. After a violent 0\u20130 draw against Uruguay, the Scots were eliminated from the tournament. During that game [[Jos\u00e9 Batista]] of Uruguay was [[misconduct (football)|sent off]] after less than one minute of play for a foul on Strachan, a [[FIFA World Cup records|World Cup record]] that still stands. West Germany went through to the second round despite a loss against Denmark.\n\n[[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] topped Group F after holding both [[Poland national football team|Poland]] and [[England national football team|England]] to goalless draws, and beating [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] 3\u20131. By doing so, they became the first African team, and only the second nation from outside Europe and the Americas (after North Korea in 1966), to reach the second round. England lost 1\u20130 to Portugal, followed by a 0\u20130 draw against Morocco in which they lost captain [[Bryan Robson]] to injury (for the remainder of the tournament) and vice-captain [[Ray Wilkins]] to a red card (he was never to be selected for England again, even after having served his obligatory one-match ban). In their last first-round game, with the captaincy taken over by [[Peter Shilton]] in goal, a first-half [[Gary Lineker]] hat-trick helped the reshaped side beat Poland 3\u20130 \u2013 although losing yet another player to a ban for the next round, Terry Fenwick receiving his second booking of the tournament. Poland had previously beaten Portugal, and in the end the Portuguese were the only team from Group F to be eliminated in the first round. Portugal, making their first appearance in 20 years, went on strike (in the [[Saltillo Affair]]) during the competition. Players refused to train between their first and second games (against England and Poland) and were eliminated after a loss to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in the final group match.\n\n=== Second round and quarter-finals ===\nBelgium beat the Soviet Union 4\u20133, despite a hat-trick by the Soviets' [[Igor Belanov]]. The game was level at 2\u20132 after 90 minutes, and in extra time [[Stephane Demol]] and [[Nico Claesen]] put Belgium 4\u20132 up. Belanov scored from the penalty spot with nine minutes remaining, but neither he nor any of his teammates could find a fourth goal for the Soviet Union. At the [[Estadio Olimpico Universitario|Olympic University Stadium]] in Mexico City, the European champions France ended Italy's reign as world champions with a 2\u20130 victory thanks to goals from [[Michel Platini]] and [[Yannick Stopyra]]. In the rematch of the [[1930 FIFA World Cup Final]], Argentina just edged out South American champions Uruguay in Puebla thanks to a 42nd-minute strike from [[Pedro Pasculli]]. The all-South American affair had a Diego Maradona's goal disallowed.\n\nIn Quer\u00e9taro, Denmark were eliminated as they went from a 1\u20130 lead to a 5\u20131 battering against Spain; key player [[Frank Arnesen]] was suspended for the game after being sent off against West Germany in their last group match, for taking a swipe at German playmaker [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]]. The Danes scored first, with a Jesper Olsen penalty, but they were then taken apart by a devastating performance from [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o|Butrague\u00f1o]] of Spain, who scored four of his team's five goals. At the [[Estadio Azteca|Azteca Stadium]] in Mexico City, England progressed to the quarter-finals comfortably when they saw off Paraguay 3\u20130, while Brazil brushed aside Poland 4\u20130. West Germany had a much harder time getting past Morocco, for whom goalkeeper [[Badou Zaki]] had an outstanding game. Morocco held out until the 87th minute, when Lothar Matth\u00e4us scored the only goal of the match with a free kick. Mexico won 2\u20130 against Bulgaria with an outstanding scissor-kick goal by [[Manuel Negrete Arias|Manuel Negrete]] which is honored by a remembrance plaque at [[Estadio Azteca|the Azteca]].\n\nIn the quarter-finals, France faced three-time world champion Brazil in Guadalajara. Brazil were well on top in the early stages, and Careca put them one up after 18 minutes. Five minutes before half-time, France drew level when Michel Platini scored his 41st goal after converting a cross from [[Dominique Rocheteau]]. Brazil had a chance to regain the lead in the second half when Branco was fouled by French keeper [[Jo\u00ebl Bats]] in the penalty area. [[Zico]] got up to take the kick, but Bats saved Zico's penalty.\n\nThe match went to extra time, and France finished slightly the stronger of the two sides. No more goals were scored, and so it was time for a penalty shoot-out. Socrates, who had earlier missed an open goal and headed an easy chance straight into the French keeper's arms, failed with the first kick for Brazil. The next six penalties were all converted, and then Platini fired over the bar. Brazil were back on level terms \u2013 but not for long. [[J\u00falio C\u00e9sar da Silva|Julio Cesar]] struck the post with his penalty, and [[Luis Fern\u00e1ndez]] then scored to put France through 4\u20133 on penalties.\n\nTwo other quarter-finals were also decided on penalties. [[Jan Ceulemans]] put Belgium ahead against Spain in the 35th minute, but Spanish substitute Se\u00f1or equalised with five minutes to go. No more goals were scored in extra time, and Belgium won the shoot-out 5\u20134. West Germany and Mexico drew 0\u20130 after extra time, and the West Germans eliminated the hosts 4\u20131 on penalties. As a curiosity, the German goalkeeper [[Harald Schumacher]] jumped to the right in the three Mexican penalties (stopping two of them).\n\nThe quarter-final between Argentina and England at the Azteca featured two very different goals in the second half by Diego Maradona: the first was scored illegally, as he punched the ball into the goal past England goalkeeper [[Peter Shilton]]. The referee did not see the handball and the goal was given as valid. After the game, Maradona claimed the goal was scored \"A bit with the head of Maradona and another bit with the hand of God\"; it became known as the \"[[The hand of God|Hand of God]]\" goal. For his second goal, voted \"[[Goal of the Century]]\" in 2002 on the FIFA website, Maradona dribbled half the length of the field past five English players before scoring. With 20 minutes to go, the introduction of John Barnes as a substitute changed the tide of play in England's favour, as he pinged cross after cross into the Argentine penalty area: with 9 minutes to go, Lineker got on the end of one and scored, then almost repeated the dose six minutes later but was just unable to reach the ball thanks to a timely block by Olarticoechea: 2\u20131 to Argentina was the final score. In Argentina, the game was seen as revenge for the [[Falklands War]].<ref>El Diego \u2013 Diego Maradona, Page 127, {{ISBN|0-224-07190-4}}</ref>\n\n=== Semi-finals, third-place match, and final ===\nIn the first semi-final match, [[Andreas Brehme]] put West Germany 1\u20130 ahead against France in the ninth minute in Guadalajara, but the outcome remained in doubt until two minutes from time when [[Rudi V\u00f6ller]] made it 2\u20130, and West Germany were in the final for the second World Cup in succession. In the second semi-final match, Maradona struck twice in the second half as Argentina beat Belgium 2\u20130 at the Azteca. France went on to defeat Belgium in the third-place match, 4\u20132.\n\nSo it was to be the South American Argentina vs the European West Germany at the final at the Azteca, the second time this massive stadium would host a World Cup Final ([[1970 FIFA World Cup Final|the first]] in 1970). [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Brown|Jose Brown]] put Argentina one up midway through the first half of the final, and when [[Jorge Valdano]] scored a second for the South Americans in the 55th minute, Argentina looked to be strolling to victory. West Germany then staged a spirited comeback. [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]] pulled one back in the 74th minute, and six minutes later Rudi V\u00f6ller hit the equaliser. With seven minutes remaining, a pass from Maradona gave [[Jorge Burruchaga]] the chance to score the winner for Argentina. Eight years on from their [[1978 FIFA World Cup|home triumph]], Argentina regained the world title and 30 million people in Argentina celebrated in the streets after the final victory. Maradona was the Golden Ball winner as the best player of the tournament, while Gary Lineker of England won the Golden Boot as the leading scorer of the World Cup with six goals.\n\n== Results ==\n''All times are [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] ([[UTC\u221206:00|UTC\u22126]])''\n\n=== Group stage ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colours in group tables\n|-\n|bgcolor=#ccffcc style=\"width: 20px;\"|\n|align=left|Group winners, runners-up, and [[#Ranking of third-placed teams|best four third-placed teams]] advance to the [[#Round of 16|Round of 16]]\n|}\n\n==== Group A ====\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup Group A}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup group tables|Group A}}\nSouth Korea made their first appearance since 1954. They managed to score their first goal (against Argentina) and their first draw (against Bulgaria).\n{| style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|31 May 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|BUL|1971}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Bulgaria vs Italy|1\u20131]]||{{fb|ITA}}||[[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|2 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ARG}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Argentina vs South Korea|3\u20131]]||{{fb|KOR|1984}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|5 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ITA}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Italy vs Argentina|1\u20131]]||{{fb|ARG}}||[[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]], [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|KOR|1984}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#South Korea vs Bulgaria|1\u20131]]||{{fb|BUL|1971}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|10 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|KOR|1984}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#South Korea vs Italy|2\u20133]]||{{fb|ITA}}||[[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]], [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ARG}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Argentina vs Bulgaria|2\u20130]]||{{fb|BUL|1971}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|}\n\n==== Group B ====\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup Group B}}\n[[File:Cruz vs cabanas.jpg|thumb|right|[[Francisco Javier Cruz|Cruz]] and [[Roberto Caba\u00f1as|Caba\u00f1as]] going for the ball in Mexico v Paraguay]]\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup group tables|Group B}}\n{| style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|3 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|BEL}