0e1szl\u00f3 Dajka]] (against the Soviet Union)\n* {{flagicon|KOR|1984}} [[Cho Kwang-rae]] (against Italy)\n\n== Red cards ==\nEight players received a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]] during the tournament:\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Mike Sweeney (soccer)|Mike Sweeney]]<ref name=\"PWC HUN CAN\">{{cite web|title=HUNGARY \u2013 CANADA|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupc_hun_v_can.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=19 December 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Frank Arnesen]]<ref>{{cite web|title=DENMARK \u2013 WEST GERMANY|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupe_den_v_ger.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ray Wilkins]]<ref>{{cite web|title=ENGLAND \u2013 MOROCCO|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupf_eng_v_mor.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|FRG}} [[Thomas Berthold]]<ref name=\"PWC FRG MEX\">{{cite web|title=WEST GERMANY \u2013 MEXICO|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/qf_ger_v_mex.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|IRQ|1963}} [[Basil Gorgis]]<ref>{{cite web|title=IRAQ \u2013 BELGIUM|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupb_irq_v_bel.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Javier Aguirre]]<ref name=\"PWC FRG MEX\" />\n* {{flagicon|URU}} [[Jos\u00e9 Batista]]<ref>{{cite web|title=SCOTLAND \u2013 URUGUAY|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupe_sco_v_uru.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|URU}} [[Miguel Bossio]]<ref>{{cite web|title=DENMARK \u2013 URUGUAY|url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1986/groupe_den_v_uru.html|work=Planet World Cup|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== FIFA retrospective ranking ==\nIn 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/00/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part4_279.pdf Argentina's Road to the World Title] FIFA.com. page 45</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mencompwc/51/97/55/171012-statisticalkit-fifaworldcup-milestonesfactsfigures-statusafterfwc2010.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521092116/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mencompwc/51/97/55/171012-statisticalkit-fifaworldcup-milestonesfactsfigures-statusafterfwc2010.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2013 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |title=FIFA World Cup: Milestones, facts & figures. Statistical Kit 7 |date=26 March 2013}}</ref> The rankings for the 1986 tournament were as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=25| {{abbr|R|Final Ranking}}\n!width=165| Team\n!width=25| {{abbr|G|Group}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|P|Played}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|W|Win}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|D|Draw}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|L|Lose}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|GF|Goals For}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|GD|Goal Difference}}\n!width=25| {{abbr|Pts.|Points}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:gold;\"\n| 1 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ARG}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 7 || 6 || 1 || 0 || 14 || 5 || +9 || 13\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| 2 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|FRG}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group E|E]] || 7 || 3 || 2 || 2 || 8 || 7 || +1 || 8\n|- style=\"background:#c96;\"\n| 3 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|FRA}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C|C]] || 7 || 4 || 2 || 1 || 12 || 6 || +6 || 10\n|- style=\"background:gray;\"\n| 4 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|BEL}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B|B]] || 7 || 2 || 2 || 3 || 12 || 15 || \u22123 || 6\n|-\n| colspan=\"11\"| '''Eliminated in the quarter-finals'''\n|-\n| 5 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|BRA|1968}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group D|D]] || 5 || 4 || 1 || 0 || 10 || 1 || +9 || 9\n|-\n| 6 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|MEX}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B|B]] || 5 || 3 || 2 || 0 || 6 || 2 || +4 || 8\n|-\n| 7 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ESP}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group D|D]] || 5 || 3 || 1 || 1 || 11 || 4 || +7 || 7\n|-\n| 8 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ENG}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group F|F]] || 5 || 2 || 1 || 2 || 7 || 3 || +4 || 5\n|-\n| colspan=\"11\"| '''Eliminated in the round of 16'''\n|-\n| 9 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|DEN}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group E|E]] || 4 || 3 || 0 || 1 || 10 || 6 || +4 || 6\n|-\n| 10 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|URS}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C|C]] || 4 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 12 || 5 || +7 || 5\n|-\n| 11 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|MAR}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group F|F]] || 4 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 3 || 2 || +1 || 4\n|-\n| 12 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ITA}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 4 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 5 || 6 || \u22121 || 4\n|-\n| 13 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|PAR|1954}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B|B]] || 4 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 4 || 6 || \u22122 || 4\n|-\n| 14 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|POL}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group F|F]] || 4 || 1 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 7 || \u22126 || 3\n|-\n| 15 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|BUL|1971}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 4 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 2 || 6 || \u22124 || 2\n|-\n| 16 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|URU}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group E|E]] || 4 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 2 || 8 || \u22126 || 2\n|-\n| colspan=\"11\"| '''Eliminated in the group stage'''\n|-\n| 17 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|POR}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group F|F]] || 3 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 4 || \u22122 || 2\n|-\n| 18 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|HPR}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C|C]] || 3 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 9 || \u22127 || 2\n|-\n| 19 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|SCO}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group E|E]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 3 || \u22122 || 1\n|-\n| 20 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|KOR|1984}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 4 || 7 || \u22123 || 1\n|-\n| 21 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|NIR}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group D|D]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 2 || 6 || \u22124 || 1\n|-\n| 22 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ALG}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group D|D]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 5 || \u22124 || 1\n|-\n| 23 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|IRQ|1963}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B|B]] || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 1 || 4 || \u22123 || 0\n|-\n| 24 || style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|CAN}} || [[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C|C]] || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 5 || \u22125 || 0\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|1986 FIFA World Cup}}\n* [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/mexico1986/index.html 1986 FIFA World Cup Mexico \u2122], FIFA.com\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tables/86full.html 1986 World Cup Details RSSSF]\n* [https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/08/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part1_283.pdf FIFA Technical Report (Part 1)], [https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/06/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part2_281.pdf (Part 2)], [https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/03/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part3_280.pdf (Part 3)] and [https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/00/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part4_279.pdf (Part 4)]\n\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Mexico}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup finalists}}\n{{FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:1985\u201386 in Mexican football]]\n[[Category:1986 in association football|World Cup]]\n[[Category:May 1986 sports events in North America]]\n[[Category:June 1986 sports events in North America]]\n[[Category:May 1986 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:June 1986 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup tournaments]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|1986 World Cup}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = FIFA World Cup\n| year = 1986\n| other_titles = Copa Mundial de F\u00fatbol M\u00e9xico '86\n| image = 1986 FIFA World Cup.svg\n| size = 175px\n| caption = 1986 FIFA World Cup official logo, designed by Rub\u00e9n Santiago Hern\u00e1ndez\n| country = Mexico\n| dates = 31 May \u2013 29 June\n| confederations = 5\n| num_teams = 24\n| venues = 12\n| cities = 11\n| champion = Argentina\n| count = 2\n| second = West Germany\n| third = France\n| fourth = Belgium\n| matches = 52\n| goals = 132\n| attendance = 2394031\n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Gary Lineker]] (6 goals)\n| player = {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Diego Maradona]]\n| young_player = {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Enzo Scifo]]\n| fair_play = {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n| prevseason = [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]\n| nextseason = [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1986 FIFA World Cup''', the 13th [[FIFA World Cup]], was held in [[Mexico]] from 31 May to 29 June 1986.  The tournament was the second to feature a 24-team format.  With European nations not allowed to host after the previous World Cup in Spain, Colombia had been originally chosen to host the competition by [[FIFA]] but, largely due to economic reasons, was not able to do so and officially resigned in 1982.  Mexico was selected as the new host in May 1983, thus becoming the first country to host the World Cup more than once. This was the third FIFA World Cup tournament in succession that was hosted by a Spanish-speaking country, after Argentina 1978, and Spain 1982.\n\nIt was won by [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] (their second title, after winning in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]). Argentina was captained by the 25-year old [[Diego Maradona]], who played a large part in his team's success. Maradona scored the \"[[The hand of God|Hand of God]]\" goal, as well as another voted \"Goal of the Century\", in the [[Argentina v England (1986 FIFA World Cup quarter-final)|same quarter-final]] against England. These were two of the five goals that Maradona scored during the tournament, and he also created another five for his teammates.<ref name=Over>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/news/newsid=502188/index.html |title=1986 FIFA World Cup Mexico \u2013 Overview |work=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref> Argentina beat [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] 3\u20132 in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] at [[Mexico City]]'s [[Estadio Azteca]]. Total attendance was 2,394,031, an average per match of 46,039.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/worldcup/mexico1986/index.html |title=1986 FIFA World Cup Mexico |work=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n[[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] made their first appearances at the final stage.\n\nThe format of the competition changed from [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]. The final pair of matches in each group started at the same time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algeria.com/blog/the-game-that-changed-the-world-cup-algeria|title=The Game that Changed the World Cup&nbsp;\u2014 Algeria|work=algeria.com|accessdate=15 September 2009}}</ref> and the second round was played on a knock-out basis rather than groups. The 24 teams qualified were divided into six groups of four (A to F). The top two teams and the four best third-place finishers from the six groups advanced to the knockout round of 16 teams.\n[[Italy national football team|Italy]] were the defending champions, but were eliminated by [[France national football team|France]] in the Round of 16.\n\nThe 1986 World Cup saw the appearance of an audience phenomenon dubbed the [[Mexican wave]], which was popularised worldwide after featuring during the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who invented the Mexican Wave? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8742454.stm |accessdate=12 September 2018 |agency=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/168505,fan-crazes.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110173626/http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/168505%2Cfan-crazes.aspx |archivedate=10 November 2013 |title=...Fan Crazes |first=Andy |last=Jackson |date=11 June 2010 |publisher=[[FourFourTwo (Australia)]] |accessdate=25 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/the-100-greatest-world-cup-moments-1915569.html?action=Gallery&ino=94 |title=The 100 greatest World Cup moments. # 94. The Mexican Wave |first=Simon |last=Rice |newspaper=The Independent |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Host selection ==\n[[File:1986 FIFA World Cup official Mascot.png|thumb|150px|Pique, the official mascot of the 1986 FIFA World Cup]]\n{{Main|FIFA World Cup hosts}}\n[[Colombia]] was originally chosen as [[FIFA World Cup hosts#1986 FIFA World Cup|hosts]] by [[FIFA]] in June 1974. However, the Colombian authorities eventually declared on 5 November 1982 that they could not afford to host the World Cup under the terms that FIFA demanded because of economic concerns.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pougatch|first=Mark|title=Three Lions Versus the World: England's World Cup Stories from the Men Who Were There|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcLeQJan_skC&pg=PT175|date=11 January 2011|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-907195-59-4|page=175}}</ref> [[Mexico]] was selected on 20 May 1983 as the replacement hosts, beating the bids of Canada and the United States (who eventually hosted the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]]), and thereby became the first nation to host two World Cups. This second World Cup in Mexico came 16 years after the first one in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]. A [[1985 Mexico City earthquake|severe earthquake]] in September 1985, eight months before the tournament, cast doubt over Mexico's ability to organize the event, but the stadia were not affected and it was decided to go ahead with the preparations.\n\nAs 1986 had been declared the International Year of Peace by the [[United Nations]], the advertising boards of all the stadia displayed the [[FIFA]] and [[United Nations]] logos along with the legend \"Football for Peace \u2013 Peace Year\".\n\nFor the design of the logo an unofficial motto was adopted:  \"El Mundo Unido por Un Bal\u00f3n\" (\"The World United by a Ball\").\n\n== Mascot ==\nThe [[FIFA World Cup mascots|official mascot]] of the 1986 World Cup was ''Pique'', a [[jalape\u00f1o]] pepper, characteristic of [[Mexican cuisine]], with a moustache, a Colimote [[sombrero]], and Mexican football team colours. Its name comes from ''picante'', Spanish for spicy, and was also a pun on the \"PK\" abbreviation of the football term [[penalty shot|penalty kick]].\n\nThe character caused a degree of controversy within Mexico for its ethnic stereotypes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Snyder|first=John|title=Soccer's Most Wanted\u2122: The Top 10 Book of Clumsy Keepers, Clever Crosses, and Outlandish Oddities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_fvyc3QC0TYC&pg=PA247|date=1 September 2001|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|isbn=978-1-57488-365-7|page=247}}</ref>\n\n== Qualification ==\n\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup qualification}}\nThree teams qualified for the World Cup for the first time: [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]]. Canada clinched its spot after winning the final match against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] 2\u20131 in [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]]. [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] played all their home matches on neutral ground because of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]].  South Korea qualified for the first time since 1954, Paraguay for the first time since 1958, Portugal for the first time since 1966 and Bulgaria and Uruguay for the first time since 1974. {{As of|2018}}, this was the last time that [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], Canada, Iraq and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] qualified for the finals. In addition, this was the last time that the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] did not qualify for the finals until the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] tournament.\n\n===List of qualified teams===\n\nThe following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.\n{{col begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|AFC]] (2)\n* {{fb|IRQ|1963}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|KOR|1984}}&nbsp;\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|CAF]] (2)\n* {{fb|ALG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|MAR}}&nbsp;\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|OFC]] (0)\n* ''None qualified''\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|CONCACAF]] (2)\n* {{fb|CAN}}&nbsp; \n* {{fb|MEX}}&nbsp;(hosts)\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|CONMEBOL]] (4)\n* {{fb|ARG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|BRA|1968}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|PAR|1954}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|URU}}&nbsp;\n{{col-4}}\n;[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|UEFA]] (14)\n* {{fb|BEL}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|BUL|1971}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|DEN}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ENG}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|FRA}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|HPR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ITA|1946}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|NIR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|POL}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|POR}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|SCO}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|SOV}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|ESP}}&nbsp;\n* {{fb|FRG}}&nbsp;\n\n{{col-4}}\n[[File:1986 world cup qualification.png|thumb|upright=1.5|{{legend|#000cff|Countries qualified for World Cup}} {{legend|#ffb400|Country did not qualify}} {{legend|black|Countries that did not enter World Cup}} {{legend|#ababab|Country not a FIFA member}}]]\n{{col end}}\n\n== Venues ==\nEleven cities hosted the tournament. The Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, the largest stadium used for the tournament, hosted nine matches (including the final), more than any other stadium used. Mexico City hosted 13 total matches; the Olimpico Universitario Stadium hosted four matches (if the Mexico City suburban town Nezahualcoyotl's 3 matches are included, this brings the total up to 16 matches; nearly a third of all matches in this tournament). Guadalajara, Mexico's second largest city hosted 10 total matches (the Jalisco Stadium hosted seven matches, the Tres de Marzo Stadium in Zapopan hosted three), Monterrey hosted 8 matches (The Tecnologico Stadium and the Universitario Stadium in San Nicolas de los Garza hosted four matches each), and the Cuauht\u00e9moc Stadium in [[Puebla]] hosted 5 matches.\n\nThe hot, humid and rainy summer weather in Mexico varied from humid desert locations like Monterrey to tropical locations such as Guadalajara; but perhaps the greatest hardship the players had to contend with was the high altitude of the Mexican locations. With the exception of the 93-104&nbsp;\u00b0F (34-40&nbsp;\u00b0C) temperatures of Monterrey (still 2,000 feet above sea level), all of the stadia were located in cities that varied anywhere from Guadalajara being {{convert|5138|ft}} above sea level to Toluca being {{convert|8730|ft}} above sea level, making conditions very difficult for the players running around in these stadia- but the higher the cities, the less intense the heat. Mexico City, the location of the final match and the location where the most matches were played was {{convert|7380|ft}} above sea level and the weather there was not as hot as in other cities used in this World Cup.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Mexico City]]\n! [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]]\n! [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n![[San Nicol\u00e1s de los Garza]]<br>{{small|(Monterrey area)}}\n|-\n| [[Estadio Azteca]]\n| [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]]\n| [[Estadio Jalisco]]\n| [[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]]\n|[[Estadio Universitario (UANL)|Estadio Universitario]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''114,600'''\n| Capacity: '''72,212'''\n| Capacity: '''66,193'''\n| Capacity: '''46,416'''\n|Capacity: '''43,780'''\n|-\n|[[File:Estadio Azteca, 2015.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio olimpico universitario unam.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio jalisco.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc.jpeg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Universitario Concachampions.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|-\n![[Santiago de Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]]\n! colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"4\" |{{Location map+|Mexico|places={{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.302911 |long=-99.150442 |label=<small>[[Mexico City]]</small>|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.681667 |long=-103.462778 |label=<small>[[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]]</small>|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=25.722806 |long=-100.312056 |label=<small>[[Monterrey]]</small> |position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.5875 |long=-100.392778 |label=<small>[[Quer\u00e9taro, Quer\u00e9taro|Quer\u00e9taro]]</small>|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.0778 |long=-98.1644 |label=<small>[[Puebla]]</small>|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=19.2873 |long=-99.6667 |label=<small>[[Toluca]]</small>|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=20.6841 |long=-101.3563 |label=<small>[[Irapuato]]</small>|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Mexico |lat=21.1155 |long=-101.6577 |label=<small>[[Le\u00f3n]]</small>|position=top}}|float=center|width=650|caption=}}\n![[Ciudad Nezahualc\u00f3yotl|Nezahualcoyotl]]<br>{{small|(Mexico City area)}}\n|-\n|[[Estadio La Corregidora]]\n|[[Estadio Neza 86]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''38,576'''\n|Capacity: '''34,536'''\n|-\n|[[File:Estadio la Corregidora.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Neza 86.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|-\n![[Monterrey]]\n![[Toluca]]\n![[Irapuato]]\n![[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]\n![[Zapopan, Jalisco|Zapopan]]<br>{{small|(Guadalajara area)}}\n|-\n|[[Estadio Tecnol\u00f3gico]]\n|[[Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez]]\n|[[Estadio Sergio Le\u00f3n Ch\u00e1vez]]\n|[[Estadio Nou Camp]]\n|[[Estadio Tres de Marzo]]\n|-\n| Capacity: '''33,805'''\n| Capacity: '''32,612'''\n| Capacity: '''31,336'''\n| Capacity: '''30,531'''\n|Capacity: '''30,015'''\n|-\n|[[File:EstadioTecnologico.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Nemesio diez.JPG|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio SLC Irapuato.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Estadio Le\u00f3n (Nou Camp), Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato, M\u00e9xico -Imagen Actual- 2013-12-10 14-09.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|[[File:Tecos stadium.jpg|alt=|220x220px]]\n|}\n\nAll of these venues except Monterrey were located in central Mexico, as this tournament was organized with the then-standard way of keeping teams playing in locations in close proximity to each other. Group A only played at the Olimpico and in Puebla (except for the Bulgaria-Italy opening tournament match, which was played in the Azteca), Group B only played at the Azteca and in Toluca (hosts Mexico were part of this group; they played all their group stage matches at the Azteca), Group C played in Le\u00f3n and Irapuato, Group D only played in Guadalajara (including the Guadalajara area town of Zapopan; the last match of this group was played in Monterrey), Group E exclusively played in Quer\u00e9taro and Nezahualc\u00f3yotl, and Group F played in the northern city of Monterrey (including the Monterrey area town of San Nicolas de los Garza; the last match of this group was played in Guadalajara). All of the venues listed hosted knockout round matches except the ones in Nezahualcoyotl, Irapuato, Zapopan, Toluca and the Estadio Tecnologico in Monterrey.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Stadium\n!Matches\n!Teams hosted in the first round\n|-\n|Estadio Azteca||Opening match, Group B,<br /> R2, QF, SF, Final||'''{{fb|MEX}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario||Group A, R2||{{fb|ARG}}, {{fb|BUL|1971}}, {{fb|KOR|1984}}\n|-\n|Estadio Jalisco||Group D, R2, QF, SF||'''{{fb|BRA|1968}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc||Group A, R2, QF,<br />Third-place match||'''{{fb|ITA}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Universitario||Group F, R2, QF||'''{{fb|POL}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio La Corregidora||Group E, R2||'''{{fb|FRG}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Tecnol\u00f3gico||Group F||{{fb|ENG}}, {{fb|POR}}*, {{fb|MAR}}*\n|-\n|Estadio Nou Camp||Group C, R2||'''{{fb|FRA}}'''\n|-\n|Estadio Neza 86||Group E||{{fb|URU}}, {{fb|DEN}}, {{fb|SCO}}\n|-\n|Estadio Sergio Le\u00f3n Ch\u00e1vez||Group C||{{fb|URS}}, {{fb|HPR}}, {{fb|CAN}}\n|-\n|Estadio Tres de Marzo||Group D||{{fb|ESP}}*, {{fb|NIR}}, {{fb|ALG}}*\n|-\n|Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez||Group B||{{fb|BEL}}, {{fb|PAR|1954}}, {{fb|IRQ|1963}}\n|}\n* ''Morocco and Portugal played in Guadalajara while Spain and Algeria played in Monterrey.''\n\n== Match officials ==\n{{col-begin-small}}\n{{col-3}}\n;Africa\n* {{fbaicon|TUN|1959}} [[Ali Bin Nasser]]\n* {{fbaicon|MRI}} [[Edwin Picon-Ackong]]\n* {{fbaicon|MLI}} [[Idrissa Traor\u00e9 (referee)|Idrissa Traor\u00e9]]\n\n;Asia\n* {{fbaicon|KSA}} [[Fallaj Al-Shanar]]\n* {{fbaicon|SYR}} [[Jamal Al Sharif]]\n* {{fbaicon|JPN|1870}} [[Shizuo Takada]]\n\n;Europe\n* {{fbaicon|ITA}} [[Luigi Agnolin]]\n* {{fbaicon|AUT}} [[Horst Brummeier]]\n* {{fbaicon|URS}} [[Valeri Butenko]]\n* {{fbaicon|TCH}} [[Vojtech Christov]]\n* {{fbaicon|ENG}} [[George Courtney]]\n{{col-3}}\n* {{fbaicon|SUI}} [[Andr\u00e9 Daina]]\n* {{fbaicon|BUL|1971}} [[Bogdan Dotchev]]\n* {{fbaicon|SWE}} [[Erik Fredriksson]]\n* {{fbaicon|ROU|1965}} [[Ioan Igna]]\n* {{fbaicon|NED}} [[Jan Keizer (referee)|Jan Keizer]]\n* {{fbaicon|GDR}} [[Siegfried Kirschen]]\n* {{fbaicon|HPR}} [[Lajos N\u00e9meth]]\n* {{fbaicon|YUG}} [[Zoran Petrovi\u0107 (referee)|Zoran Petrovi\u0107]]\n* {{fbaicon|BEL}} [[Alexis Ponnet]]\n* {{fbaicon|FRA}} [[Jo\u00ebl Quiniou]]\n* {{fbaicon|FRG}} [[Volker Roth]]\n* {{fbaicon|ESP}} [[Victoriano S\u00e1nchez Arminio]]\n* {{fbaicon|POR}} [[Carlos Silva Valente]]\n* {{fbaicon|NIR}} [[Alan Snoddy]]\n{{col-3}}\n;North and Central America\n* {{fbaicon|GUA}} [[R\u00f3mulo M\u00e9ndez]]\n* {{fbaicon|MEX}} [[Antonio M\u00e1rquez Ram\u00edrez]]\n* {{fbaicon|USA}} [[David Socha]]\n* {{fbaicon|CRC}} [[Berny Ulloa Morera]]\n\n;Oceania\n* {{fbaicon|AUS}} [[Chris Bambridge]]\n\n;South America\n* {{fbaicon|BRA|1968}} [[Romualdo Arppi Filho]]\n* {{fbaicon|COL}} [[Jes\u00fas D\u00edaz (football referee)|Jes\u00fas D\u00edaz]]\n* {{fbaicon|ARG}} [[Carlos Esp\u00f3sito]]\n* {{fbaicon|PAR|1954}} [[Gabriel Gonz\u00e1lez (referee)|Gabriel Gonz\u00e1lez Roa]]\n* {{fbaicon|URU}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Mart\u00ednez Baz\u00e1n]]\n* {{fbaicon|CHI}} [[Hern\u00e1n Silva]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Squads ==\nFor a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see ''[[1986 FIFA World Cup squads]]''.\n\n== Seeding ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=98%\n|-\n!width=25%| Pot 1\n!width=25%| Pot 2\n!width=25%| Pot 3\n!width=25%| Pot 4\n|-\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|MEX}} (hosts)\n* {{fb|ITA}} (1982 winners)\n* {{nowrap|{{fb|FRG}} (1982 runners-up)}}\n* {{fb|POL}} (1982 third place)\n* {{fb|FRA}} (1982 fourth place)\n* {{fb|BRA|1968}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|ENG}}\n* {{fb|URS}}\n* {{fb|ARG}}\n* {{fb|ESP}}\n* {{fb|PAR|1954}}\n* {{fb|URU}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|ALG}}\n* {{fb|CAN}}\n* {{fb|DEN}}\n* {{fb|IRQ|1963}}\n* {{fb|MAR}}\n* {{fb|KOR|1984}}\n| valign=\"top\"|\n* {{fb|BEL}}\n* {{fb|BUL|1971}}\n* {{fb|HPR}}\n* {{fb|NIR}}\n* {{fb|POR}}\n* {{fb|SCO}}\n|}\n\n== Summary ==\n[[File:1986 world cup.png|thumb|upright=1.9|Map of results {{col-start}} {{col-4}} {{legend|#2b42a3|Champion}} {{legend|#34c0be|Runner-up}}{{col-4}}  {{legend|#269c5a|Third place}} {{legend|#81c846|Fourth place}} {{col-4}} {{legend|#e4e454|Quarter-finals}} {{legend|#f4d4ac|Round of 16}} {{col-4}}{{legend|#b94954|Group stage}}{{col-end}}]]\n\n=== First round ===\n[[File:026549-018 FUTBOLEROS FESTEJANDO EN EL Z\u00d3CALO JUNIO 7 1986 (45398933914).jpg|thumb|Celebrations of Mexican fans at Zocalo main square, June 7, 1986.]]\nThe first round of the finals began in Group A, where [[Italy national football team|Italy]] were held 1\u20131 by [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]]. Meanwhile, [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] beat [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] 3\u20131, with [[Diego Maradona]] playing a major part. [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] drew 1\u20131, Maradona and [[Alessandro Altobelli]] scoring. South Korea and Bulgaria also drew 1\u20131 in a downpour. The final set of matches saw Argentina beating Bulgaria 2\u20130, and Italy narrowly defeating South Korea 3\u20132.\n\nIn Group B [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] beat [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] 2\u20131, and despite being held 1\u20131 by [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]], they won the group after a further win over [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]], 1\u20130. Paraguay and Belgium also progressed after both beating Iraq and drawing with each other.\n\nGroup C pitted a strong [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]]-dominated [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] side against the reigning European champions [[France national football team|France]]. They drew with each other 1\u20131, with a goal scored by [[Vasyl Rats]]. France beat [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] 1\u20130 and finished in 2nd place in the group after beating [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], 3\u20130. Hungary had earlier lost 6\u20130 against the Soviet Union, which won the group due to goal difference.\n\nGroup D saw [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] start against [[Spain national football team|Spain]], winning 1\u20130 after the referee failed to validate a legal goal scored by [[M\u00edchel (footballer, born 1963)|M\u00edchel]]. [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] began their campaign with a draw against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]. Northern Ireland were then narrowly beaten by Spain before losing to Brazil 3\u20130 in their final match. This match saw a goal from [[Josimar]] on his debut and was also the final time [[Pat Jennings]] played for [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]]. Spain qualified along with Brazil after defeating Algeria 3\u20130.\n\n[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] stormed through Group E, dubbed the [[group of death]], with a 100 per cent record. They beat [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] 1\u20130 in their first game, then hammered [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 6\u20131, with [[Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen]] hitting a hat-trick. Denmark beat one of the favourites to win the tournament, [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Jesper Olsen]] penalty and a goal from [[John Eriksen]]. After losing to Denmark, Scotland took the lead against West Germany thanks to a [[Gordon Strachan]] goal, but the West Germans fought back to win 2\u20131. After a violent 0\u20130 draw against Uruguay, the Scots were eliminated from the tournament. During that game [[Jos\u00e9 Batista]] of Uruguay was [[misconduct (football)|sent off]] after less than one minute of play for a foul on Strachan, a [[FIFA World Cup records|World Cup record]] that still stands. West Germany went through to the second round despite a loss against Denmark.\n\n[[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] topped Group F after holding both [[Poland national football team|Poland]] and [[England national football team|England]] to goalless draws, and beating [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] 3\u20131. By doing so, they became the first African team, and only the second nation from outside Europe and the Americas (after North Korea in 1966), to reach the second round. England lost 1\u20130 to Portugal, followed by a 0\u20130 draw against Morocco in which they lost captain [[Bryan Robson]] to injury (for the remainder of the tournament) and vice-captain [[Ray Wilkins]] to a red card (he was never to be selected for England again, even after having served his obligatory one-match ban). In their last first-round game, with the captaincy taken over by [[Peter Shilton]] in goal, a first-half [[Gary Lineker]] hat-trick helped the reshaped side beat Poland 3\u20130 \u2013 although losing yet another player to a ban for the next round, Terry Fenwick receiving his second booking of the tournament. Poland had previously beaten Portugal, and in the end the Portuguese were the only team from Group F to be eliminated in the first round. Portugal, making their first appearance in 20 years, went on strike (in the [[Saltillo Affair]]) during the competition. Players refused to train between their first and second games (against England and Poland) and were eliminated after a loss to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in the final group match.\n\n=== Second round and quarter-finals ===\nBelgium beat the Soviet Union 4\u20133, despite a hat-trick by the Soviets' [[Igor Belanov]]. The game was level at 2\u20132 after 90 minutes, and in extra time [[Stephane Demol]] and [[Nico Claesen]] put Belgium 4\u20132 up. Belanov scored from the penalty spot with nine minutes remaining, but neither he nor any of his teammates could find a fourth goal for the Soviet Union. At the [[Estadio Olimpico Universitario|Olympic University Stadium]] in Mexico City, the European champions France ended Italy's reign as world champions with a 2\u20130 victory thanks to goals from [[Michel Platini]] and [[Yannick Stopyra]]. In the rematch of the [[1930 FIFA World Cup Final]], Argentina just edged out South American champions Uruguay in Puebla thanks to a 42nd-minute strike from [[Pedro Pasculli]]. The all-South American affair had a Diego Maradona's goal disallowed.\n\nIn Quer\u00e9taro, Denmark were eliminated as they went from a 1\u20130 lead to a 5\u20131 battering against Spain; key player [[Frank Arnesen]] was suspended for the game after being sent off against West Germany in their last group match, for taking a swipe at German playmaker [[Lothar Matth\u00e4us]]. The Danes scored first, with a Jesper Olsen penalty, but they were then taken apart by a devastating performance from [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o|Butrague\u00f1o]] of Spain, who scored four of his team's five goals. At the [[Estadio Azteca|Azteca Stadium]] in Mexico City, England progressed to the quarter-finals comfortably when they saw off Paraguay 3\u20130, while Brazil brushed aside Poland 4\u20130. West Germany had a much harder time getting past Morocco, for whom goalkeeper [[Badou Zaki]] had an outstanding game. Morocco held out until the 87th minute, when Lothar Matth\u00e4us scored the only goal of the match with a free kick. Mexico won 2\u20130 against Bulgaria with an outstanding scissor-kick goal by [[Manuel Negrete Arias|Manuel Negrete]] which is honored by a remembrance plaque at [[Estadio Azteca|the Azteca]].\n\nIn the quarter-finals, France faced three-time world champion Brazil in Guadalajara. Brazil were well on top in the early stages, and Careca put them one up after 18 minutes. Five minutes before half-time, France drew level when Michel Platini scored his 41st goal after converting a cross from [[Dominique Rocheteau]]. Brazil had a chance to regain the lead in the second half when Branco was fouled by French keeper [[Jo\u00ebl Bats]] in the penalty area. [[Zico]] got up to take the kick, but Bats saved Zico's penalty.\n\nThe match went to extra time, and France finished slightly the stronger of the two sides. No more goals were scored, and so it was time for a penalty shoot-out. Socrates, who had earlier missed an open goal and headed an easy chance straight into the French keeper's arms, failed with the first kick for Brazil. The next six penalties were all converted, and then Platini fired over the bar. Brazil were back on level terms \u2013 but not for long. [[J\u00falio C\u00e9sar da Silva|Julio Cesar]] struck the post with his penalty, and [[Luis Fern\u00e1ndez]] then scored to put France through 4\u20133 on penalties.\n\nTwo other quarter-finals were also decided on penalties. [[Jan Ceulemans]] put Belgium ahead against Spain in the 35th minute, but Spanish substitute Se\u00f1or equalised with five minutes to go. No more goals were scored in extra time, and Belgium won the shoot-out 5\u20134. West Germany and Mexico drew 0\u20130 after extra time, and the West Germans eliminated the hosts 4\u20131 on penalties. As a curiosity, the German goalkeeper [[Harald Schumacher]] jumped to the right in the three Mexican penalties (stopping two of them).\n\nThe quarter-final between Argentina and England at the Azteca featured two very different goals in the second half by Diego Maradona: the first was scored illegally, as he punched the ball into the goal past England goalkeeper [[Peter Shilton]]. The referee did not see the handball and the goal was given as valid. After the game, Maradona claimed the goal was scored \"A bit with the head of Maradona and another bit with the hand of God\"; it became known as the \"[[The hand of God|Hand of God]]\" goal. For his second goal, voted \"[[Goal of the Century]]\" in 2002 on the FIFA website, Maradona dribbled half the length of the field past five English players before scoring. With 20 minutes to go, the introduction of John Barnes as a substitute changed the tide of play in England's favour, as he pinged cross after cross into the Argentine penalty area: with 9 minutes to go, Lineker got on the end of one and scored, then almost repeated the dose six minutes later but was just unable to reach the ball thanks to a timely block by Olarticoechea: 2\u20131 to Argentina was the final score. In Argentina, the game was seen as revenge for the [[Falklands War]].<ref>El Diego \u2013 Diego Maradona, Page 127, {{ISBN|0-224-07190-4}}</ref>\n\n=== Semi-finals, third-place match, and final ===\nIn the first semi-final match, [[Andreas Brehme]] put West Germany 1\u20130 ahead against France in the ninth minute in Guadalajara, but the outcome remained in doubt until two minutes from time when [[Rudi V\u00f6ller]] made it 2\u20130, and West Germany were in the final for the second World Cup in succession. In the second semi-final match, Maradona struck twice in the second half as Argentina beat Belgium 2\u20130 at the Azteca. France went on to defeat Belgium in the third-place match, 4\u20132.\n\nSo it was to be the South American Argentina vs the European West Germany at the final at the Azteca, the second time this massive stadium would host a World Cup Final ([[1970 FIFA World Cup Final|the first]] in 1970). [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Brown|Jose Brown]] put Argentina one up midway through the first half of the final, and when [[Jorge Valdano]] scored a second for the South Americans in the 55th minute, Argentina looked to be strolling to victory. West Germany then staged a spirited comeback. [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]] pulled one back in the 74th minute, and six minutes later Rudi V\u00f6ller hit the equaliser. With seven minutes remaining, a pass from Maradona gave [[Jorge Burruchaga]] the chance to score the winner for Argentina. Eight years on from their [[1978 FIFA World Cup|home triumph]], Argentina regained the world title and 30 million people in Argentina celebrated in the streets after the final victory. Maradona was the Golden Ball winner as the best player of the tournament, while Gary Lineker of England won the Golden Boot as the leading scorer of the World Cup with six goals.\n\n== Results ==\n''All times are [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] ([[UTC\u221206:00|UTC\u22126]])''\n\n=== Group stage ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colours in group tables\n|-\n|bgcolor=#ccffcc style=\"width: 20px;\"|\n|align=left|Group winners, runners-up, and [[#Ranking of third-placed teams|best four third-placed teams]] advance to the [[#Round of 16|Round of 16]]\n|}\n\n==== Group A ====\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup Group A}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup group tables|Group A}}\nSouth Korea made their first appearance since 1954. They managed to score their first goal (against Argentina) and their first draw (against Bulgaria).\n{| style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|31 May 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|BUL|1971}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Bulgaria vs Italy|1\u20131]]||{{fb|ITA}}||[[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|2 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ARG}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Argentina vs South Korea|3\u20131]]||{{fb|KOR|1984}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|5 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ITA}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Italy vs Argentina|1\u20131]]||{{fb|ARG}}||[[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]], [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|KOR|1984}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#South Korea vs Bulgaria|1\u20131]]||{{fb|BUL|1971}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|10 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|KOR|1984}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#South Korea vs Italy|2\u20133]]||{{fb|ITA}}||[[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]], [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|ARG}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group A#Argentina vs Bulgaria|2\u20130]]||{{fb|BUL|1971}}||[[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], [[Mexico City]]\n|}\n\n==== Group B ====\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup Group B}}\n[[File:Cruz vs cabanas.jpg|thumb|right|[[Francisco Javier Cruz|Cruz]] and [[Roberto Caba\u00f1as|Caba\u00f1as]] going for the ball in Mexico v Paraguay]]\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup group tables|Group B}}\n{| style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|3 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|BEL}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Belgium vs Mexico|1\u20132]]||{{fb|MEX}}||[[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|4 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|PAR|1954}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Paraguay vs Iraq|1\u20130]]||{{fb|IRQ|1963}}||[[Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez]], [[Toluca]]\n|-\n|7 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|MEX}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Mexico vs Paraguay|1\u20131]]||{{fb|PAR|1954}}||[[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]]\n|-\n|8 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|IRQ|1963}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Iraq vs Belgium|1\u20132]]||{{fb|BEL}}||[[Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez]], [[Toluca]]\n|-\n|11 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|PAR|1954}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Paraguay vs Belgium|2\u20132]]||{{fb|BEL}}||[[Estadio Nemesio D\u00edez]], [[Toluca]]\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|IRQ|1963}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group B#Iraq vs Mexico|0\u20131]]||{{fb|MEX}}||[[Estadio Azteca]], [[Mexico City]]\n|}\n\n==== Group C ====\n{{Main|1986 FIFA World Cup Group C}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup group tables|Group C}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|1 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|CAN}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C#Canada vs France|0\u20131]]||{{fb|FRA}}||[[Estadio Nou Camp]], [[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]\n|-\n|2 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|URS}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C#Soviet Union vs Hungary|6\u20130]]||{{fb|HPR}}||[[Estadio Sergio Le\u00f3n Chavez]], [[Irapuato]]\n|-\n|5 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|FRA}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C#France vs Soviet Union|1\u20131]]||{{fb|URS}}||[[Estadio Nou Camp]], [[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]\n|-\n|6 June 1986\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fb-rt|HPR}}||align=center|[[1986 FIFA World Cup Group C#Hungary vs Canada|2\u201